38   
39   INTRODUCTION
40   W-in.1. A theoretical foundation such as the text provides is necessary as a framework 
41   to make the exercises in this workbook meaningful. 2 Yet it is doing the exercises that 
42   will make the goal of the course possible. 3 An untrained mind can accomplish nothing. 4 It
43   is the purpose of this workbook to train your mind to think along the lines the text 
44   sets forth.
45   W-in.2. The exercises are very simple. 2 They do not require a great deal of time, and 
46   it does not matter where you do them. 3 They need no preparation. 4 The training period 
47   is one year. 5 The exercises are numbered from 1 to 365. 6 Do not undertake to do more 
48   than one set of exercises a day.
49   W-in.3. The workbook is divided into two main sections, the first dealing with the 
50   undoing of the way you see now, and the second with the acquisition of true perception. 2 With
0407
 1   the exception of the review periods, each day's exercises are planned around one 
 2   central idea, which is stated first. 3 This is followed by a description of the specific 
 3   procedures by which the idea for the day is to be applied.
 4   W-in.4. The purpose of the workbook is to train your mind in a systematic way to a 
 5   different perception of everyone and everything in the world. 2 The exercises are planned to 
 6   help you generalize the lessons, so that you will understand that each of them is equally 
 7   applicable to everyone and everything you see.
 8   W-in.5. Transfer of training in true perception does not proceed as does transfer of 
 9   the training of the world. 2 If true perception has been achieved in connection with any 
10   person, situation or event, total transfer to everyone and everything is certain. 3 On the 
11   other hand, one exception held apart from true perception makes its accomplishments anywhere
12   impossible.
13   W-in.6. The only general rules to be observed throughout, then, are: First, that the 
14   exercises be practiced with great specificity, as will be indicated. 2 This will help you to 
15   generalize the ideas involved to every situation in which you find yourself, and to everyone and 
16   everything in it. 3 Second, be sure that you do not decide for yourself that there are some 
17   people, situations or things to which the ideas are inapplicable. 4 This will interfere with 
18   transfer of training. 5 The very nature of true perception is that it has no limits. 6 It is 
19   the opposite of the way you see now.
20   W-in.7. The overall aim of the exercises is to increase your ability to extend the 
21   ideas you will be practicing to include everything. 2 This will require no effort on your 
22   part. 3 The exercises themselves meet the conditions necessary for this kind of transfer.
23   W-in.8. Some of the ideas the workbook presents you will find hard to believe, and 
24   others may seem to be quite startling. 2 This does not matter. 3 You are merely asked to 
25   apply the ideas as you are directed to do. 4 You are not asked to judge them at all. 5 You 
26   are asked only to use them. 6 It is their use that will give them meaning to you, and will
27   show you that they are true.
28   W-in.9. Remember only this; you need not believe the ideas, you need not accept them, 
29   and you need not even welcome them. 2 Some of them you may actively resist. 3 None of this
30   will matter, or decrease their efficacy. 4 But do not allow yourself to make exceptions
31   in applying the ideas the workbook contains, and whatever your reactions to the ideas 
32   may be, use them. 5 Nothing more than that is required.
33   
34   
35   
36   PART I
37   
38   LESSON 1.
39   
40   Nothing I see in this room [on this street, 
41   from this window, in this place] means anything.
42   W-pI.1.1. Now look slowly around you, and practice applying this idea very specifically
43   to whatever you see: 
44   
45   2 This table does not mean anything. 
46   3 This chair does not mean anything. 
47   4 This hand does not mean anything. 
48   5 This foot does not mean anything. 
49   6 This pen does not mean anything.
50   
0408
 1   W-pI.1.2. Then look farther away from your immediate area, and apply the idea to a 
 2   wider range: 
 3   
 4   2 That door does not mean anything. 
 5   3 That body does not mean anything. 
 6   4 That lamp does not mean anything. 
 7   5 That sign does not mean anything. 
 8   6 That shadow does not mean anything.
 9   
10   W-pI.1.3. Notice that these statements are not arranged in any order, and make no 
11   allowance for differences in the kinds of things to which they are applied. 2 That is the 
12   purpose of the exercise. 3 The statement should merely be applied to anything you see. 4 As 
13   you practice the idea for the day, use it totally indiscriminately. 5 Do not attempt to 
14   apply it to everything you see, for these exercises should not become ritualistic. 6 Only be
15   sure that nothing you see is specifically excluded. 7 One thing is like another as far 
16   as the application of the idea is concerned.
17   W-pI.1.4. Each of the first three lessons should not be done more than twice a day each,
18    preferably morning and evening. 2 Nor should they be attempted for more than a minute 
19   or so, unless that entails a sense of hurry. 3 A comfortable sense of leisure is 
20   essential.
21   
22   
23   
24   LESSON 2.
25   
26   I have given everything I see in this room 
27   [on this street, from this window, in this place] 
28   all the meaning that it has for me.
29   W-pI.2.1. The exercises with this idea are the same as those for the first one. 2 Begin
30   with the things that are near you, and apply the idea to whatever your glance rests on.
31   3 Then increase the range outward. 4 Turn your head so that you include whatever is on 
32   either side. 5 If possible, turn around and apply the idea to what was behind you. 6 Remain 
33   as indiscriminate as possible in selecting subjects for its application, do not 
34   concentrate on anything in particular, and do not attempt to include everything you see in a given
35   area, or you will introduce strain.
36   W-pI.2.2. Merely glance easily and fairly quickly around you, trying to avoid selection
37   by size, brightness, color, material, or relative importance to you. 2 Take the 
38   subjects simply as you see them. 3 Try to apply the exercise with equal ease to a body or a 
39   button, a fly or a floor, an arm or an apple. 4 The sole criterion for applying the idea to 
40   anything is merely that your eyes have lighted on it. 5 Make no attempt to include anything 
41   particular, but be sure that nothing is specifically excluded.
42   
43   
44   
45   LESSON 3.
46   
47   I do not understand anything I see in this room 
48   [on this street, from this window, in this place].
49   W-pI.3.1. Apply this idea in the same way as the previous ones, without making 
50   distinctions of any kind. 2 Whatever you see becomes a proper subject for applying the idea. 3 Be 
0409
 1   sure that you do not question the suitability of anything for application of the idea. 4 
 2   These are not exercises in judgment. 5 Anything is suitable if you see it. 6 Some of the 
 3   things you see may have emotionally charged meaning for you. 7 Try to lay such feelings aside,
 4    and merely use these things exactly as you would anything else.
 5   W-pI.3.2. The point of the exercises is to help you clear your mind of all past 
 6   associations, to see things exactly as they appear to you now, and to realize how little you really
 7   understand about them. 2 It is therefore essential that you keep a perfectly open mind,
 8   unhampered by judgment, in selecting the things to which the idea for the day is to be 
 9   applied. 3 For this purpose one thing is like another; equally suitable and therefore equally 
10   useful.
11   
12   
13   
14   LESSON 4.
15   
16   These thoughts do not mean anything. They are like
17    the things I see in this room [on this street, 
18   from this window, in this place].
19   W-pI.4.1. Unlike the preceding ones, these exercises do not begin with the idea for the
20   day. 2 In these practice periods, begin with noting the thoughts that are crossing your
21   mind for about a minute. 3 Then apply the idea to them. 4 If you are already aware of 
22   unhappy thoughts, use them as subjects for the idea. 5 Do not, however, select only the 
23   thoughts you think are "bad." 6 You will find, if you train yourself to look at your thoughts, 
24   that they represent such a mixture that, in a sense, none of them can be called "good" or "
25   bad." 7 This is why they do not mean anything.
26   W-pI.4.2. In selecting the subjects for the application of today's idea, the usual 
27   specificity is required. 2 Do not be afraid to use "good" thoughts as well as "bad." 3 None of 
28   them represents your real thoughts, which are being covered up by them. 4 The "good" ones 
29   are but shadows of what lies beyond, and shadows make sight difficult. 5 The "bad" ones 
30   are blocks to sight, and make seeing impossible. 6 You do not want either.
31   W-pI.4.3. This is a major exercise, and will be repeated from time to time in somewhat 
32   different form. 2 The aim here is to train you in the first steps toward the goal of separating 
33   the meaningless from the meaningful. 3 It is a first attempt in the long-range purpose of 
34   learning to see the meaningless as outside you, and the meaningful within. 4 It is also the 
35   beginning of training your mind to recognize what is the same and what is different.
36   W-pI.4.4. In using your thoughts for application of the idea for today, identify each 
37   thought by the central figure or event it contains; for example: 
38   
39   2 This thought about___does not mean anything. 
40   3 It is like the things I see in this room [on this street, and so on].
41   
42   W-pI.4.5. You can also use the idea for a particular thought that you recognize as 
43   harmful. 2 This practice is useful, but is not a substitute for the more random procedures to 
44   be followed for the exercises. 3 Do not, however, examine your mind for more than a 
45   minute or so. 4 You are too inexperienced as yet to avoid a tendency to become pointlessly 
46   preoccupied.
47   W-pI.4.6. Further, since these exercises are the first of their kind, you may find the 
48   suspension of judgment in connection with thoughts particularly difficult. 2 Do not repeat these 
49   exercises more than three or four times during the day. 3 We will return to them later.
50   
0410
 1   
 2   
 3   LESSON 5.
 4   
 5   I am never upset for the reason I think.
 6   W-pI.5.1. This idea, like the preceding one, can be used with any person, situation or 
 7   event you think is causing you pain. 2 Apply it specifically to whatever you believe is the 
 8   cause of your upset, using the description of the feeling in whatever term seems accurate to
 9   you. 3 The upset may seem to be fear, worry, depression, anxiety, anger, hatred, 
10   jealousy or any number of forms, all of which will be perceived as different. 4 This is not 
11   true. 5 However, until you learn that form does not matter, each form becomes a proper 
12   subject for the exercises for the day. 6 Applying the same idea to each of them separately is 
13   the first step in ultimately recognizing they are all the same.
14   W-pI.5.2. When using the idea for today for a specific perceived cause of an upset in 
15   any form, use both the name of the form in which you see the upset, and the cause which 
16   you ascribe to it. 2 For example: 
17   
18   3 I am not angry at___for the reason I think. 
19   4 I am not afraid of___for the reason I think.
20   
21   W-pI.5.3. But again, this should not be substituted for practice periods in which you 
22   first search your mind for "sources" of upset in which you believe, and forms of upset which
23   you think result.
24   W-pI.5.4. In these exercises, more than in the preceding ones, you may find it hard to 
25   be indiscriminate, and to avoid giving greater weight to some subjects than to others. 2 
26   It might help to precede the exercises with the statement: 
27   
28   3 There are no small upsets. 4 They are all equally disturbing to my peace of mind.
29   
30   W-pI.5.5. Then examine your mind for whatever is distressing you, regardless of how 
31   much or how little you think it is doing so.
32   W-pI.5.6. You may also find yourself less willing to apply today's idea to some 
33   perceived sources of upset than to others. 2 If this occurs, think first of this: 
34   
35   3 I cannot keep this form of upset and let the others go. 4 For the purposes of these 
36   exercises, then, I will regard them all as the same.
37   
38   W-pI.5.7. Then search your mind for no more than a minute or so, and try to identify a 
39   number of different forms of upset that are disturbing you, regardless of the relative 
40   importance you may give them. 2 Apply the idea for today to each of them, using the name of both 
41   the source of the upset as you perceive it, and of the feeling as you experience it. 3 
42   Further examples are: 
43   
44   4 I am not worried about___for the reason I think. 
45   5 I am not depressed about___for the reason I think. 
46   
47   6 Three or four times during the day is enough.
48   
49   
50   
0411
 1   LESSON 6.
 2   
 3   I am upset because I see something that is not there.
 4   W-pI.6.1. The exercises with this idea are very similar to the preceding ones. 2 Again,
 5   it is necessary to name both the form of upset (anger, fear, worry, depression and so 
 6   on) and the perceived source very specifically for any application of the idea. 3 For 
 7   example: 
 8   
 9   4 I am angry at___because I see something that is not there. 
10   5 I am worried about___because I see something that is not there.
11   
12   W-pI.6.2. Today's idea is useful for application to anything that seems to upset you, 
13   and can profitably be used throughout the day for that purpose. 2 However, the three or 
14   four practice periods which are required should be preceded by a minute or so of mind 
15   searching, as before, and the application of the idea to each upsetting thought uncovered in the
16   search.
17   W-pI.6.3. Again, if you resist applying the idea to some upsetting thoughts more than 
18   to others, remind yourself of the two cautions stated in the previous lesson: 
19   
20   2 There are no small upsets. 3 They are all equally disturbing to my peace of mind. 
21   
22   4 And: 
23   
24   5 I cannot keep this form of upset and let the others go. 6 For the purposes of these 
25   exercises, then, I will regard them all as the same.
26   
27   
28   
29   LESSON 7.
30   
31   I see only the past.
32   W-pI.7.1. This idea is particularly difficult to believe at first. 2 Yet it is the 
33   rationale for all of the preceding ones. 
34   3 It is the reason why nothing that you see means anything. 
35   4 It is the reason why you have given everything you see all the meaning that it has 
36   for you. 
37   5 It is the reason why you do not understand anything you see. 
38   6 It is the reason why your thoughts do not mean anything, and why they are like the 
39   things you see. 
40   7 It is the reason why you are never upset for the reason you think. 
41   8 It is the reason why you are upset because you see something that is not there.
42   W-pI.7.2. Old ideas about time are very difficult to change, because everything you 
43   believe is rooted in time, and depends on your not learning these new ideas about it. 2 Yet 
44   that is precisely why you need new ideas about time. 3 This first time idea is not really 
45   so strange as it may sound at first.
46   W-pI.7.3. Look at a cup, for example. 2 Do you see a cup, or are you merely reviewing 
47   your past experiences of picking up a cup, being thirsty, drinking from a cup, feeling the 
48   rim of a cup against your lips, having breakfast and so on? 3 Are not your aesthetic 
49   reactions to the cup, too, based on past experiences? 4 How else would you know whether or not 
50   this kind of cup will break if you drop it? 5 What do you know about this cup except what 
0412
 1   you learned in the past? 6 You would have no idea what this cup is, except for your past 
 2   learning. 7 Do you, then, really see it?
 3   W-pI.7.4. Look about you. 2 This is equally true of whatever you look at. 3 Acknowledge
 4   this by applying the idea for today indiscriminately to whatever catches your eye. 4 
 5   For example: 
 6   
 7   5 I see only the past in this pencil. 
 8   6 I see only the past in this shoe. 
 9   7 I see only the past in this hand. 
10   8 I see only the past in that body. 
11   9 I see only the past in that face.
12   
13   W-pI.7.5. Do not linger over any one thing in particular, but remember to omit nothing 
14   specifically. 2 Glance briefly at each subject, and then move on to the next. 3 Three or four 
15   practice periods, each to last a minute or so, will be enough.
16   
17   
18   
19   LESSON 8.
20   
21   My mind is preoccupied with past thoughts.
22   W-pI.8.1. This idea is, of course, the reason why you see only the past. 2 No one 
23   really sees anything. 3 He sees only his thoughts projected outward. 4 The mind's 
24   preoccupation with the past is the cause of the misconception about time from which your seeing 
25   suffers. 5 Your mind cannot grasp the present, which is the only time there is. 6 It therefore
26   cannot understand time, and cannot, in fact, understand anything.
27   W-pI.8.2. The one wholly true thought one can hold about the past is that it is not 
28   here. 2 To think about it at all is therefore to think about illusions. 3 Very few have 
29   realized what is actually entailed in picturing the past or in anticipating the future. 4 The 
30   mind is actually blank when it does this, because it is not really thinking about anything.
31   W-pI.8.3. The purpose of the exercises for today is to begin to train your mind to 
32   recognize when it is not really thinking at all. 2 While thoughtless ideas preoccupy your mind, 
33   the truth is blocked. 3 Recognizing that your mind has been merely blank, rather than 
34   believing that it is filled with real ideas, is the first step to opening the way to vision.
35   W-pI.8.4. The exercises for today should be done with eyes closed. 2 This is because 
36   you actually cannot see anything, and it is easier to recognize that no matter how vividly
37   you may picture a thought, you are not seeing anything. 3 With as little investment as 
38   possible, search your mind for the usual minute or so, merely noting the thoughts you find 
39   there. 4 Name each one by the central figure or theme it contains, and pass on to the next. 
40   5 Introduce the practice period by saying: 
41   
42   6 I seem to be thinking about ___.
43   
44   W-pI.8.5. Then name each of your thoughts specifically, for example: 
45   
46   2 I seem to be thinking about [name of a person], about [name of an object], about [
47   name of an emotion], 
48   
49   and so on, concluding at the end of the mind-searching period with: 
50   
0413
 1   3 But my mind is preoccupied with past thoughts.
 2   
 3   W-pI.8.6. This can be done four or five times during the day, unless you find it 
 4   irritates you. 2 If you find it trying, three or four times is sufficient. 3 You might find it 
 5   helpful, however, to include your irritation, or any emotion that the idea for today may 
 6   induce, in the mind searching itself.
 7   
 8   
 9   
10   LESSON 9.
11   
12   I see nothing as it is now.
13   W-pI.9.1. This idea obviously follows from the two preceding ones. 2 But while you may 
14   be able to accept it intellectually, it is unlikely that it will mean anything to you as 
15   yet. 3 However, understanding is not necessary at this point. 4 In fact, the recognition 
16   that you do not understand is a prerequisite for undoing your false ideas. 5 These 
17   exercises are concerned with practice, not with understanding. 6 You do not need to practice 
18   what you already understand. 7 It would indeed be circular to aim at understanding, and 
19   assume that you have it already.
20   W-pI.9.2. It is difficult for the untrained mind to believe that what it seems to 
21   picture is not there. 2 This idea can be quite disturbing, and may meet with active resistance
22   in any number of forms. 3 Yet that does not preclude applying it. 4 No more than that 
23   is required for these or any other exercises. 5 Each small step will clear a little of 
24   the darkness away, and understanding will finally come to lighten every corner of the mind
25   that has been cleared of the debris that darkens it.
26   W-pI.9.3. These exercises, for which three or four practice periods are sufficient, 
27   involve looking about you and applying the idea for the day to whatever you see, remembering 
28   the need for its indiscriminate application, and the essential rule of excluding nothing. 
29   2 For example: 
30   
31   3 I do not see this typewriter as it is now. 
32   4 I do not see this telephone as it is now. 
33   5 I do not see this arm as it is now.
34   
35   W-pI.9.4. Begin with things that are nearest you, and then extend the range outward: 
36   
37   2 I do not see that coat rack as it is now. 
38   3 I do not see that door as it is now. 
39   4 I do not see that face as it is now.
40   
41   W-pI.9.5. It is emphasized again that while complete inclusion should not be attempted,
42   specific exclusion must be avoided. 2 Be sure you are honest with yourself in making 
43   this distinction. 3 You may be tempted to obscure it.
44   
45   
46   
47   LESSON 10.
48   
49   My thoughts do not mean anything.
50   W-pI.10.1. This idea applies to all the thoughts of which you are aware, or become 
0414
 1   aware in the practice periods. 2 The reason the idea is applicable to all of them is that 
 2   they are not your real thoughts. 3 We have made this distinction before, and will do so 
 3   again. 4 You have no basis for comparison as yet. 5 When you do, you will have no doubt that
 4   what you once believed were your thoughts did not mean anything.
 5   W-pI.10.2. This is the second time we have used this kind of idea. 2 The form is only 
 6   slightly different. 3 This time the idea is introduced with "My thoughts" instead of "These 
 7   thoughts," and no link is made overtly with the things around you. 4 The emphasis is now on the
 8   lack of reality of what you think you think.
 9   W-pI.10.3. This aspect of the correction process began with the idea that the thoughts 
10   of which you are aware are meaningless, outside rather than within; and then stressed 
11   their past rather than their present status. 2 Now we are emphasizing that the presence of 
12   these "thoughts" means that you are not thinking. 3 This is merely another way of repeating 
13   our earlier statement that your mind is really a blank. 4 To recognize this is to 
14   recognize nothingness when you think you see it. 5 As such, it is the prerequisite for vision.
15   W-pI.10.4. Close your eyes for these exercises, and introduce them by repeating the 
16   idea for today quite slowly to yourself. 2 Then add: 
17   
18   3 This idea will help to release me from all that I now believe. 
19   
20   4 The exercises consist, as before, in searching your mind for all the thoughts that 
21   are available to you, without selection or judgment. 5 Try to avoid classification of any 
22   kind. 6 In fact, if you find it helpful to do so, you might imagine that you are watching 
23   an oddly assorted procession going by, which has little if any personal meaning to you. 7
24   As each one crosses your mind, say: 
25   
26   8 My thought about___does not mean anything. 
27   9 My thought about___does not mean anything.
28   
29   W-pI.10.5. Today's thought can obviously serve for any thought that distresses you at 
30   any time. 2 In addition, five practice periods are recommended, each involving no more 
31   than a minute or so of mind searching. 3 It is not recommended that this time period be 
32   extended, and it should be reduced to half a minute or less if you experience discomfort. 4 
33   Remember, however, to repeat the idea slowly before applying it specifically, and also to add: 
34   
35   5 This idea will help to release me from all that I now believe.
36   
37   
38   
39   LESSON 11.
40   
41   My meaningless thoughts are showing me a 
42   meaningless world.
43   W-pI.11.1. This is the first idea we have had that is related to a major phase of the 
44   correction process; the reversal of the thinking of the world. 2 It seems as if the world 
45   determines what you perceive. 3 Today's idea introduces the concept that your thoughts determine 
46   the world you see. 4 Be glad indeed to practice the idea in its initial form, for in this 
47   idea is your release made sure. 5 The key to forgiveness lies in it.
48   W-pI.11.2. The practice periods for today's idea are to be undertaken somewhat 
49   differently from the previous ones. 2 Begin with your eyes closed, and repeat the idea slowly to 
50   yourself. 3 Then open your eyes and look about, near and far, up and down,--anywhere. 4 During 
0415
 1   the minute or so to be spent in using the idea merely repeat it to yourself, being sure to
 2   do so without haste, and with no sense of urgency or effort.
 3   W-pI.11.3. To do these exercises for maximum benefit, the eyes should move from one 
 4   thing to another fairly rapidly, since they should not linger on anything in particular. 2 
 5   The words, however, should be used in an unhurried, even leisurely fashion. 3 The 
 6   introduction to this idea, in particular, should be practiced as casually as possible. 4 It 
 7   contains the foundation for the peace, relaxation and freedom from worry that we are trying to 
 8   achieve. 5 On concluding the exercises, close your eyes and repeat the idea once more slowly 
 9   to yourself.
10   W-pI.11.4. Three practice periods today will probably be sufficient. 2 However, if 
11   there is little or no uneasiness and an inclination to do more, as many as five may be 
12   undertaken. 3 More than this is not recommended.
13   
14   
15   
16   LESSON 12.
17   
18   I am upset because I see a meaningless world.
19   W-pI.12.1. The importance of this idea lies in the fact that it contains a correction 
20   for a major perceptual distortion. 2 You think that what upsets you is a frightening world,
21    or a sad world, or a violent world, or an insane world. 3 All these attributes are 
22   given it by you. 4 The world is meaningless in itself.
23   W-pI.12.2. These exercises are done with eyes open. 2 Look around you, this time quite 
24   slowly. 3 Try to pace yourself so that the slow shifting of your glance from one thing to 
25   another involves a fairly constant time interval. 4 Do not allow the time of the shift to 
26   become markedly longer or shorter, but try, instead, to keep a measured, even tempo 
27   throughout. 5 What you see does not matter. 6 You teach yourself this as you give whatever your 
28   glance rests on equal attention and equal time. 7 This is a beginning step in learning to 
29   give them all equal value.
30   W-pI.12.3. As you look about you, say to yourself: 
31   
32   2 I think I see a fearful world, a dangerous world, a hostile world, a sad world, a 
33   wicked world, a crazy world, 
34   
35   and so on, using whatever descriptive terms happen to occur to you. 3 If terms which 
36   seem positive rather than negative occur to you, include them. 4 For example, you might 
37   think of "a good world," or "a satisfying world." 5 If such terms occur to you, use them 
38   along with the rest. 6 You may not yet understand why these "nice" adjectives belong in 
39   these exercises but remember that a "good world" implies a "bad" one, and a "satisfying 
40   world" implies an "unsatisfying" one. 7 All terms which cross your mind are suitable 
41   subjects for today's exercises. 8 Their seeming quality does not matter.
42   W-pI.12.4. Be sure that you do not alter the time intervals between applying today's 
43   idea to what you think is pleasant and what you think is unpleasant. 2 For the purposes of 
44   these exercises, there is no difference between them. 3 At the end of the practice period, 
45   add: 
46   
47   4 But I am upset because I see a meaningless world.
48   
49   W-pI.12.5. What is meaningless is neither good nor bad. 2 Why, then, should a 
50   meaningless world upset you? 3 If you could accept the world as meaningless and let the truth be 
0416
 1   written upon it for you, it would make you indescribably happy. 4 But because it is 
 2   meaningless, you are impelled to write upon it what you would have it be. 5 It is this you see in 
 3   it. 6 It is this that is meaningless in truth. 7 Beneath your words is written the Word 
 4   of God. 8 The truth upsets you now, but when your words have been erased, you will see 
 5   His. 9 That is the ultimate purpose of these exercises.
 6   W-pI.12.6. Three or four times is enough for practicing the idea for today. 2 Nor 
 7   should the practice periods exceed a minute. 3 You may find even this too long. 4 Terminate 
 8   the exercises whenever you experience a sense of strain.
 9   
10   
11   
12   LESSON 13.
13   
14   A meaningless world engenders fear.
15   W-pI.13.1. Today's idea is really another form of the preceding one, except that it is 
16   more specific as to the emotion aroused. 2 Actually, a meaningless world is impossible. 3 
17   Nothing without meaning exists. 4 However, it does not follow that you will not think you 
18   perceive something that has no meaning. 5 On the contrary, you will be particularly likely to 
19   think you do perceive it.
20   W-pI.13.2. Recognition of meaninglessness arouses intense anxiety in all the separated 
21   ones. 2 It represents a situation in which God and the ego "challenge" each other as to 
22   whose meaning is to be written in the empty space that meaninglessness provides. 3 The ego 
23   rushes in frantically to establish its own ideas there, fearful that the void may otherwise 
24   be used to demonstrate its own impotence and unreality. 4 And on this alone it is correct.
25   
26   W-pI.13.3. It is essential, therefore, that you learn to recognize the meaningless, and
27   accept it without fear. 2 If you are fearful, it is certain that you will endow the 
28   world with attributes that it does not possess, and crowd it with images that do not exist. 
29   3 To the ego illusions are safety devices, as they must also be to you who equate 
30   yourself with the ego.
31   W-pI.13.4. The exercises for today, which should be done about three or four times for 
32   not more than a minute or so at most each time, are to be practiced in a somewhat 
33   different way from the preceding ones. 2 With eyes closed, repeat today's idea to yourself. 3 
34   Then open your eyes, and look about you slowly, saying: 
35   
36   4 I am looking at a meaningless world. 
37   
38   5 Repeat this statement to yourself as you look about. 6 Then close your eyes, and 
39   conclude with: 
40   
41   7 A meaningless world engenders fear because I think I am in competition with God.
42   
43   W-pI.13.5. You may find it difficult to avoid resistance, in one form or another, to 
44   this concluding statement. 2 Whatever form such resistance may take, remind yourself that 
45   you are really afraid of such a thought because of the "vengeance" of the "enemy." 3 You 
46   are not expected to believe the statement at this point, and will probably dismiss it as 
47   preposterous. 4 Note carefully, however, any signs of overt or covert fear which it may arouse.
48   W-pI.13.6. This is our first attempt at stating an explicit cause and effect 
49   relationship of a kind which you are very inexperienced in recognizing. 2 Do not dwell on the 
50   concluding statement, and try not even to think of it except during the practice periods. 3 That 
0417
 1   will suffice at present.
 2   
 3   
 4   
 5   LESSON 14.
 6   
 7   God did not create a meaningless world.
 8   W-pI.14.1. The idea for today is, of course, the reason why a meaningless world is 
 9   impossible. 2 What God did not create does not exist. 3 And everything that does exist exists as 
10   He created it. 4 The world you see has nothing to do with reality. 5 It is of your own 
11   making, and it does not exist.
12   W-pI.14.2. The exercises for today are to be practiced with eyes closed throughout. 2 
13   The mind-searching period should be short, a minute at most. 3 Do not have more than three
14   practice periods with today's idea unless you find them comfortable. 4 If you do, it 
15   will be because you really understand what they are for.
16   W-pI.14.3. The idea for today is another step in learning to let go the thoughts that 
17   you have written on the world, and see the Word of God in their place. 2 The early steps 
18   in this exchange, which can truly be called salvation, can be quite difficult and even 
19   quite painful. 3 Some of them will lead you directly into fear. 4 You will not be left there.
20    5 You will go far beyond it. 6 Our direction is toward perfect safety and perfect 
21   peace.
22   W-pI.14.4. With eyes closed, think of all the horrors in the world that cross your mind.
23    2 Name each one as it occurs to you, and then deny its reality. 3 God did not create 
24   it, and so it is not real. 4 Say, for example: 
25   
26   5 God did not create that war, and so it is not real. 
27   6 God did not create that airplane crash, and so it is not real. 
28   7 God did not create that disaster [specify], and so it is not real.
29   
30   W-pI.14.5. Suitable subjects for the application of today's idea also include anything 
31   you are afraid might happen to you, or to anyone about whom you are concerned. 2 In each 
32   case, name the "disaster" quite specifically. 3 Do not use general terms. 4 For example, do
33   not say, "God did not create illness," but, "God did not create cancer," or heart 
34   attacks, or whatever may arouse fear in you.
35   W-pI.14.6. This is your personal repertory of horrors at which you are looking. 2 These
36   things are part of the world you see. 3 Some of them are shared illusions, and others 
37   are part of your personal hell. 4 It does not matter. 5 What God did not create can only 
38   be in your own mind apart from His. 6 Therefore, it has no meaning. 7 In recognition of 
39   this fact, conclude the practice periods by repeating today's idea: 
40   
41   8 God did not create a meaningless world.
42   
43   W-pI.14.7. The idea for today can, of course, be applied to anything that disturbs you 
44   during the day, aside from the practice periods. 2 Be very specific in applying it. 3 Say: 
45   
46   4 God did not create a meaningless world. 5 He did not create [specify the situation 
47   which is disturbing you], and so it is not real.
