38   LESSON 16.
39   
40   I have no neutral thoughts.
41   W-pI.16.W-pI.1. The idea for today is a beginning step in dispelling the belief that 
42   your thoughts have no effect. 2 Everything you see is the result of your thoughts. 3 There 
43   is no exception to this fact. 4 Thoughts are not big or little; powerful or weak. 5 They 
44   are merely true or false. 6 Those that are true create their own likeness. 7 Those that 
45   are false make theirs.
46   W-pI.16.2. There is no more self-contradictory concept than that of "idle thoughts." 2 
47   What gives rise to the perception of a whole world can hardly be called idle. 3 Every 
48   thought you have contributes to truth or to illusion; either it extends the truth or it 
49   multiplies illusions. 4 You can indeed multiply nothing, but you will not extend it by doing so.
50   W-pI.16.3. Besides your recognizing that thoughts are never idle, salvation requires 
0419
 1   that you also recognize that every thought you have brings either peace or war; either love
 2   or fear. 2 A neutral result is impossible because a neutral thought is impossible. 3 
 3   There is such a temptation to dismiss fear thoughts as unimportant, trivial and not worth 
 4   bothering about that it is essential you recognize them all as equally destructive, but equally 
 5   unreal. 4 We will practice this idea in many forms before you really understand it.
 6   W-pI.16.4. In applying the idea for today, search your mind for a minute or so with 
 7   eyes closed, and actively seek not to overlook any "little" thought that may tend to elude 
 8   the search. 2 This is quite difficult until you get used to it. 3 You will find that it is
 9   still hard for you not to make artificial distinctions. 4 Every thought that occurs to 
10   you, regardless of the qualities that you assign to it, is a suitable subject for applying
11   today's idea.
12   W-pI.16.5. In the practice periods, first repeat the idea to yourself, and then as each
13   one crosses your mind hold it in awareness while you tell yourself: 
14   
15   2 This thought about___is not a neutral thought. 
16   3 That thought about___is not a neutral thought. 
17   
18   4 As usual, use today's idea whenever you are aware of a particular thought that 
19   arouses uneasiness. 5 The following form is suggested for this purpose: 
20   
21   6 This thought about___is not a neutral thought, because I have no neutral thoughts.
22   
23   W-pI.16.6. Four or five practice periods are recommended, if you find them relatively 
24   effortless. 2 If strain is experienced, three will be enough. 3 The length of the exercise period
25   should also be reduced if there is discomfort.
