29   LESSON 17.
30   
31   I see no neutral things.
32   W-pI.17.1. This idea is another step in the direction of identifying cause and effect 
33   as it really operates in the world. 2 You see no neutral things because you have no 
34   neutral thoughts. 3 It is always the thought that comes first, despite the temptation to 
35   believe that it is the other way around. 4 This is not the way the world thinks, but you must 
36   learn that it is the way you think. 5 If it were not so, perception would have no cause, and
37   would itself be the cause of reality. 6 In view of its highly variable nature, this is 
38   hardly likely.
39   W-pI.17.2. In applying today's idea, say to yourself, with eyes open: 
40   
41   2 I see no neutral things because I have no neutral thoughts. 
42   
43   3 Then look about you, resting your glance on each thing you note long enough to say: 
44   
45   4 I do not see a neutral ___, because my thoughts about___are not neutral. 
46   
47   5 For example, you might say: 
48   
49   6 I do not see a neutral wall, because my thoughts about walls are not neutral. 
50   7 I do not see a neutral body, because my thoughts about bodies are not neutral.
0420
 1   
 2   W-pI.17.3. As usual, it is essential to make no distinctions between what you believe 
 3   to be animate or inanimate; pleasant or unpleasant. 2 Regardless of what you may believe,
 4   you do not see anything that is really alive or really joyous. 3 That is because you 
 5   are unaware as yet of any thought that is really true, and therefore really happy.
 6   W-pI.17.4. Three or four specific practice periods are recommended, and no less than 
 7   three are required for maximum benefit, even if you experience resistance. 2 However, if you
 8   do, the length of the practice period may be reduced to less than the minute or so that
 9   is otherwise recommended.
