35   LESSON 22.
36   
37   What I see is a form of vengeance.
38   W-pI.22.1. Today's idea accurately describes the way anyone who holds attack thoughts 
39   in his mind must see the world. 2 Having projected his anger onto the world, he sees 
40   vengeance about to strike at him. 3 His own attack is thus perceived as self defense. 4 This 
41   becomes an increasingly vicious circle until he is willing to change how he sees. 5 Otherwise,
42   thoughts of attack and counter-attack will preoccupy him and people his entire world. 6
43   What peace of mind is possible to him then?
44   W-pI.22.2. It is from this savage fantasy that you want to escape. 2 Is it not joyous 
45   news to hear that it is not real? 3 Is it not a happy discovery to find that you can escape?
46    4 You made what you would destroy; everything that you hate and would attack and kill.
47   5 All that you fear does not exist.
48   W-pI.22.3. Look at the world about you at least five times today, for at least a minute
49   each time. 2 As your eyes move slowly from one object to another, from one body to 
50   another, say to yourself: 
0423
 1   
 2   3 I see only the perishable. 
 3   4 I see nothing that will last. 
 4   5 What I see is not real. 
 5   6 What I see is a form of vengeance. 
 6   
 7   7 At the end of each practice period, ask yourself: 
 8   
 9   8 Is this the world I really want to see? 
10   
11   9 The answer is surely obvious.
12   
