12   LESSON 24.
13   
14   I do not perceive my own best interests.
15   W-pI.24.1. In no situation that arises do you realize the outcome that would make you 
16   happy. 2 Therefore, you have no guide to appropriate action, and no way of judging the 
17   result. 3 What you do is determined by your perception of the situation, and that perception 
18   is wrong. 4 It is inevitable, then, that you will not serve your own best interests. 5 
19   Yet they are your only goal in any situation which is correctly perceived. 6 Otherwise, 
20   you will not recognize what they are.
21   W-pI.24.2. If you realized that you do not perceive your own best interests, you could 
22   be taught what they are. 2 But in the presence of your conviction that you do know what 
23   they are, you cannot learn. 3 The idea for today is a step toward opening your mind so that
24   learning can begin.
25   W-pI.24.3. The exercises for today require much more honesty than you are accustomed to
26   using. 2 A few subjects, honestly and carefully considered in each of the five practice
27   periods which should be undertaken today, will be more helpful than a more cursory 
28   examination of a large number. 3 Two minutes are suggested for each of the mind-searching periods 
29   which the exercises involve.
30   W-pI.24.4. The practice periods should begin with repeating today's idea, followed by 
31   searching the mind, with closed eyes, for unresolved situations about which you are currently 
32   concerned. 2 The emphasis should be on uncovering the outcome you want. 3 You will quickly 
33   realize that you have a number of goals in mind as part of the desired outcome, and also that 
34   these goals are on different levels and often conflict.
35   W-pI.24.5. In applying the idea for today, name each situation that occurs to you, and 
36   then enumerate carefully as many goals as possible that you would like to be met in its 
37   resolution. 2 The form of each application should be roughly as follows: 
38   
39   3 In the situation involving___, I would like___to happen, and___to happen, 
40   
41   and so on. 4 Try to cover as many different kinds of outcomes as may honestly occur to 
42   you, even if some of them do not appear to be directly related to the situation, or even 
43   to be inherent in it at all.
44   W-pI.24.6. If these exercises are done properly, you will quickly recognize that you 
45   are making a large number of demands of the situation which have nothing to do with it. 2 
46   You will also recognize that many of your goals are contradictory, that you have no 
47   unified outcome in mind, and that you must experience disappointment in connection with some 
48   of your goals, however the situation turns out.
49   W-pI.24.7. After covering the list of as many hoped-for goals as possible, for each 
50   unresolved situation that crosses your mind say to yourself: 
0425
 1   
 2   2 I do not perceive my own best interests in this situation, 
 3   
 4   and go on to the next one.
