 8   LESSON 25.
 9   
10   I do not know what anything is for.
11   W-pI.25.1. Purpose is meaning. 2 Today's idea explains why nothing you see means 
12   anything. 3 You do not know what it is for. 4 Therefore, it is meaningless to you. 5 Everything
13   is for your own best interests. 6 That is what it is for; that is its purpose; that is 
14   what it means. 7 It is in recognizing this that your goals become unified. 8 It is in 
15   recognizing this that what you see is given meaning.
16   W-pI.25.2. You perceive the world and everything in it as meaningful in terms of ego 
17   goals. 2 These goals have nothing to do with your own best interests, because the ego is not
18   you. 3 This false identification makes you incapable of understanding what anything is 
19   for. 4 As a result, you are bound to misuse it. 5 When you believe this, you will try to 
20   withdraw the goals you have assigned to the world, instead of attempting to reinforce them.
21   W-pI.25.3. Another way of describing the goals you now perceive is to say that they are
22   all concerned with "personal" interests. 2 Since you have no personal interests, your 
23   goals are really concerned with nothing. 3 In cherishing them, therefore, you have no goals 
24   at all. 4 And thus you do not know what anything is for.
25   W-pI.25.4. Before you can make any sense out of the exercises for today, one more 
26   thought is necessary. 2 At the most superficial levels, you do recognize purpose. 3 Yet 
27   purpose cannot be understood at these levels. 4 For example, you do understand that a 
28   telephone is for the purpose of talking to someone who is not physically in your immediate 
29   vicinity. 5 What you do not understand is what you want to reach him for. 6 And it is this that
30   makes your contact with him meaningful or not.
31   W-pI.25.5. It is crucial to your learning to be willing to give up the goals you have 
32   established for everything. 2 The recognition that they are meaningless, rather than "good" or "
33   bad," is the only way to accomplish this. 3 The idea for today is a step in this direction.
34   
35   W-pI.25.6. Six practice periods, each of two-minutes duration, are required. 2 Each 
36   practice period should begin with a slow repetition of the idea for today, followed by looking 
37   about you and letting your glance rest on whatever happens to catch your eye, near or far, "
38   important" or "unimportant," "human" or "nonhuman." 3 With your eyes resting on each subject you
39   so select, say, for example: 
40   
41   4 I do not know what this chair is for. 
42   5 I do not know what this pencil is for. 
43   6 I do not know what this hand is for. 
44   
45   7 Say this quite slowly, without shifting your eyes from the subject until you have 
46   completed the statement about it. 8 Then move on to the next subject, and apply today's idea as 
47   before.
