0426
 1   LESSON 26.
 2   
 3   My attack thoughts are attacking my invulnerability.
 4   W-pI.26.1. It is surely obvious that if you can be attacked you are not invulnerable. 2
 5   You see attack as a real threat. 3 That is because you believe that you can really 
 6   attack. 4 And what would have effects through you must also have effects on you. 5 It is this
 7   law that will ultimately save you, but you are misusing it now. 6 You must therefore 
 8   learn how it can be used for your own best interests, rather than against them.
 9   W-pI.26.2. Because your attack thoughts will be projected, you will fear attack. 2 And 
10   if you fear attack, you must believe that you are not invulnerable. 3 Attack thoughts 
11   therefore make you vulnerable in your own mind, which is where the attack thoughts are. 4 Attack
12   thoughts and invulnerability cannot be accepted together. 5 They contradict each other.
13   W-pI.26.3. The idea for today introduces the thought that you always attack yourself 
14   first. 2 If attack thoughts must entail the belief that you are vulnerable, their effect is 
15   to weaken you in your own eyes. 3 Thus they have attacked your perception of yourself. 4 
16   And because you believe in them, you can no longer believe in yourself. 5 A false image of
17   yourself has come to take the place of what you are.
18   W-pI.26.4. Practice with today's idea will help you to understand that vulnerability or
19   invulnerability is the result of your own thoughts. 2 Nothing except your thoughts can 
20   attack you. 3 Nothing except your thoughts can make you think you are vulnerable. 4 And 
21   nothing except your thoughts can prove to you this is not so.
22   W-pI.26.5. Six practice periods are required in applying today's idea. 2 A full two 
23   minutes should be attempted for each of them, although the time may be reduced to a minute if 
24   the discomfort is too great. 3 Do not reduce it further.
25   W-pI.26.6. The practice period should begin with repeating the idea for today, then 
26   closing your eyes and reviewing the unresolved questions whose outcomes are causing you 
27   concern. 2 The concern may take the form of depression, worry, anger, a sense of imposition, 
28   fear, foreboding or preoccupation. 3 Any problem as yet unsettled that tends to recur in 
29   your thoughts during the day is a suitable subject. 4 You will not be able to use very many
30   for any one practice period, because a longer time than usual should be spent with each
31   one. 5 Today's idea should be applied as follows:
32   W-pI.26.7. First, name the situation: 
33   
34   2 I am concerned about ___. 
35   
36   3 Then go over every possible outcome that has occurred to you in that connection and 
37   which has caused you concern, referring to each one quite specifically, saying: 
38   
39   4 I am afraid___will happen.
40   
41   W-pI.26.8. If you are doing the exercises properly, you should have some five or six 
42   distressing possibilities available for each situation you use, and quite possibly more. 2 It is 
43   much more helpful to cover a few situations thoroughly than to touch on a larger number. 3 
44   As the list of anticipated outcomes for each situation continues, you will probably find 
45   some of them, especially those that occur to you toward the end, less acceptable to you. 4 
46   Try, however, to treat them all alike to whatever extent you can.
47   W-pI.26.9. After you have named each outcome of which you are afraid, tell yourself: 
48   
49   2 That thought is an attack upon myself. 
50   
0427
 1   3 Conclude each practice period by repeating today's idea to yourself once more.
