39   LESSON 28.
40   
41   Above all else I want to see things differently.
42   W-pI.28.1. Today we are really giving specific application to the idea for yesterday. 2
43   In these practice periods, you will be making a series of definite commitments. 3 The 
44   question of whether you will keep them in the future is not our concern here. 4 If you are 
45   willing at least to make them now, you have started on the way to keeping them. 5 And we are 
46   still at the beginning.
47   W-pI.28.2. You may wonder why it is important to say, for example, "Above all else I 
48   want to see this table differently." 2 In itself it is not important at all. 3 Yet what is 
49   by itself? 4 And what does "in itself" mean? 5 You see a lot of separate things about you,
50    which really means you are not seeing at all. 6 You either see or not. 7 When you have
0428
 1   seen one thing differently, you will see all things differently. 8 The light you will 
 2   see in any one of them is the same light you will see in them all.
 3   W-pI.28.3. When you say, "Above all else I want to see this table differently," you are
 4   making a commitment to withdraw your preconceived ideas about the table, and open your 
 5   mind to what it is, and what it is for. 2 You are not defining it in past terms. 3 You are 
 6   asking what it is, rather than telling it what it is. 4 You are not binding its meaning to 
 7   your tiny experience of tables, nor are you limiting its purpose to your little personal 
 8   thoughts.
 9   W-pI.28.4. You will not question what you have already defined. 2 And the purpose of 
10   these exercises is to ask questions and receive the answers. 3 In saying, "Above all else I 
11   want to see this table differently," you are committing yourself to seeing. 4 It is not an 
12   exclusive commitment. 5 It is a commitment that applies to the table just as much as to anything
13   else, neither more nor less.
14   W-pI.28.5. You could, in fact, gain vision from just that table, if you would withdraw 
15   all your own ideas from it, and look upon it with a completely open mind. 2 It has 
16   something to show you; something beautiful and clean and of infinite value, full of happiness 
17   and hope. 3 Hidden under all your ideas about it is its real purpose, the purpose it 
18   shares with all the universe.
19   W-pI.28.6. In using the table as a subject for applying the idea for today, you are 
20   therefore really asking to see the purpose of the universe. 2 You will be making this same 
21   request of each subject that you use in the practice periods. 3 And you are making a 
22   commitment to each of them to let its purpose be revealed to you, instead of placing your own 
23   judgment upon it.
24   W-pI.28.7. We will have six two-minute practice periods today, in which the idea for 
25   the day is stated first, and then applied to whatever you see about you. 2 Not only should
26   the subjects be chosen randomly, but each one should be accorded equal sincerity as 
27   today's idea is applied to it, in an attempt to acknowledge the equal value of them all in 
28   their contribution to your seeing.
29   W-pI.28.8. As usual, the applications should include the name of the subject your eyes 
30   happen to light on, and you should rest your eyes on it while saying: 
31   
32   2 Above all else I want to see this___differently. 
33   
34   3 Each application should be made quite slowly, and as thoughtfully as possible. 4 
35   There is no hurry.
