30   LESSON 35.
31   
32   My mind is part of God's. I am very holy.
33   W-pI.35.1. Today's idea does not describe the way you see yourself now. 2 It does, 
34   however, describe what vision will show you. 3 It is difficult for anyone who thinks he is in 
35   this world to believe this of himself. 4 Yet the reason he thinks he is in this world is 
36   because he does not believe it.
37   W-pI.35.2. You will believe that you are part of where you think you are. 2 That is 
38   because you surround yourself with the environment you want. 3 And you want it to protect the 
39   image of yourself that you have made. 4 The image is part of this environment. 5 What you 
40   see while you believe you are in it is seen through the eyes of the image. 6 This is not 
41   vision. 7 Images cannot see.
42   W-pI.35.3. The idea for today presents a very different view of yourself. 2 By 
43   establishing your Source it establishes your Identity, and it describes you as you must really be 
44   in truth. 3 We will use a somewhat different kind of application for today's idea because
45   the emphasis for today is on the perceiver, rather than on what he perceives.
46   W-pI.35.4. For each of the three five-minute practice periods today, begin by repeating
47   today's idea to yourself, and then close your eyes and search your mind for the various
48   kinds of descriptive terms in which you see yourself. 2 Include all the ego-based 
49   attributes which you ascribe to yourself, positive or negative, desirable or undesirable, 
50   grandiose or debased. 3 All of them are equally unreal, because you do not look upon yourself 
0433
 1   through the eyes of holiness.
 2   W-pI.35.5. In the earlier part of the mind-searching period, you will probably 
 3   emphasize what you consider to be the more negative aspects of your perception of yourself. 2 
 4   Toward the latter part of the exercise period, however, more self-inflating descriptive terms
 5   may well cross your mind. 3 Try to recognize that the direction of your fantasies about
 6   yourself does not matter. 4 Illusions have no direction in reality. 5 They are merely 
 7   not true.
 8   W-pI.35.6. A suitable unselected list for applying the idea for today might be as 
 9   follows: 
10   
11   2 I see myself as imposed on. 
12   3 I see myself as depressed. 
13   4 I see myself as failing. 
14   5 I see myself as endangered. 
15   6 I see myself as helpless. 
16   7 I see myself as victorious. 
17   8 I see myself as losing out. 
18   9 I see myself as charitable. 
19   10 I see myself as virtuous.
20   
21   W-pI.35.7. You should not think of these terms in an abstract way. 2 They will occur to
22   you as various situations, personalities and events in which you figure cross your mind.
23    3 Pick up any specific situation that occurs to you, identify the descriptive term or 
24   terms you feel are applicable to your reactions to that situation, and use them in applying 
25   today's idea. 4 After you have named each one, add: 
26   
27   5 But my mind is part of God's. 6 I am very holy.
28   
29   W-pI.35.8. During the longer exercise periods, there will probably be intervals in 
30   which nothing specific occurs to you. 2 Do not strain to think up specific things to fill 
31   the interval, but merely relax and repeat today's idea slowly until something occurs to 
32   you. 3 Although nothing that does occur should be omitted from the exercises, nothing 
33   should be "dug out" with effort. 4 Neither force nor discrimination should be used.
34   W-pI.35.9. As often as possible during the day, pick up a specific attribute or 
35   attributes you are ascribing to yourself at the time and apply the idea for today to them, adding
36   the idea in the form stated above to each of them. 2 If nothing particular occurs to 
37   you, merely repeat the idea to yourself, with closed eyes.
