23   LESSON 37.
24   
25   My holiness blesses the world.
26   W-pI.37.1. This idea contains the first glimmerings of your true function in the world,
27   or why you are here. 2 Your purpose is to see the world through your own holiness. 3 
28   Thus are you and the world blessed together. 4 No one loses; nothing is taken away from 
29   anyone; everyone gains through your holy vision. 5 It signifies the end of sacrifice because 
30   it offers everyone his full due. 6 And he is entitled to everything because it is his 
31   birthright as a Son of God.
32   W-pI.37.2. There is no other way in which the idea of sacrifice can be removed from the
33   world's thinking. 2 Any other way of seeing will inevitably demand payment of someone 
34   or something. 3 As a result, the perceiver will lose. 4 Nor will he have any idea why he 
35   is losing. 5 Yet is his wholeness restored to his awareness through your vision. 6 Your 
36   holiness blesses him by asking nothing of him. 7 Those who see themselves as whole make no 
37   demands.
38   W-pI.37.3. Your holiness is the salvation of the world. 2 It lets you teach the world 
39   that it is one with you, not by preaching to it, not by telling it anything, but merely by 
40   your quiet recognition that in your holiness are all things blessed along with you.
41   W-pI.37.4. Today's four longer exercise periods, each to involve three to five minutes 
42   of practice, begin with the repetition of the idea for today, followed by a minute or so 
43   of looking about you as you apply the idea to whatever you see: 
44   
45   2 My holiness blesses this chair
46   3 My holiness blesses that window
47   4 My holiness blesses this body. 
48   
49   5 Then close your eyes and apply the idea to any person who occurs to you, using his 
50   name and saying: 
0435
 1   
 2   6 My holiness blesses you, [name].
 3   
 4   W-pI.37.5. You may continue the practice period with your eyes closed; you may open 
 5   your eyes again and apply the idea for today to your outer world if you so desire; you may 
 6   alternate between applying the idea to what you see around you and to those who are in your 
 7   thoughts; or you may use any combination of these two phases of application that you prefer. 2 
 8   The practice period should conclude with a repetition of the idea with your eyes closed, 
 9   and another, following immediately, with your eyes open.
10   W-pI.37.6. The shorter exercises consist of repeating the idea as often as you can. 2 
11   It is particularly helpful to apply it silently to anyone you meet, using his name as you
12   do so. 3 It is essential to use the idea if anyone seems to cause an adverse reaction 
13   in you. 4 Offer him the blessing of your holiness immediately, that you may learn to keep
14   it in your own awareness.
