12   LESSON 39.
13   
14   My holiness is my salvation.
15   W-pI.39.1. If guilt is hell, what is its opposite? 2 Like the text for which this 
16   workbook was written, the ideas used for the exercises are very simple, very clear and totally 
17   unambiguous. 3 We are not concerned with intellectual feats nor logical toys. 4 We are dealing 
18   only in the very obvious, which has been overlooked in the clouds of complexity in which 
19   you think you think.
20   W-pI.39.2. If guilt is hell, what is its opposite? 2 This is not difficult, surely. 3 
21   The hesitation you may feel in answering is not due to the ambiguity of the question. 4 
22   But do you believe that guilt is hell? 5 If you did, you would see at once how direct and 
23   simple the text is, and you would not need a workbook at all. 6 No one needs practice to gain
24   what is already his.
25   W-pI.39.3. We have already said that your holiness is the salvation of the world. 2 
26   What about your own salvation? 3 You cannot give what you do not have. 4 A savior must be 
27   saved. 5 How else can he teach salvation? 6 Today's exercises will apply to you, recognizing
28   that your salvation is crucial to the salvation of the world. 7 As you apply the 
29   exercises to your world, the whole world stands to benefit.
30   W-pI.39.4. Your holiness is the answer to every question that was ever asked, is being 
31   asked now, or will be asked in the future. 2 Your holiness means the end of guilt, and 
32   therefore the end of hell. 3 Your holiness is the salvation of the world, and your own. 4 How 
33   could you to whom your holiness belongs be excluded from it? 5 God does not know unholiness.
34   6 Can it be He does not know His Son?
35   W-pI.39.5. A full five minutes are urged for the four longer practice periods for today,
36    and longer and more frequent practice sessions are encouraged. 2 If you want to exceed
37   the minimum requirements, more rather than longer sessions are recommended, although 
38   both are suggested.
39   W-pI.39.6. Begin the practice periods as usual, by repeating today's idea to yourself. 
40   2 Then, with closed eyes, search out your unloving thoughts in whatever form they appear;
41    uneasiness, depression, anger, fear, worry, attack, insecurity and so on. 3 Whatever 
42   form they take, they are unloving and therefore fearful. 4 And so it is from them that you 
43   need to be saved.
44   W-pI.39.7. Specific situations, events or personalities you associate with unloving 
45   thoughts of any kind are suitable subjects for today's exercises. 2 It is imperative for your 
46   salvation that you see them differently. 3 And it is your blessing on them that will save you 
47   and give you vision.
48   W-pI.39.8. Slowly, without conscious selection and without undue emphasis on any one in
49   particular, search your mind for every thought that stands between you and your 
50   salvation. 2 Apply the idea for today to each of them in this way: 
0437
 1   
 2   3 My unloving thoughts about___are keeping me in hell
 3   4 My holiness is my salvation.
 4   
 5   W-pI.39.9. You may find these practice periods easier if you intersperse them with 
 6   several short periods during which you merely repeat today's idea to yourself slowly a few 
 7   times. 2 You may also find it helpful to include a few short intervals in which you just 
 8   relax and do not seem to be thinking of anything. 3 Sustained concentration is very 
 9   difficult at first. 4 It will become much easier as your mind becomes more disciplined and less 
10   distractible.
11   W-pI.39.10. Meanwhile, you should feel free to introduce variety into the exercise 
12   periods in whatever form appeals to you. 2 Do not, however, change the idea itself as you vary
13   the method of applying it. 3 However you elect to use it, the idea should be stated so 
14   that its meaning is the fact that your holiness is your salvation. 4 End each practice 
15   period by repeating the idea in its original form once more, and adding: 
16   
17   5 If guilt is hell, what is its opposite?
18   
19   W-pI.39.11. In the shorter applications, which should be made some three or four times 
20   an hour and more if possible, you may ask yourself this question, repeat today's idea, 
21   and preferably both. 2 If temptations arise, a particularly helpful form of the idea is: 
22   
23   3 My holiness is my salvation from this.
