 6   LESSON 42.
 7   
 8   God is my strength. Vision is His gift.
 9   W-pI.42.1. The idea for today combines two very powerful thoughts, both of major 
10   importance. 2 It also sets forth a cause and effect relationship that explains why you cannot 
11   fail in your efforts to achieve the goal of the course. 3 You will see because it is the 
12   Will of God. 4 It is His strength, not your own, that gives you power. 5 And it is His gift,
13    rather than your own, that offers vision to you.
14   W-pI.42.2. God is indeed your strength, and what He gives is truly given. 2 This means 
15   that you can receive it any time and anywhere, wherever you are, and in whatever 
16   circumstance you find yourself. 3 Your passage through time and space is not at random. 4 You 
17   cannot but be in the right place at the right time. 5 Such is the strength of God. 6 Such are
18   His gifts.
19   W-pI.42.3. We will have two three-to-five-minute practice periods today, one as soon as
20   possible after you wake, and another as close as possible to the time you go to sleep. 
21   2 It is better, however, to wait until you can sit quietly by yourself, at a time when 
22   you feel ready, than it is to be concerned with the time as such.
23   W-pI.42.4. Begin these practice periods by repeating the idea for today slowly, with 
24   your eyes open, looking about you. 2 Then close your eyes and repeat the idea again, even 
25   slower than before. 3 After this, try to think of nothing except thoughts that occur to you 
26   in relation to the idea for the day. 4 You might think, for example: 
27   
28   5 Vision must be possible. 6 God gives truly, 
29   
30   or: 
31   
32   7 God's gifts to me must be mine, because He gave them to me.
33   
34   W-pI.42.5. Any thought that is clearly related to the idea for today is suitable. 2 You
35   may, in fact, be astonished at the amount of course-related understanding some of your 
36   thoughts contain. 3 Let them come without censoring unless you find your mind is merely 
37   wandering, and you have let obviously irrelevant thoughts intrude. 4 You may also reach a point 
38   where no thoughts at all seem to come to mind. 5 If such interferences occur, open your eyes
39   and repeat the thought once more while looking slowly about; close your eyes, repeat 
40   the idea once more, and then continue to look for related thoughts in your mind.
41   W-pI.42.6. Remember, however, that active searching for relevant thoughts is not 
42   appropriate for today's exercises. 2 Try merely to step back and let the thoughts come. 3 If you 
43   find this difficult, it is better to spend the practice period alternating between slow 
44   repetitions of the idea with eyes open, then with eyes closed, than it is to strain to find 
45   suitable thoughts.
46   W-pI.42.7. There is no limit on the number of short practice periods that would be 
47   beneficial today. 2 The idea for the day is a beginning step in bringing thoughts together, and 
48   teaching you that you are studying a unified thought system in which nothing is lacking that is
49   needed, and nothing is included that is contradictory or irrelevant.
50   W-pI.42.8. The more often you repeat the idea during the day, the more often you will 
0440
 1   be reminding yourself that the goal of the course is important to you, and that you have 
 2   not forgotten it.
