26   REVIEW I
27   
28   Introduction
29   W-pI.rI.in.1. Beginning with today we will have a series of review periods. 2 Each of 
30   them will cover five of the ideas already presented, starting with the first and ending 
31   with the fiftieth. 3 There will be a few short comments after each of the ideas, which you 
32   should consider in your review. 4 In the practice periods, the exercises should be done as 
33   follows:
34   W-pI.rI.in.2. Begin the day by reading the five ideas, with the comments included. 2 
35   Thereafter, it is not necessary to follow any particular order in considering them, though each 
36   one should be practiced at least once. 3 Devote two minutes or more to each practice 
37   period, thinking about the idea and the related comments after reading them over. 4 Do this 
38   as often as possible during the day. 5 If any one of the five ideas appeals to you more 
39   than the others, concentrate on that one. 6 At the end of the day, however, be sure to 
40   review all of them once more.
41   W-pI.rI.in.3. It is not necessary to cover the comments that follow each idea either 
42   literally or thoroughly in the practice periods. 2 Try, rather, to emphasize the central point, 
43   and think about it as part of your review of the idea to which it relates. 3 After you 
44   have read the idea and the related comments, the exercises should be done with your eyes 
45   closed and when you are alone in a quiet place, if possible.
46   W-pI.rI.in.4. This is emphasized for practice periods at your stage of learning. 2 It 
47   will be necessary, however, that you learn to require no special settings in which to apply
48   what you have learned. 3 You will need your learning most in situations that appear to 
49   be upsetting, rather than in those that already seem to be calm and quiet. 4 The purpose 
50   of your learning is to enable you to bring the quiet with you, and to heal distress and 
0448
 1   turmoil. 5 This is not done by avoiding them and seeking a haven of isolation for yourself.
 2   W-pI.rI.in.5. You will yet learn that peace is part of you, and requires only that you 
 3   be there to embrace any situation in which you are. 2 And finally you will learn that 
 4   there is no limit to where you are, so that your peace is everywhere, as you are.
 5   W-pI.rI.in.6. You will note that, for review purposes, some of the ideas are not given 
 6   in quite their original form. 2 Use them as they are given here. 3 It is not necessary to
 7   return to the original statements, nor to apply the ideas as was suggested then. 4 We 
 8   are now emphasizing the relationships among the first fifty of the ideas we have covered, 
 9   and the cohesiveness of the thought system to which they are leading you.
10   
