12   
13   LESSON 51.
14   
15   The review for today covers the following ideas:
16   W-pI.51.1. (1) Nothing I see means anything.
17    2 The reason this is so is that I see nothing, and nothing has no meaning. 3 It is 
18   necessary that I recognize this, that I may learn to see. 4 What I think I see now is taking the
19   place of vision. 5 I must let it go by realizing it has no meaning, so that vision may 
20   take its place.
21   
22   W-pI.51.2. (2) I have given what I see all the meaning it has for me. 2 I have judged 
23   everything I look upon, and it is this and only this I see. 3 This is not vision. 4 It is merely 
24   an illusion of reality, because my judgments have been made quite apart from reality. 5 I
25   am willing to recognize the lack of validity in my judgments, because I want to see. 6 
26   My judgments have hurt me, and I do not want to see according to them.
27   
28   W-pI.51.3. (3) I do not understand anything I see. 2 How could I understand what I see 
29   when I have judged it amiss? 3 What I see is the projection of my own errors of thought. 4 
30   I do not understand what I see because it is not understandable. 5 There is no sense in 
31   trying to understand it. 6 But there is every reason to let it go, and make room for what can
32   be seen and understood and loved. 7 I can exchange what I see now for this merely by 
33   being willing to do so. 8 Is not this a better choice than the one I made before?
34   
35   W-pI.51.4. (4) These thoughts do not mean anything. 
36   2 The thoughts of which I am aware do not mean anything because I am trying to think 
37   without God. 3 What I call "my" thoughts are not my real thoughts. 4 My real thoughts are the 
38   thoughts I think with God. 5 I am not aware of them because I have made my thoughts to take 
39   their place. 6 I am willing to recognize that my thoughts do not mean anything, and to let 
40   them go. 7 I choose to have them be replaced by what they were intended to replace. 8 My 
41   thoughts are meaningless, but all creation lies in the thoughts I think with God.
42   
43   W-pI.51.5. (5) I am never upset for the reason I think. 
44   2 I am never upset for the reason I think because I am constantly trying to justify my 
45   thoughts. 3 I am constantly trying to make them true. 4 I make all things my enemies, so that 
46   my anger is justified and my attacks are warranted. 5 I have not realized how much I have
47   misused everything I see by assigning this role to it. 6 I have done this to defend a 
48   thought system that has hurt me, and that I no longer want. 7 I am willing to let it go.
49   
50   
0449
 1   
 2   LESSON 52.
 3   
 4   Today's review covers these ideas:
 5   W-pI.52.1. (6) I am upset because I see what is not there. 
 6   2 Reality is never frightening. 3 It is impossible that it could upset me. 4 Reality 
 7   brings only perfect peace. 5 When I am upset, it is always because I have replaced reality 
 8   with illusions I made up. 6 The illusions are upsetting because I have given them reality, 
 9   and thus regard reality as an illusion. 7 Nothing in God's creation is affected in any way
10   by this confusion of mine. 8 I am always upset by nothing.
11   
12   W-pI.52.2. (7) I see only the past. 
13   2 As I look about, I condemn the world I look upon. 3 I call this seeing. 4 I hold the 
14   past against everyone and everything, making them my enemies. 5 When I have forgiven myself
15   and remembered Who I am, I will bless everyone and everything I see. 6 There will be no
16   past, and therefore no enemies. 7 And I will look with love on all that I failed to see
17   before.
18   
19   W-pI.52.3. (8) My mind is preoccupied with past thoughts. 
20   2 I see only my own thoughts, and my mind is preoccupied with the past. 3 What, then, 
21   can I see as it is? 4 Let me remember that I look on the past to prevent the present from 
22   dawning on my mind. 5 Let me understand that I am trying to use time against God. 6 Let me 
23   learn to give the past away, realizing that in so doing I am giving up nothing.
24   
25   W-pI.52.4. (9) I see nothing as it is now. 
26   2 If I see nothing as it is now, it can truly be said that I see nothing. 3 I can see 
27   only what is now. 4 The choice is not whether to see the past or the present; the choice is
28   merely whether to see or not. 5 What I have chosen to see has cost me vision. 6 Now I 
29   would choose again, that I may see.
30   
31   W-pI.52.5. (10) My thoughts do not mean anything. 
32   2 I have no private thoughts. 3 Yet it is only private thoughts of which I am aware. 4 
33   What can these thoughts mean? 5 They do not exist, and so they mean nothing. 6 Yet my mind 
34   is part of creation and part of its Creator. 7 Would I not rather join the thinking of 
35   the universe than to obscure all that is really mine with my pitiful and meaningless "
36   private" thoughts?
37   
38   
39   
40   LESSON 53.
41   
42   Today we will review the following:
43   W-pI.53.1. (11) My meaningless thoughts are showing me a meaningless world. 
44   2 Since the thoughts of which I am aware do not mean anything, the world that pictures 
45   them can have no meaning. 3 What is producing this world is insane, and so is what it 
46   produces. 4 Reality is not insane, and I have real thoughts as well as insane ones. 5 I can 
47   therefore see a real world, if I look to my real thoughts as my guide for seeing.
48   
49   W-pI.53.2. (12) I am upset because I see a meaningless world. 
50   2 Insane thoughts are upsetting. 3 They produce a world in which there is no order 
0450
 1   anywhere. 4 Only chaos rules a world that represents chaotic thinking, and chaos has no laws. 5
 2   I cannot live in peace in such a world. 6 I am grateful that this world is not real, 
 3   and that I need not see it at all unless I choose to value it. 7 And I do not choose to 
 4   value what is totally insane and has no meaning.
 5   
 6   W-pI.53.3. (13) A meaningless world engenders fear. 
 7   2 The totally insane engenders fear because it is completely undependable, and offers 
 8   no grounds for trust. 3 Nothing in madness is dependable. 4 It holds out no safety and no
 9   hope. 5 But such a world is not real. 6 I have given it the illusion of reality, and 
10   have suffered from my belief in it. 7 Now I choose to withdraw this belief, and place my 
11   trust in reality. 8 In choosing this, I will escape all the effects of the world of fear, 
12   because I am acknowledging that it does not exist.
13   
14   W-pI.53.4. (14) God did not create a meaningless world. 
15   2 How can a meaningless world exist if God did not create it? 3 He is the Source of all
16   meaning, and everything that is real is in His Mind. 4 It is in my mind too, because He
17   created it with me. 5 Why should I continue to suffer from the effects of my own insane
18   thoughts, when the perfection of creation is my home? 6 Let me remember the power of my
19   decision, and recognize where I really abide.
20   
21   W-pI.53.5. (15) My thoughts are images that I have made. 
22   2 Whatever I see reflects my thoughts. 3 It is my thoughts that tell me where I am and 
23   what I am. 4 The fact that I see a world in which there is suffering and loss and death 
24   shows me that I am seeing only the representation of my insane thoughts, and am not allowing
25   my real thoughts to cast their beneficent light on what I see. 5 Yet God's way is sure.
26   6 The images I have made cannot prevail against Him because it is not my will that they
27   do so. 7 My will is His, and I will place no other gods before Him.
28   
29   
30   
31   LESSON 54.
32   
33   These are the review ideas for today:
34   W-pI.54.1. (16) I have no neutral thoughts. 
35   2 Neutral thoughts are impossible because all thoughts have power. 3 They will either 
36   make a false world or lead me to the real one. 4 But thoughts cannot be without effects. 5 
37   As the world I see arises from my thinking errors, so will the real world rise before my 
38   eyes as I let my errors be corrected. 6 My thoughts cannot be neither true nor false. 7 
39   They must be one or the other. 8 What I see shows me which they are.
40   
41   W-pI.54.2. (17) I see no neutral things. 
42   2 What I see witnesses to what I think. 3 If I did not think I would not exist, because
43   life is thought. 4 Let me look on the world I see as the representation of my own state
44   of mind. 5 I know that my state of mind can change. 6 And so I also know the world I 
45   see can change as well.
46   
47   W-pI.54.3. (18) I am not alone in experiencing the effects of my seeing. 
48   2 If I have no private thoughts, I cannot see a private world. 3 Even the mad idea of 
49   separation had to be shared before it could form the basis of the world I see. 4 Yet that sharing
50   was a sharing of nothing. 5 I can also call upon my real thoughts, which share 
0451
 1   everything with everyone. 6 As my thoughts of separation call to the separation thoughts of 
 2   others, so my real thoughts awaken the real thoughts in them. 7 And the world my real 
 3   thoughts show me will dawn on their sight as well as mine.
 4   
 5   W-pI.54.4. (19) I am not alone in experiencing the effects of my thoughts. 
 6   2 I am alone in nothing. 3 Everything I think or say or do teaches all the universe. 4 
 7   A Son of God cannot think or speak or act in vain. 5 He cannot be alone in anything. 6 
 8   It is therefore in my power to change every mind along with mine, for mine is the power 
 9   of God.
10   
11   W-pI.54.5. (20) I am determined to see. 2 Recognizing the shared nature of my thoughts,
12   I am determined to see. 3 I would look upon the witnesses that show me the thinking of 
13   the world has been changed. 4 I would behold the proof that what has been done through me 
14   has enabled love to replace fear, laughter to replace tears, and abundance to replace loss.
15    5 I would look upon the real world, and let it teach me that my will and the Will of 
16   God are one.
17   
18   
19   
20   LESSON 55.
21   
22   Today's review includes the following:
23   W-pI.55.1. (21) I am determined to see things differently. 
24   2 What I see now are but signs of disease, disaster and death. 3 This cannot be what 
25   God created for His beloved Son. 4 The very fact that I see such things is proof that I do
26   not understand God. 5 Therefore I also do not understand His Son. 6 What I see tells me
27   that I do not know who I am. 7 I am determined to see the witnesses to the truth in me,
28   rather than those which show me an illusion of myself.
29   
30   W-pI.55.2. (22) What I see is a form of vengeance. 
31   2 The world I see is hardly the representation of loving thoughts. 3 It is a picture of
32   attack on everything by everything. 4 It is anything but a reflection of the Love of 
33   God and the love of His Son. 5 It is my own attack thoughts that give rise to this picture.
34    6 My loving thoughts will save me from this perception of the world, and give me the 
35   peace God intended me to have.
36   
37   W-pI.55.3. (23) I can escape from this world by giving up attack thoughts. 
38   2 Herein lies salvation, and nowhere else. 3 Without attack thoughts I could not see a 
39   world of attack. 4 As forgiveness allows love to return to my awareness, I will see a world 
40   of peace and safety and joy. 5 And it is this I choose to see, in place of what I look on
41   now.
42   
43   W-pI.55.4. (24) I do not perceive my own best interests. 
44   2 How could I recognize my own best interests when I do not know who I am? 3 What I 
45   think are my best interests would merely bind me closer to the world of illusions. 4 I am 
46   willing to follow the Guide God has given me to find out what my own best interests are, 
47   recognizing that I cannot perceive them by myself.
48   
49   W-pI.55.5. (25) I do not know what anything is for. 
50   2 To me, the purpose of everything is to prove that my illusions about myself are real.
0452
 1   3 It is for this purpose that I attempt to use everyone and everything. 4 It is for 
 2   this that I believe the world is for. 5 Therefore I do not recognize its real purpose. 6 
 3   The purpose I have given the world has led to a frightening picture of it. 7 Let me open 
 4   my mind to the world's real purpose by withdrawing the one I have given it, and learning 
 5   the truth about it.
 6   
 7   
