12   LESSON 66.
13   
14   My happiness and my function are one.
15   W-pI.66.1. You have surely noticed an emphasis throughout our recent lessons on the 
16   connection between fulfilling your function and achieving happiness. 2 This is because you do not
17   really see the connection. 3 Yet there is more than just a connection between them; 
18   they are the same. 4 Their forms are different, but their content is completely one.
19   W-pI.66.2. The ego does constant battle with the Holy Spirit on the fundamental 
20   question of what your function is. 2 So does it do constant battle with the Holy Spirit about 
21   what your happiness is. 3 It is not a two-way battle. 4 The ego attacks and the Holy Spirit
22   does not respond. 5 He knows what your function is. 6 He knows that it is your 
23   happiness.
24   W-pI.66.3. Today we will try to go past this wholly meaningless battle and arrive at 
25   the truth about your function. 2 We will not engage in senseless arguments about what it 
26   is. 3 We will not become hopelessly involved in defining happiness and determining the 
27   means for achieving it. 4 We will not indulge the ego by listening to its attacks on truth. 
28   5 We will merely be glad that we can find out what truth is.
29   W-pI.66.4. Our longer practice period today has as its purpose your acceptance of the 
30   fact that not only is there a very real connection between the function God gave you and 
31   your happiness, but that they are actually identical. 2 God gives you only happiness. 3 
32   Therefore, the function He gave you must be happiness, even if it appears to be different. 4 
33   Today's exercises are an attempt to go beyond these differences in appearance, and recognize a
34   common content where it exists in truth.
35   W-pI.66.5. Begin the ten-to-fifteen-minute practice period by reviewing these thoughts:
36   
37   
38   2 God gives me only happiness. 
39   3 He has given my function to me. 
40   4 Therefore my function must be happiness. 
41   
42   5 Try to see the logic in this sequence, even if you do not yet accept the conclusion. 
43   6 It is only if the first two thoughts are wrong that the conclusion could be false. 7 
44   Let us, then, think about the premises for a while, as we are practicing.
45   W-pI.66.6. The first premise is that God gives you only happiness. 2 This could be 
46   false, of course, but in order to be false it is necessary to define God as something He is 
47   not. 3 Love cannot give evil, and what is not happiness is evil. 4 God cannot give what He
48   does not have, and He cannot have what He is not. 5 Unless God gives you only happiness,
49    He must be evil. 6 And it is this definition of Him you are believing if you do not 
50   accept the first premise.
0461
 1   W-pI.66.7. The second premise is that God has given you your function. 2 We have seen 
 2   that there are only two parts of your mind. 3 One is ruled by the ego, and is made up of 
 3   illusions. 4 The other is the home of the Holy Spirit, where truth abides. 5 There are no other 
 4   guides but these to choose between, and no other outcomes possible as a result of your choice
 5   but the fear that the ego always engenders, and the love that the Holy Spirit always 
 6   offers to replace it.
 7   W-pI.66.8. Thus, it must be that your function is established by God through His Voice,
 8   or is made by the ego which you have made to replace Him. 2 Which is true? 3 Unless God
 9   gave your function to you, it must be the gift of the ego. 4 Does the ego really have 
10   gifts to give, being itself an illusion and offering only the illusion of gifts?
11   W-pI.66.9. Think about this during the longer practice period today. 2 Think also about
12   the many forms the illusion of your function has taken in your mind, and the many ways 
13   in which you tried to find salvation under the ego's guidance. 3 Did you find it? 4 Were 
14   you happy? 5 Did they bring you peace? 6 We need great honesty today. 7 Remember the 
15   outcomes fairly, and consider also whether it was ever reasonable to expect happiness from 
16   anything the ego ever proposed. 8 Yet the ego is the only alternative to the Holy Spirit's 
17   Voice.
18   W-pI.66.10. You will listen to madness or hear the truth. 2 Try to make this choice as 
19   you think about the premises on which our conclusion rests. 3 We can share in this 
20   conclusion, but in no other. 4 For God Himself shares it with us. 5 Today's idea is another giant
21   stride in the perception of the same as the same, and the different as different. 6 On 
22   one side stand all illusions. 7 All truth stands on the other. 8 Let us try today to 
23   realize that only the truth is true.
24   W-pI.66.11. In the shorter practice periods, which would be most helpful today if 
25   undertaken twice an hour, this form of the application is suggested: 
26   
27   2 My happiness and function are one, because God has given me both. 
28   
29   3 It will not take more than a minute, and probably less, to repeat these words slowly 
30   and think about them a little while as you say them.
31   
32   
33   
34   LESSON 67.
35   
36   Love created me like itself.
37   W-pI.67.1. Today's idea is a complete and accurate statement of what you are. 2 This is
38   why you are the light of the world. 3 This is why God appointed you as the world's 
39   savior. 4 This is why the Son of God looks to you for his salvation. 5 He is saved by what 
40   you are. 6 We will make every effort today to reach this truth about you, and to realize 
41   fully, if only for a moment, that it is the truth.
42   W-pI.67.2. In the longer practice period, we will think about your reality and its 
43   wholly unchanged and unchangeable nature. 2 We will begin by repeating this truth about you, 
44   and then spend a few minutes adding some relevant thoughts, such as: 
45   
46   3 Holiness created me holy. 
47   4 Kindness created me kind. 
48   5 Helpfulness created me helpful. 
49   6 Perfection created me perfect. 
50   
0462
 1   7 Any attribute which is in accord with God as He defines Himself is appropriate for 
 2   use. 8 We are trying today to undo your definition of God and replace it with His Own. 9 
 3   We are also trying to emphasize that you are part of His definition of Himself.
 4   W-pI.67.3. After you have gone over several such related thoughts, try to let all 
 5   thoughts drop away for a brief preparatory interval, and then try to reach past all your images
 6   and preconceptions about yourself to the truth in you. 2 If love created you like 
 7   itself, this Self must be in you. 3 And somewhere in your mind It is there for you to find.
 8   W-pI.67.4. You may find it necessary to repeat the idea for today from time to time to 
 9   replace distracting thoughts. 2 You may also find that this is not sufficient, and that you 
10   need to continue adding other thoughts related to the truth about yourself. 3 Yet perhaps 
11   you will succeed in going past that, and through the interval of thoughtlessness to the 
12   awareness of a blazing light in which you recognize yourself as love created you. 4 Be confident
13   that you will do much today to bring that awareness nearer, whether you feel you have 
14   succeeded or not.
15   W-pI.67.5. It will be particularly helpful today to practice the idea for the day as 
16   often as you can. 2 You need to hear the truth about yourself as frequently as possible, 
17   because your mind is so preoccupied with false self-images. 3 Four or five times an hour, and 
18   perhaps even more, it would be most beneficial to remind yourself that love created you like 
19   itself. 4 Hear the truth about yourself in this.
20   W-pI.67.6. Try to realize in the shorter practice periods that this is not your tiny, 
21   solitary voice that tells you this. 2 This is the Voice for God, reminding you of your Father 
22   and of your Self. 3 This is the Voice of truth, replacing everything that the ego tells 
23   you about yourself with the simple truth about the Son of God. 4 You were created by love 
24   like itself.
