28   LESSON 68.
29   
30   Love holds no grievances.
31   W-pI.68.1. You who were created by love like itself can hold no grievances and know 
32   your Self. 2 To hold a grievance is to forget who you are. 3 To hold a grievance is to see 
33   yourself as a body. 4 To hold a grievance is to let the ego rule your mind and to condemn the 
34   body to death. 5 Perhaps you do not yet fully realize just what holding grievances does to 
35   your mind. 6 It seems to split you off from your Source and make you unlike Him. 7 It makes
36   you believe that He is like what you think you have become, for no one can conceive of 
37   his Creator as unlike himself.
38   W-pI.68.2. Shut off from your Self, which remains aware of Its likeness to Its Creator,
39   your Self seems to sleep, while the part of your mind that weaves illusions in its 
40   sleep appears to be awake. 2 Can all this arise from holding grievances? 3 Oh, yes! 4 For he
41   who holds grievances denies he was created by love, and his Creator has become fearful 
42   to him in his dream of hate. 5 Who can dream of hatred and not fear God?
43   W-pI.68.3. It is as sure that those who hold grievances will redefine God in their own 
44   image, as it is certain that God created them like Himself, and defined them as part of Him.
45   2 It is as sure that those who hold grievances will suffer guilt, as it is certain that
46   those who forgive will find peace. 3 It is as sure that those who hold grievances will 
47   forget who they are, as it is certain that those who forgive will remember.
48   W-pI.68.4. Would you not be willing to relinquish your grievances if you believed all 
49   this were so? 2 Perhaps you do not think you can let your grievances go. 3 That, however, 
50   is simply a matter of motivation. 4 Today we will try to find out how you would feel 
0463
 1   without them. 5 If you succeed even by ever so little, there will never be a problem in 
 2   motivation ever again.
 3   W-pI.68.5. Begin today's extended practice period by searching your mind for those 
 4   against whom you hold what you regard as major grievances. 2 Some of these will be quite easy 
 5   to find. 3 Then think of the seemingly minor grievances you hold against those you like 
 6   and even think you love. 4 It will quickly become apparent that there is no one against 
 7   whom you do not cherish grievances of some sort. 5 This has left you alone in all the 
 8   universe in your perception of yourself.
 9   W-pI.68.6. Determine now to see all these people as friends. 2 Say to them all, 
10   thinking of each one in turn as you do so: 
11   
12   3 I would see you as my friend, that I may remember you are part of me and come to know
13   myself. 
14   
15   4 Spend the remainder of the practice period trying to think of yourself as completely 
16   at peace with everyone and everything, safe in a world that protects you and loves you, 
17   and that you love in return. 5 Try to feel safety surrounding you, hovering over you and 
18   holding you up. 6 Try to believe, however briefly, that nothing can harm you in any way. 7 At 
19   the end of the practice period tell yourself: 
20   
21   8 Love holds no grievances. 9 When I let all my grievances go I will know I am 
22   perfectly safe.
23   
24   W-pI.68.7. The short practice periods should include a quick application of today's 
25   idea in this form, whenever any thought of grievance arises against anyone, physically 
26   present or not: 
27   
28   2 Love holds no grievances. 3 Let me not betray my Self. 
29   
30   4 In addition, repeat the idea several times an hour in this form: 
31   
32   5 Love holds no grievances. 6 I would wake to my Self by laying all my grievances aside
33   and wakening in Him.
