20   LESSON 71.
21   
22   Only God's plan for salvation will work.
23   W-pI.71.1. You may not realize that the ego has set up a plan for salvation in 
24   opposition to God's. 2 It is this plan in which you believe. 3 Since it is the opposite of God's,
25   you also believe that to accept God's plan in place of the ego's is to be damned. 4 
26   This sounds preposterous, of course. 5 Yet after we have considered just what the ego's 
27   plan is, perhaps you will realize that, however preposterous it may be, you do believe in 
28   it.
29   W-pI.71.2. The ego's plan for salvation centers around holding grievances. 2 It 
30   maintains that, if someone else spoke or acted differently, if some external circumstance or 
31   event were changed, you would be saved. 3 Thus, the source of salvation is constantly 
32   perceived as outside yourself. 4 Each grievance you hold is a declaration, and an assertion in 
33   which you believe, that says, "If this were different, I would be saved." 5 The change of 
34   mind necessary for salvation is thus demanded of everyone and everything except yourself.
35   W-pI.71.3. The role assigned to your own mind in this plan, then, is simply to 
36   determine what, other than itself, must change if you are to be saved. 2 According to this 
37   insane plan, any perceived source of salvation is acceptable provided that it will not work. 
38   3 This ensures that the fruitless search will continue, for the illusion persists that, 
39   although this hope has always failed, there is still grounds for hope in other places and in 
40   other things. 4 Another person will yet serve better; another situation will yet offer 
41   success.
42   W-pI.71.4. Such is the ego's plan for your salvation. 2 Surely you can see how it is in
43   strict accord with the ego's basic doctrine, "Seek but do not find." 3 For what could 
44   more surely guarantee that you will not find salvation than to channelize all your efforts 
45   in searching for it where it is not?
46   W-pI.71.5. God's plan for salvation works simply because, by following His direction, 
47   you seek for salvation where it is. 2 But if you are to succeed, as God promises you will,
48   you must be willing to seek there only. 3 Otherwise, your purpose is divided and you 
49   will attempt to follow two plans for salvation that are diametrically opposed in all ways. 
50   4 The result can only bring confusion, misery and a deep sense of failure and despair.
0467
 1   W-pI.71.6. How can you escape all this? 2 Very simply. 3 The idea for today is the 
 2   answer. 4 Only God's plan for salvation will work. 5 There can be no real conflict about this,
 3    because there is no possible alternative to God's plan that will save you. 6 His is 
 4   the only plan that is certain in its outcome. 7 His is the only plan that must succeed.
 5   W-pI.71.7. Let us practice recognizing this certainty today. 2 And let us rejoice that 
 6   there is an answer to what seems to be a conflict with no resolution possible. 3 All things 
 7   are possible to God. 4 Salvation must be yours because of His plan, which cannot fail.
 8   W-pI.71.8. Begin the two longer practice periods for today by thinking about today's 
 9   idea, and realizing that it contains two parts, each making equal contribution to the whole.
10    2 God's plan for your salvation will work, and other plans will not. 3 Do not allow 
11   yourself to become depressed or angry at the second part; it is inherent in the first. 4 And in
12   the first is your full release from all your own insane attempts and mad proposals to 
13   free yourself. 5 They have led to depression and anger; but God's plan will succeed. 6 It 
14   will lead to release and joy.
15   W-pI.71.9. Remembering this, let us devote the remainder of the extended practice 
16   periods to asking God to reveal His plan to us. 2 Ask Him very specifically: 
17   
18   3 What would You have me do? 
19   4 Where would You have me go? 
20   5 What would You have me say, and to whom? 
21   
22   6 Give Him full charge of the rest of the practice period, and let Him tell you what 
23   needs to be done by you in His plan for your salvation. 7 He will answer in proportion to 
24   your willingness to hear His Voice. 8 Refuse not to hear. 9 The very fact that you are 
25   doing the exercises proves that you have some willingness to listen. 10 This is enough to 
26   establish your claim to God's answer.
27   W-pI.71.10. In the shorter practice periods, tell yourself often that God's plan for 
28   salvation, and only His, will work. 2 Be alert to all temptation to hold grievances today, and 
29   respond to them with this form of today's idea: 
30   
31   3 Holding grievances is the opposite of God's plan for salvation. 4 And only His plan 
32   will work. 
33   
34   5 Try to remember today's idea some six or seven times an hour. 6 There could be no 
35   better way to spend a half minute or less than to remember the Source of your salvation, and 
36   to see It where It is.
37   
38   
39   
40   LESSON 72.
41   
42   Holding grievances is an attack on God's plan for salvation.
43   W-pI.72.1. While we have recognized that the ego's plan for salvation is the opposite 
44   of God's, we have not yet emphasized that it is an active attack on His plan, and a 
45   deliberate attempt to destroy it. 2 In the attack, God is assigned the attributes which are 
46   actually associated with the ego, while the ego appears to take on the attributes of God.
47   W-pI.72.2. The ego's fundamental wish is to replace God. 2 In fact, the ego is the 
48   physical embodiment of that wish. 3 For it is that wish that seems to surround the mind with a 
49   body, keeping it separate and alone, and unable to reach other minds except through the 
50   body that was made to imprison it. 4 The limit on communication cannot be the best means to
0468
 1   expand communication. 5 Yet the ego would have you believe that it is.
 2   W-pI.72.3. Although the attempt to keep the limitations that a body would impose is 
 3   obvious here, it is perhaps not so apparent why holding grievances is an attack on God's plan 
 4   for salvation. 2 But let us consider the kinds of things you are apt to hold grievances 
 5   for. 3 Are they not always associated with something a body does? 4 A person says 
 6   something you do not like. 5 He does something that displeases you. 6 He "betrays" his hostile 
 7   thoughts in his behavior.
 8   W-pI.72.4. You are not dealing here with what the person is. 2 On the contrary, you are
 9   exclusively concerned with what he does in a body. 3 You are doing more than failing to
10   help in freeing him from the body's limitations. 4 You are actively trying to hold him 
11   to it by confusing it with him, and judging them as one. 5 Herein is God attacked, for if
12   His Son is only a body, so must He be as well. 6 A creator wholly unlike his creation 
13   is inconceivable.
14   W-pI.72.5. If God is a body, what must His plan for salvation be? 2 What could it be 
15   but death? 3 In trying to present Himself as the Author of life and not of death, He is a 
16   liar and a deceiver, full of false promises and offering illusions in place of truth. 4 The
17   body's apparent reality makes this view of God quite convincing. 5 In fact, if the body
18   were real, it would be difficult indeed to escape this conclusion. 6 And every 
19   grievance that you hold insists that the body is real. 7 It overlooks entirely what your brother
20   is. 8 It reinforces your belief that he is a body, and condemns him for it. 9 And it 
21   asserts that his salvation must be death, projecting this attack onto God, and holding Him 
22   responsible for it.
23   W-pI.72.6. To this carefully prepared arena, where angry animals seek for prey and 
24   mercy cannot enter, the ego comes to save you. 2 God made you a body. 3 Very well. 4 Let us 
25   accept this and be glad. 5 As a body, do not let yourself be deprived of what the body offers.
26    6 Take the little you can get. 7 God gave you nothing. 8 The body is your only savior.
27   9 It is the death of God and your salvation.
28   W-pI.72.7. This is the universal belief of the world you see. 2 Some hate the body, and
29   try to hurt and humiliate it. 3 Others love the body, and try to glorify and exalt it. 
30   4 But while the body stands at the center of your concept of yourself, you are attacking
31   God's plan for salvation, and holding your grievances against Him and His creation, 
32   that you may not hear the Voice of truth and welcome It as Friend. 5 Your chosen savior 
33   takes His place instead. 6 It is your friend; He is your enemy.
34   W-pI.72.8. We will try today to stop these senseless attacks on salvation. 2 We will 
35   try to welcome it instead. 3 Your upside-down perception has been ruinous to your peace of
36   mind. 4 You have seen yourself in a body and the truth outside you, locked away from 
37   your awareness by the body's limitations. 5 Now we are going to try to see this differently.
38   
39   W-pI.72.9. The light of truth is in us, where it was placed by God. 2 It is the body 
40   that is outside us, and is not our concern. 3 To be without a body is to be in our natural 
41   state. 4 To recognize the light of truth in us is to recognize ourselves as we are. 5 To see
42   our Self as separate from the body is to end the attack on God's plan for salvation, 
43   and to accept it instead. 6 And wherever His plan is accepted, it is accomplished already.
44   W-pI.72.10. Our goal in the longer practice periods today is to become aware that God's
45   plan for salvation has already been accomplished in us. 2 To achieve this goal, we must
46   replace attack with acceptance. 3 As long as we attack it, we cannot understand what 
47   God's plan for us is. 4 We are therefore attacking what we do not recognize. 5 Now we are 
48   going to try to lay judgment aside, and ask what God's plan for us is: 
49   
50   6 What is salvation, Father? 7 I do not know. 8 Tell me, that I may understand. 
0469
 1   
 2   9 Then we will wait in quiet for His answer. 10 We have attacked God's plan for 
 3   salvation without waiting to hear what it is. 11 We have shouted our grievances so loudly that 
 4   we have not listened to His Voice. 12 We have used our grievances to close our eyes and 
 5   stop our ears.
 6   W-pI.72.11. Now we would see and hear and learn. 2 "What is salvation, Father?" 3 Ask 
 7   and you will be answered. 4 Seek and you will find. 5 We are no longer asking the ego what
 8   salvation is and where to find it. 6 We are asking it of truth. 7 Be certain, then, 
 9   that the answer will be true because of Whom you ask.
10   W-pI.72.12. Whenever you feel your confidence wane and your hope of success flicker and
11   go out, repeat your question and your request, remembering that you are asking of the 
12   infinite Creator of infinity, Who created you like Himself: 
13   
14   2 What is salvation, Father? 3 I do not know. 4 Tell me, that I may understand. 
15   
16   5 He will answer. 6 Be determined to hear.
17   W-pI.72.13. One or perhaps two shorter practice periods an hour will be enough for 
18   today, since they will be somewhat longer than usual. 2 These exercises should begin with 
19   this: 
20   
21   3 Holding grievances is an attack on God's plan for salvation. 4 Let me accept it 
22   instead. 5 What is salvation, Father? 
23   
24   6 Then wait a minute or so in silence, preferably with your eyes closed, and listen for
25   His answer.
26   
