42   LESSON 95.
43   
44   I am one Self, united with my Creator.
45   W-pI.95.1. Today's idea accurately describes you as God created you. 2 You are one 
46   within yourself, and one with Him. 3 Yours is the unity of all creation. 4 Your perfect unity
47   makes change in you impossible. 5 You do not accept this, and you fail to realize it 
48   must be so, only because you believe that you have changed yourself already.
49   W-pI.95.2. You see yourself as a ridiculous parody on God's creation; weak, vicious, 
50   ugly and sinful, miserable and beset with pain. 2 Such is your version of yourself; a self 
0491
 1   divided into many warring parts, separate from God, and tenuously held together by its erratic
 2   and capricious maker, to which you pray. 3 It does not hear your prayers, for it is 
 3   deaf. 4 It does not see the oneness in you, for it is blind. 5 It does not understand you 
 4   are the Son of God, for it is senseless and understands nothing.
 5   W-pI.95.3. We will attempt today to be aware only of what can hear and see, and what 
 6   makes perfect sense. 2 We will again direct our exercises towards reaching your one Self, 
 7   which is united with Its Creator. 3 In patience and in hope we try again today.
 8   W-pI.95.4. The use of the first five minutes of every waking hour for practicing the 
 9   idea for the day has special advantages at the stage of learning in which you are at 
10   present. 2 It is difficult at this point not to allow your mind to wander, if it undertakes 
11   extended practice. 3 You have surely realized this by now. 4 You have seen the extent of your 
12   lack of mental discipline, and of your need for mind training. 5 It is necessary that you 
13   be aware of this, for it is indeed a hindrance to your advance.
14   W-pI.95.5. Frequent but shorter practice periods have other advantages for you at this 
15   time. 2 In addition to recognizing your difficulties with sustained attention, you must 
16   also have noticed that, unless you are reminded of your purpose frequently, you tend to 
17   forget about it for long periods of time. 3 You often fail to remember the short applications
18   of the idea for the day, and you have not yet formed the habit of using the idea as an 
19   automatic response to temptation.
20   W-pI.95.6. Structure, then, is necessary for you at this time, planned to include 
21   frequent reminders of your goal and regular attempts to reach it. 2 Regularity in terms of time
22   is not the ideal requirement for the most beneficial form of practice in salvation. 3 
23   It is advantageous, however, for those whose motivation is inconsistent, and who remain 
24   heavily defended against learning.
25   W-pI.95.7. We will, therefore, keep to the five-minutes-an-hour practice periods for a 
26   while, and urge you to omit as few as possible. 2 Using the first five minutes of the hour 
27   will be particularly helpful, since it imposes firmer structure. 3 Do not, however, use 
28   your lapses from this schedule as an excuse not to return to it again as soon as you can. 4
29   There may well be a temptation to regard the day as lost because you have already 
30   failed to do what is required. 5 This should, however, merely be recognized as what it is; a 
31   refusal to let your mistake be corrected, and an unwillingness to try again.
32   W-pI.95.8. The Holy Spirit is not delayed in His teaching by your mistakes. 2 He can be
33   held back only by your unwillingness to let them go. 3 Let us therefore be determined, 
34   particularly for the next week or so, to be willing to forgive ourselves for our lapses in 
35   diligence, and our failures to follow the instructions for practicing the day's idea. 4 This 
36   tolerance for weakness will enable us to overlook it, rather than give it power to delay our 
37   learning. 5 If we give it power to do this, we are regarding it as strength, and are confusing 
38   strength with weakness.
39   W-pI.95.9. When you fail to comply with the requirements of this course, you have 
40   merely made a mistake. 2 This calls for correction, and for nothing else. 3 To allow a 
41   mistake to continue is to make additional mistakes, based on the first and reinforcing it. 4 
42   It is this process that must be laid aside, for it is but another way in which you would 
43   defend illusions against the truth.
44   W-pI.95.10. Let all these errors go by recognizing them for what they are. 2 They are 
45   attempts to keep you unaware you are one Self, united with your Creator, at one with every 
46   aspect of creation, and limitless in power and in peace. 3 This is the truth, and nothing 
47   else is true. 4 Today we will affirm this truth again, and try to reach the place in you in
48   which there is no doubt that only this is true.
49   W-pI.95.11. Begin the practice periods today with this assurance, offered to your mind 
50   with all the certainty that you can give: 
0492
 1   
 2   2 I am one Self, united with my Creator, at one with every aspect of creation, and 
 3   limitless in power and in peace. 
 4   
 5   3 Then close your eyes and tell yourself again, slowly and thoughtfully, attempting to 
 6   allow the meaning of the words to sink into your mind, replacing false ideas: 
 7   
 8   4 I am one Self. 
 9   
10   5 Repeat this several times, and then attempt to feel the meaning that the words convey.
