30   
31   REVIEW III
32   
33   Introduction
34   
35   
36   W-pI.rIII.in.1. Our next review begins today. 2 We will review two recent lessons every
37   day for ten successive days of practicing. 3 We will observe a special format for these
38   practice periods, that you are urged to follow just as closely as you can.
39   W-pI.rIII.in.2. We understand, of course, that it may be impossible for you to 
40   undertake what is suggested here as optimal each day and every hour of the day. 2 Learning will 
41   not be hampered when you miss a practice period because it is impossible at the appointed 
42   time. 3 Nor is it necessary that you make excessive efforts to be sure that you catch up in
43   terms of numbers. 4 Rituals are not our aim, and would defeat our goal.
44   W-pI.rIII.in.3. But learning will be hampered when you skip a practice period because 
45   you are unwilling to devote the time to it that you are asked to give. 2 Do not deceive 
46   yourself in this. 3 Unwillingness can be most carefully concealed behind a cloak of situations 
47   you cannot control. 4 Learn to distinguish situations that are poorly suited to your 
48   practicing from those that you establish to uphold a camouflage for your unwillingness.
49   W-pI.rIII.in.4. Those practice periods that you have lost because you did not want to 
50   do them, for whatever reason, should be done as soon as you have changed your mind about 
0510
 1   your goal. 2 You are unwilling to cooperate in practicing salvation only if it interferes 
 2   with goals you hold more dear. 3 When you withdraw the value given them, allow your 
 3   practice periods to be replacements for your litanies to them. 4 They gave you nothing. 5 But 
 4   your practicing can offer everything to you. 6 And so accept their offering and be at peace.
 5   
 6   W-pI.rIII.in.5. The format you should use for these reviews is this: Devote five 
 7   minutes twice a day, or longer if you would prefer it, to considering the thoughts that are 
 8   assigned. 2 Read over the ideas and comments that are written down for each day's exercise. 3 
 9   And then begin to think about them, while letting your mind relate them to your needs, 
10   your seeming problems and all your concerns.
11   W-pI.rIII.in.6. Place the ideas within your mind, and let it use them as it chooses. 2 
12   Give it faith that it will use them wisely, being helped in its decisions by the One Who 
13   gave the thoughts to you. 3 What can you trust but what is in your mind? 4 Have faith, in 
14   these reviews, the means the Holy Spirit uses will not fail. 5 The wisdom of your mind will 
15   come to your assistance. 6 Give direction at the outset; then lean back in quiet faith, and
16   let the mind employ the thoughts you gave as they were given you for it to use.
17   W-pI.rIII.in.7. You have been given them in perfect trust; in perfect confidence that 
18   you would use them well; in perfect faith that you would see their messages and use them 
19   for yourself. 2 Offer them to your mind in that same trust and confidence and faith. 3 It 
20   will not fail. 4 It is the Holy Spirit's chosen means for your salvation. 5 Since it has 
21   His trust, His means must surely merit yours as well.
22   W-pI.rIII.in.8. We emphasize the benefits to you if you devote the first five minutes 
23   of the day to your reviews, and also give the last five minutes of your waking day to 
24   them. 2 If this cannot be done, at least try to divide them so you undertake one in the 
25   morning, and the other in the hour just before you go to sleep.
26   W-pI.rIII.in.9. The exercises to be done throughout the day are equally important, and 
27   perhaps of even greater value. 2 You have been inclined to practice only at appointed times, 
28   and then go on your way to other things, without applying what you learned to them. 3 As a
29   result, you have gained little reinforcement, and have not given your learning a fair 
30   chance to prove how great are its potential gifts to you. 4 Here is another chance to use it 
31   well.
32   W-pI.rIII.in.10. In these reviews, we stress the need to let your learning not lie idly
33   by between your longer practice periods. 2 Attempt to give your daily two ideas a brief
34   but serious review each hour. 3 Use one on the hour, and the other one a half an hour 
35   later. 4 You need not give more than just a moment to each one. 5 Repeat it, and allow your 
36   mind to rest a little time in silence and in peace. 6 Then turn to other things, but try to
37   keep the thought with you, and let it serve to help you keep your peace throughout the 
38   day as well.
39   W-pI.rIII.in.11. If you are shaken, think of it again. 2 These practice periods are 
40   planned to help you form the habit of applying what you learn each day to everything you do. 3
41   Do not repeat the thought and lay it down. 4 Its usefulness is limitless to you. 5 And 
42   it is meant to serve you in all ways, all times and places, and whenever you need help of
43   any kind. 6 Try, then, to take it with you in the business of the day and make it holy,
44   worthy of God's Son, acceptable to God and to your Self.
45   W-pI.rIII.in.12. Each day's review assignments will conclude with a restatement of the 
46   thought to use each hour, and the one to be applied on each half hour as well. 2 Forget them 
47   not. 3 This second chance with each of these ideas will bring such large advances that we 
48   come from these reviews with learning gains so great we will continue on more solid ground,
49   with firmer footsteps and with stronger faith.
50   W-pI.rIII.in.13. Do not forget how little you have learned. 
0511
 1    2 Do not forget how much you can learn now. 
 2    3 Do not forget your Father's need of you, 
 3    As you review these thoughts He gave to you.
