17   LESSON 126.
18   
19   All that I give is given to myself.
20   W-pI.126.1. Today's idea, completely alien to the ego and the thinking of the world, is
21   crucial to the thought reversal that this course will bring about. 2 If you believed 
22   this statement, there would be no problem in complete forgiveness, certainty of goal, and 
23   sure direction. 3 You would understand the means by which salvation comes to you, and would
24   not hesitate to use it now.
25   W-pI.126.2. Let us consider what you do believe, in place of this idea. 2 It seems to 
26   you that other people are apart from you, and able to behave in ways which have no bearing
27   on your thoughts, nor yours on theirs. 3 Therefore, your attitudes have no effect on 
28   them, and their appeals for help are not in any way related to your own. 4 You further 
29   think that they can sin without affecting your perception of yourself, while you can judge 
30   their sin, and yet remain apart from condemnation and at peace.
31   W-pI.126.3. When you "forgive" a sin, there is no gain to you directly. 2 You give 
32   charity to one unworthy, merely to point out that you are better, on a higher plane than he 
33   whom you forgive. 3 He has not earned your charitable tolerance, which you bestow on one 
34   unworthy of the gift, because his sins have lowered him beneath a true equality with you. 4 He 
35   has no claim on your forgiveness. 5 It holds out a gift to him, but hardly to yourself.
36   W-pI.126.4. Thus is forgiveness basically unsound; a charitable whim, benevolent yet 
37   undeserved, a gift bestowed at times, at other times withheld. 2 Unmerited, withholding it is 
38   just, nor is it fair that you should suffer when it is withheld. 3 The sin that you forgive
39   is not your own. 4 Someone apart from you committed it. 5 And if you then are gracious 
40   unto him by giving him what he does not deserve, the gift is no more yours than was his sin.
41   
42   W-pI.126.5. If this be true, forgiveness has no grounds on which to rest dependably and
43   sure. 2 It is an eccentricity, in which you sometimes choose to give indulgently an 
44   undeserved reprieve. 3 Yet it remains your right to let the sinner not escape the justified 
45   repayment for his sin. 4 Think you the Lord of Heaven would allow the world's salvation to 
46   depend on this? 5 Would not His care for you be small indeed, if your salvation rested on a 
47   whim?
48   W-pI.126.6. You do not understand forgiveness. 2 As you see it, it is but a check upon 
49   overt attack, without requiring correction in your mind. 3 It cannot give you peace as you 
50   perceive it. 4 It is not a means for your release from what you see in someone other than 
0522
 1   yourself. 5 It has no power to restore your unity with him to your awareness. 6 It is not what 
 2   God intended it to be for you.
 3   W-pI.126.7. Not having given Him the gift He asks of you, you cannot recognize His 
 4   gifts, and think He has not given them to you. 2 Yet would He ask you for a gift unless it 
 5   was for you? 3 Could He be satisfied with empty gestures, and evaluate such petty gifts as
 6   worthy of His Son? 4 Salvation is a better gift than this. 5 And true forgiveness, as 
 7   the means by which it is attained, must heal the mind that gives, for giving is receiving.
 8   6 What remains as unreceived has not been given, but what has been given must have been
 9   received.
10   W-pI.126.8. Today we try to understand the truth that giver and receiver are the same. 
11   2 You will need help to make this meaningful, because it is so alien to the thoughts to 
12   which you are accustomed. 3 But the Help you need is there. 4 Give Him your faith today, and
13   ask Him that He share your practicing in truth today. 5 And if you only catch a tiny 
14   glimpse of the release that lies in the idea we practice for today, this is a day of glory for
15   the world.
16   W-pI.126.9. Give fifteen minutes twice today to the attempt to understand today's idea.
17   2 It is the thought by which forgiveness takes its proper place in your priorities. 3 
18   It is the thought that will release your mind from every bar to what forgiveness means, 
19   and let you realize its worth to you.
20   W-pI.126.10. In silence, close your eyes upon the world that does not understand 
21   forgiveness, and seek sanctuary in the quiet place where thoughts are changed and false beliefs 
22   laid by. 2 Repeat today's idea, and ask for help in understanding what it really means. 3 
23   Be willing to be taught. 4 Be glad to hear the Voice of truth and healing speak to you, 
24   and you will understand the words He speaks, and recognize He speaks your words to you.
25   W-pI.126.11. As often as you can, remind yourself you have a goal today; an aim which 
26   makes this day of special value to yourself and all your brothers. 2 Do not let your mind 
27   forget this goal for long, but tell yourself: 
28   
29   3 All that I give is given to myself. 4 The Help I need to learn that this is true is 
30   with me now. 5 And I will trust in Him. 
31   
32   6 Then spend a quiet moment, opening your mind to His correction and His Love. 7 And 
33   what you hear of Him you will believe, for what He gives will be received by you.
34   
35   
