37   LESSON 127.
38   
39   There is no love but God's.
40   W-pI.127.1. Perhaps you think that different kinds of love are possible. 2 Perhaps you 
41   think there is a kind of love for this, a kind for that; a way of loving one, another way of
42   loving still another. 3 Love is one. 4 It has no separate parts and no degrees; no 
43   kinds nor levels, no divergencies and no distinctions. 5 It is like itself, unchanged 
44   throughout. 6 It never alters with a person or a circumstance. 7 It is the Heart of God, and also
45   of His Son.
46   W-pI.127.2. Love's meaning is obscure to anyone who thinks that love can change. 2 He 
47   does not see that changing love must be impossible. 3 And thus he thinks that he can love 
48   at times, and hate at other times. 4 He also thinks that love can be bestowed on one, and
49   yet remain itself although it is withheld from others. 5 To believe these things of 
50   love is not to understand it. 6 If it could make such distinctions, it would have to judge 
0523
 1   between the righteous and the sinner, and perceive the Son of God in separate parts.
 2   W-pI.127.3. Love cannot judge. 2 As it is one itself, it looks on all as one. 3 Its 
 3   meaning lies in oneness. 4 And it must elude the mind that thinks of it as partial or in part.
 4   5 There is no love but God's, and all of love is His. 6 There is no other principle 
 5   that rules where love is not. 7 Love is a law without an opposite. 8 Its wholeness is the 
 6   power holding everything as one, the link between the Father and the Son which holds Them 
 7   Both forever as the same.
 8   W-pI.127.4. No course whose purpose is to teach you to remember what you really are 
 9   could fail to emphasize that there can never be a difference in what you really are and what
10   love is. 2 Love's meaning is your own, and shared by God Himself. 3 For what you are is
11   what He is. 4 There is no love but His, and what He is, is everything there is. 5 There
12   is no limit placed upon Himself, and so are you unlimited as well.
13   W-pI.127.5. No law the world obeys can help you grasp love's meaning. 2 What the world 
14   believes was made to hide love's meaning, and to keep it dark and secret. 3 There is not one 
15   principle the world upholds but violates the truth of what love is, and what you are as well.
16   W-pI.127.6. Seek not within the world to find your Self. 2 Love is not found in 
17   darkness and in death. 3 Yet it is perfectly apparent to the eyes that see and ears that hear 
18   love's Voice. 4 Today we practice making free your mind of all the laws you think you must 
19   obey; of all the limits under which you live, and all the changes that you think are part 
20   of human destiny. 5 Today we take the largest single step this course requests in your 
21   advance towards its established goal.
22   W-pI.127.7. If you achieve the faintest glimmering of what love means today, you have 
23   advanced in distance without measure and in time beyond the count of years to your release. 2 
24   Let us together, then, be glad to give some time to God today, and understand there is no 
25   better use for time than this.
26   W-pI.127.8. For fifteen minutes twice today escape from every law in which you now 
27   believe. 2 Open your mind and rest. 3 The world that seems to hold you prisoner can be escaped
28   by anyone who does not hold it dear. 4 Withdraw all value you have placed upon its 
29   meager offerings and senseless gifts, and let the gift of God replace them all.
30   W-pI.127.9. Call to your Father, certain that His Voice will answer. 2 He Himself has 
31   promised this. 3 And He Himself will place a spark of truth within your mind wherever you give 
32   up a false belief, a dark illusion of your own reality and what love means. 4 He will 
33   shine through your idle thoughts today, and help you understand the truth of love. 5 In 
34   loving gentleness He will abide with you, as you allow His Voice to teach love's meaning to 
35   your clean and open mind. 6 And He will bless the lesson with His Love.
36   W-pI.127.10. Today the legion of the future years of waiting for salvation disappears 
37   before the timelessness of what you learn. 2 Let us give thanks today that we are spared a 
38   future like the past. 3 Today we leave the past behind us, nevermore to be remembered. 4 And 
39   we raise our eyes upon a different present, where a future dawns unlike the past in every
40   attribute.
41   W-pI.127.11. The world in infancy is newly born. 2 And we will watch it grow in health 
42   and strength, to shed its blessing upon all who come to learn to cast aside the world they
43   thought was made in hate to be love's enemy. 3 Now are they all made free, along with 
44   us. 4 Now are they all our brothers in God's Love.
45   W-pI.127.12. We will remember them throughout the day, because we cannot leave a part 
46   of us outside our love if we would know our Self. 2 At least three times an hour think of
47   one who makes the journey with you, and who came to learn what you must learn. 3 And as
48   he comes to mind, give him this message from your Self: 
49   
50   4 I bless you, brother, with the Love of God, which I would share with you. 5 For I 
0524
 1   would learn the joyous lesson that there is no love but God's and yours and mine and 
 2   everyone's.
 3   
 4   
 5   
 6   LESSON 128.
 7   
 8   The world I see holds nothing that I want.
 9   W-pI.128.1. The world you see holds nothing that you need to offer you; nothing that 
10   you can use in any way, nor anything at all that serves to give you joy. 2 Believe this 
11   thought, and you are saved from years of misery, from countless disappointments, and from 
12   hopes that turn to bitter ashes of despair. 3 No one but must accept this thought as true, 
13   if he would leave the world behind and soar beyond its petty scope and little ways.
14   W-pI.128.2. Each thing you value here is but a chain that binds you to the world, and 
15   it will serve no other end but this. 2 For everything must serve the purpose you have 
16   given it, until you see a different purpose there. 3 The only purpose worthy of your mind 
17   this world contains is that you pass it by, without delaying to perceive some hope where 
18   there is none. 4 Be you deceived no more. 5 The world you see holds nothing that you want.
19   W-pI.128.3. Escape today the chains you place upon your mind when you perceive 
20   salvation here. 2 For what you value you make part of you as you perceive yourself. 3 All things
21   you seek to make your value greater in your sight limit you further, hide your worth 
22   from you, and add another bar across the door that leads to true awareness of your Self.
23   W-pI.128.4. Let nothing that relates to body thoughts delay your progress to salvation,
24   nor permit temptation to believe the world holds anything you want to hold you back. 2 
25   Nothing is here to cherish. 3 Nothing here is worth one instant of delay and pain; one moment 
26   of uncertainty and doubt. 4 The worthless offer nothing. 5 Certainty of worth can not be 
27   found in worthlessness.
28   W-pI.128.5. Today we practice letting go all thought of values we have given to the 
29   world. 2 We leave it free of purposes we gave its aspects and its phases and its dreams. 3 
30   We hold it purposeless within our minds, and loosen it from all we wish it were. 4 Thus 
31   do we lift the chains that bar the door to freedom from the world, and go beyond all 
32   little values and diminished goals.
33   W-pI.128.6. Pause and be still a little while, and see how far you rise above the world,
34    when you release your mind from chains and let it seek the level where it finds itself
35   at home. 2 It will be grateful to be free a while. 3 It knows where it belongs. 4 But 
36   free its wings, and it will fly in sureness and in joy to join its holy purpose. 5 Let it 
37   rest in its Creator, there to be restored to sanity, to freedom and to love.
38   W-pI.128.7. Give it ten minutes rest three times today. 2 And when your eyes are opened
39   afterwards, you will not value anything you see as much as when you looked at it before.
40    3 Your whole perspective on the world will shift by just a little, every time you let 
41   your mind escape its chains. 4 The world is not where it belongs. 5 And you belong where it
42   would be, and where it goes to rest when you release it from the world. 6 Your Guide is
43   sure. 7 Open your mind to Him. 8 Be still and rest.
44   W-pI.128.8. Protect your mind throughout the day as well. 2 And when you think you see 
45   some value in an aspect or an image of the world, refuse to lay this chain upon your mind, 
46   but tell yourself with quiet certainty: 
47   
48   3 This will not tempt me to delay myself. 
49   4 The world I see holds nothing that I want.
50   
0525
 1   
 2   
 3   LESSON 129.
 4   
 5   Beyond this world there is a world I want.
 6   W-pI.129.1. This is the thought that follows from the one we practiced yesterday. 2 You
 7   cannot stop with the idea the world is worthless, for unless you see that there is 
 8   something else to hope for, you will only be depressed. 3 Our emphasis is not on giving up the 
 9   world, but on exchanging it for what is far more satisfying, filled with joy, and capable of
10   offering you peace. 4 Think you this world can offer that to you?
11   W-pI.129.2. It might be worth a little time to think once more about the value of this 
12   world. 2 Perhaps you will concede there is no loss in letting go all thought of value here. 
13   3 The world you see is merciless indeed, unstable, cruel, unconcerned with you, quick to
14   avenge and pitiless with hate. 4 It gives but to rescind, and takes away all things 
15   that you have cherished for a while. 5 No lasting love is found, for none is here. 6 This 
16   is the world of time, where all things end.
17   W-pI.129.3. Is it a loss to find a world instead where losing is impossible; where love
18   endures forever, hate cannot exist and vengeance has no meaning? 2 Is it loss to find 
19   all things you really want, and know they have no ending and they will remain exactly as 
20   you want them throughout time? 3 Yet even they will be exchanged at last for what we 
21   cannot speak of, for you go from there to where words fail entirely, into a silence where the
22   language is unspoken and yet surely understood.
23   W-pI.129.4. Communication, unambiguous and plain as day, remains unlimited for all 
24   eternity. 2 And God Himself speaks to His Son, as His Son speaks to Him. 3 Their language has 
25   no words, for what They say cannot be symbolized. 4 Their knowledge is direct and wholly 
26   shared and wholly one. 5 How far away from this are you who stay bound to this world. 6 And 
27   yet how near are you, when you exchange it for the world you want.
28   W-pI.129.5. Now is the last step certain; now you stand an instant's space away from 
29   timelessness. 2 Here can you but look forward, never back to see again the world you do not want. 3
30   Here is the world that comes to take its place, as you unbind your mind from little 
31   things the world sets forth to keep you prisoner. 4 Value them not, and they will disappear. 
32   5 Esteem them, and they will seem real to you.
33   W-pI.129.6. Such is the choice. 2 What loss can be for you in choosing not to value 
34   nothingness? 3 This world holds nothing that you really want, but what you choose instead you want
35   indeed! 4 Let it be given you today. 5 It waits but for your choosing it, to take the 
36   place of all the things you seek but do not want.
37   W-pI.129.7. Practice your willingness to make this change ten minutes in the morning 
38   and at night, and once more in between. 2 Begin with this: 
39   
40   3 Beyond this world there is a world I want. 4 I choose to see that world instead of 
41   this, for here is nothing that I really want. 
42   
43   5 Then close your eyes upon the world you see, and in the silent darkness watch the 
44   lights that are not of this world light one by one, until where one begins another ends loses
45   all meaning as they blend in one.
46   W-pI.129.8. Today the lights of Heaven bend to you, to shine upon your eyelids as you 
47   rest beyond the world of darkness. 2 Here is light your eyes can not behold. 3 And yet your
48   mind can see it plainly, and can understand. 4 A day of grace is given you today, and 
49   we give thanks. 5 This day we realize that what you feared to lose was only loss.
50   W-pI.129.9. Now do we understand there is no loss. 2 For we have seen its opposite at 
0526
 1   last, and we are grateful that the choice is made. 3 Remember your decision hourly, and 
 2   take a moment to confirm your choice by laying by whatever thoughts you have, and dwelling 
 3   briefly only upon this: 
 4   
 5   4 The world I see holds nothing that I want. 
 6   5 Beyond this world there is a world I want.
 7   
 8   
 9   
10   LESSON 130.
11   
12   It is impossible to see two worlds.
13   W-pI.130.1. Perception is consistent. 2 What you see reflects your thinking. 3 And your
14   thinking but reflects your choice of what you want to see. 4 Your values are 
15   determiners of this, for what you value you must want to see, believing what you see is really 
16   there. 5 No one can see a world his mind has not accorded value. 6 And no one can fail to 
17   look upon what he believes he wants.
18   W-pI.130.2. Yet who can really hate and love at once? 2 Who can desire what he does not
19   want to have reality? 3 And who can choose to see a world of which he is afraid? 4 Fear
20   must make blind, for this its weapon is: That which you fear to see you cannot see. 5 
21   Love and perception thus go hand in hand, but fear obscures in darkness what is there.
22   W-pI.130.3. What, then, can fear project upon the world? 2 What can be seen in darkness
23   that is real? 3 Truth is eclipsed by fear, and what remains is but imagined. 4 Yet what
24   can be real in blind imaginings of panic born? 5 What would you want that this is shown
25   to you? 6 What would you wish to keep in such a dream?
26   W-pI.130.4. Fear has made everything you think you see. 2 All separation, all 
27   distinctions, and the multitude of differences you believe make up the world. 3 They are not there.
28   4 Love's enemy has made them up. 5 Yet love can have no enemy, and so they have no 
29   cause, no being and no consequence. 6 They can be valued, but remain unreal. 7 They can be 
30   sought, but they can not be found. 8 Today we will not seek for them, nor waste this day in 
31   seeking what can not be found.
32   W-pI.130.5. It is impossible to see two worlds which have no overlap of any kind. 2 
33   Seek for the one; the other disappears. 3 But one remains. 4 They are the range of choice 
34   beyond which your decision cannot go. 5 The real and the unreal are all there are to choose 
35   between, and nothing more than these.
36   W-pI.130.6. Today we will attempt no compromise where none is possible. 2 The world you
37   see is proof you have already made a choice as all-embracing as its opposite. 3 What we
38   would learn today is more than just the lesson that you cannot see two worlds. 4 It 
39   also teaches that the one you see is quite consistent from the point of view from which you
40   see it. 5 It is all a piece because it stems from one emotion, and reflects its source 
41   in everything you see.
42   W-pI.130.7. Six times today, in thanks and gratitude, we gladly give five minutes to 
43   the thought that ends all compromise and doubt, and go beyond them all as one. 2 We will 
44   not make a thousand meaningless distinctions, nor attempt to bring with us a little part 
45   of unreality, as we devote our minds to finding only what is real.
46   W-pI.130.8. Begin your searching for the other world by asking for a strength beyond 
47   your own, and recognizing what it is you seek. 2 You do not want illusions. 3 And you come 
48   to these five minutes emptying your hands of all the petty treasures of this world. 4 You
49   wait for God to help you, as you say: 
50   
0527
 1   5 It is impossible to see two worlds. 6 Let me accept the strength God offers me and 
 2   see no value in this world, that I may find my freedom and deliverance.
 3   
 4   W-pI.130.9. God will be there. 2 For you have called upon the great unfailing power 
 5   which will take this giant step with you in gratitude. 3 Nor will you fail to see His thanks
 6   expressed in tangible perception and in truth. 4 You will not doubt what you will look 
 7   upon, for though it is perception, it is not the kind of seeing that your eyes alone have 
 8   ever seen before. 5 And you will know God's strength upheld you as you made this choice.
 9   W-pI.130.10. Dismiss temptation easily today whenever it arises, merely by remembering 
10   the limits of your choice. 2 The unreal or the real, the false or true is what you see and
11   only what you see. 3 Perception is consistent with your choice, and hell or Heaven 
12   comes to you as one.
13   W-pI.130.11. Accept a little part of hell as real, and you have damned your eyes and 
14   cursed your sight, and what you will behold is hell indeed. 2 Yet the release of Heaven still
15   remains within your range of choice, to take the place of everything that hell would 
16   show to you. 3 All you need say to any part of hell, whatever form it takes, is simply this:
17   
18   
19   4 It is impossible to see two worlds. 5 I seek my freedom and deliverance, and this is 
20   not a part of what I want.
21   
22   
23   
24   LESSON 131.
25   
26   No one can fail who seeks to reach the truth.
27   W-pI.131.1. Failure is all about you while you seek for goals that cannot be achieved. 
28   2 You look for permanence in the impermanent, for love where there is none, for safety 
29   in the midst of danger; immortality within the darkness of the dream of death. 3 Who 
30   could succeed where contradiction is the setting of his searching, and the place to which he
31   comes to find stability?
32   W-pI.131.2. Goals that are meaningless are not attained. 2 There is no way to reach 
33   them, for the means by which you strive for them are meaningless as they are. 3 Who can use
34   such senseless means, and hope through them to gain in anything? 4 Where can they lead?
35   5 And what could they achieve that offers any hope of being real? 6 Pursuit of the 
36   imagined leads to death because it is the search for nothingness, and while you seek for life 
37   you ask for death. 7 You look for safety and security, while in your heart you pray for 
38   danger and protection for the little dream you made.
39   W-pI.131.3. Yet searching is inevitable here. 2 For this you came, and you will surely 
40   do the thing you came for. 3 But the world can not dictate the goal for which you search,
41   unless you give it power to do so. 4 Otherwise, you still are free to choose a goal 
42   that lies beyond the world and every worldly thought, and one that comes to you from an 
43   idea relinquished yet remembered, old yet new; an echo of a heritage forgot, yet holding 
44   everything you really want.
45   W-pI.131.4. Be glad that search you must. 2 Be glad as well to learn you search for 
46   Heaven, and must find the goal you really want. 3 No one can fail to want this goal and reach
47   it in the end. 4 God's Son can not seek vainly, though he try to force delay, deceive 
48   himself and think that it is hell he seeks. 5 When he is wrong, he finds correction. 6 When he
49   wanders off, he is led back to his appointed task.
50   W-pI.131.5. No one remains in hell, for no one can abandon his Creator, nor affect His 
0528
 1   perfect, timeless and unchanging Love. 2 You will find Heaven. 3 Everything you seek but this 
 2   will fall away. 4 Yet not because it has been taken from you. 5 It will go because you do 
 3   not want it. 6 You will reach the goal you really want as certainly as God created you in 
 4   sinlessness.
 5   W-pI.131.6. Why wait for Heaven? 2 It is here today. 3 Time is the great illusion it is
 6   past or in the future. 4 Yet this cannot be, if it is where God wills His Son to be. 5 
 7   How could the Will of God be in the past, or yet to happen? 6 What He wills is now, 
 8   without a past and wholly futureless. 7 It is as far removed from time as is a tiny candle 
 9   from a distant star, or what you chose from what you really want.
10   W-pI.131.7. Heaven remains your one alternative to this strange world you made and all 
11   its ways; its shifting patterns and uncertain goals, its painful pleasures and its tragic 
12   joys. 2 God made no contradictions. 3 What denies its own existence and attacks itself is 
13   not of Him. 4 He did not make two minds, with Heaven as the glad effect of one, and earth 
14   the other's sorry outcome which is Heaven's opposite in every way.
15   W-pI.131.8. God does not suffer conflict. 2 Nor is His creation split in two. 3 How 
16   could it be His Son could be in hell, when God Himself established him in Heaven? 4 Could he
17   lose what the Eternal Will has given him to be his home forever? 5 Let us not try 
18   longer to impose an alien will upon God's single purpose. 6 He is here because He wills to be,
19    and what He wills is present now, beyond the reach of time.
20   W-pI.131.9. Today we will not choose a paradox in place of truth. 2 How could the Son 
21   of God make time to take away the Will of God? 3 He thus denies himself, and contradicts 
22   what has no opposite. 4 He thinks he made a hell opposing Heaven, and believes that he 
23   abides in what does not exist, while Heaven is the place he cannot find.
24   W-pI.131.10. Leave foolish thoughts like these behind today, and turn your mind to true
25   ideas instead. 2 No one can fail who seeks to reach the truth, and it is truth we seek 
26   to reach today. 3 We will devote ten minutes to this goal three times today, and we will 
27   ask to see the rising of the real world to replace the foolish images that we hold dear, 
28   with true ideas arising in the place of thoughts that have no meaning, no effect, and 
29   neither source nor substance in the truth.
30   W-pI.131.11. This we acknowledge as we start upon our practice periods. 2 Begin with 
31   this: 
32   
33   3 I ask to see a different world, and think a different kind of thought from those I 
34   made. 4 The world I seek I did not make alone, the thoughts I want to think are not my own.
35   
36   
37   5 For several minutes watch your mind and see, although your eyes are closed, the 
38   senseless world you think is real. 6 Review the thoughts as well which are compatible with such 
39   a world, and which you think are true. 7 Then let them go, and sink below them to the 
40   holy place where they can enter not. 8 There is a door beneath them in your mind, which you
41   could not completely lock to hide what lies beyond.
42   W-pI.131.12. Seek for that door and find it. 2 But before you try to open it, remind 
43   yourself no one can fail who seeks to reach the truth. 3 And it is this request you make today.
44   4 Nothing but this has any meaning now; no other goal is valued now nor sought, nothing
45   before this door you really want, and only what lies past it do you seek.
46   W-pI.131.13. Put out your hand, and see how easily the door swings open with your one 
47   intent to go beyond it. 2 Angels light the way, so that all darkness vanishes, and you are 
48   standing in a light so bright and clear that you can understand all things you see. 3 A tiny 
49   moment of surprise, perhaps, will make you pause before you realize the world you see before 
50   you in the light reflects the truth you knew, and did not quite forget in wandering away 
0529
 1   in dreams.
 2   W-pI.131.14. You cannot fail today. 2 There walks with you the Spirit Heaven sent you, 
 3   that you might approach this door some day, and through His aid slip effortlessly past it, 
 4   to the light. 3 Today that day has come. 4 Today God keeps His ancient promise to His 
 5   holy Son, as does His Son remember his to Him. 5 This is a day of gladness, for we come to 
 6   the appointed time and place where you will find the goal of all your searching here, and 
 7   all the seeking of the world, which end together as you pass beyond the door.
 8   W-pI.131.15. Remember often that today should be a time of special gladness, and 
 9   refrain from dismal thoughts and meaningless laments. 2 Salvation's time has come. 3 Today is 
10   set by Heaven itself to be a time of grace for you and for the world. 4 If you forget this
11   happy fact, remind yourself with this: 
12   
13   5 Today I seek and find all that I want. 
14   6 My single purpose offers it to me. 
15   7 No one can fail who seeks to reach the truth.
16   
17   
18   
19   LESSON 132.
20   
21   I loose the world from all I thought it was.
22   W-pI.132.1. What keeps the world in chains but your beliefs? 2 And what can save the 
23   world except your Self? 3 Belief is powerful indeed. 4 The thoughts you hold are mighty, and
24   illusions are as strong in their effects as is the truth. 5 A madman thinks the world 
25   he sees is real, and does not doubt it. 6 Nor can he be swayed by questioning his 
26   thoughts' effects. 7 It is but when their source is raised to question that the hope of freedom 
27   comes to him at last.
28   W-pI.132.2. Yet is salvation easily achieved, for anyone is free to change his mind, 
29   and all his thoughts change with it. 2 Now the source of thought has shifted, for to 
30   change your mind means you have changed the source of all ideas you think or ever thought or 
31   yet will think. 3 You free the past from what you thought before. 4 You free the future 
32   from all ancient thoughts of seeking what you do not want to find.
33   W-pI.132.3. The present now remains the only time. 2 Here in the present is the world 
34   set free. 3 For as you let the past be lifted and release the future from your ancient 
35   fears, you find escape and give it to the world. 4 You have enslaved the world with all your
36   fears, your doubts and miseries, your pain and tears, and all your sorrows press on it,
37   and keep the world a prisoner to your beliefs. 5 Death strikes it everywhere because 
38   you hold the bitter thoughts of death within your mind.
39   W-pI.132.4. The world is nothing in itself. 2 Your mind must give it meaning. 3 And 
40   what you behold upon it are your wishes, acted out so you can look on them and think them 
41   real. 4 Perhaps you think you did not make the world, but came unwillingly to what was made
42   already, hardly waiting for your thoughts to give it meaning. 5 Yet in truth you found 
43   exactly what you looked for when you came.
44   W-pI.132.5. There is no world apart from what you wish, and herein lies your ultimate 
45   release. 2 Change but your mind on what you want to see, and all the world must change 
46   accordingly. 3 Ideas leave not their source. 4 This central theme is often stated in the text, and
47   must be borne in mind if you would understand the lesson for today. 5 It is not pride 
48   which tells you that you made the world you see, and that it changes as you change your mind.
49   
50   W-pI.132.6. But it is pride that argues you have come into a world quite separate from 
0530
 1   yourself, impervious to what you think, and quite apart from what you chance to think it is. 2 
 2   There is no world! 3 This is the central thought the course attempts to teach. 4 Not 
 3   everyone is ready to accept it, and each one must go as far as he can let himself be led along 
 4   the road to truth. 5 He will return and go still farther, or perhaps step back a while and
 5   then return again.
 6   W-pI.132.7. But healing is the gift of those who are prepared to learn there is no 
 7   world, and can accept the lesson now. 2 Their readiness will bring the lesson to them in 
 8   some form which they can understand and recognize. 3 Some see it suddenly on point of death,
 9    and rise to teach it. 4 Others find it in experience that is not of this world, which 
10   shows them that the world does not exist because what they behold must be the truth, and yet
11   it clearly contradicts the world.
12   W-pI.132.8. And some will find it in this course, and in the exercises that we do today.
13    2 Today's idea is true because the world does not exist. 3 And if it is indeed your 
14   own imagining, then you can loose it from all things you ever thought it was by merely 
15   changing all the thoughts that gave it these appearances. 4 The sick are healed as you let go 
16   all thoughts of sickness, and the dead arise when you let thoughts of life replace all 
17   thoughts you ever held of death.
18   W-pI.132.9. A lesson earlier repeated once must now be stressed again, for it contains 
19   the firm foundation for today's idea. 2 You are as God created you. 3 There is no place 
20   where you can suffer, and no time that can bring change to your eternal state. 4 How can a 
21   world of time and place exist, if you remain as God created you?
22   W-pI.132.10. What is the lesson for today except another way of saying that to know 
23   your Self is the salvation of the world? 2 To free the world from every kind of pain is but
24   to change your mind about yourself. 3 There is no world apart from your ideas because 
25   ideas leave not their source, and you maintain the world within your mind in thought.
26   W-pI.132.11. Yet if you are as God created you, you cannot think apart from Him, nor 
27   make what does not share His timelessness and Love. 2 Are these inherent in the world you 
28   see? 3 Does it create like Him? 4 Unless it does, it is not real, and cannot be at all. 5 
29   If you are real the world you see is false, for God's creation is unlike the world in 
30   every way. 6 And as it was His Thought by which you were created, so it is your thoughts 
31   which made it and must set it free, that you may know the Thoughts you share with God.
32   W-pI.132.12. Release the world! 2 Your real creations wait for this release to give you
33   fatherhood, not of illusions, but as God in truth. 3 God shares His Fatherhood with you
34   who are His Son, for He makes no distinctions in what is Himself and what is still 
35   Himself. 4 What He creates is not apart from Him, and nowhere does the Father end, the Son 
36   begin as something separate from Him.
37   W-pI.132.13. There is no world because it is a thought apart from God, and made to 
38   separate the Father and the Son, and break away a part of God Himself and thus destroy His 
39   Wholeness. 2 Can a world which comes from this idea be real? 3 Can it be anywhere? 4 Deny 
40   illusions, but accept the truth. 5 Deny you are a shadow briefly laid upon a dying world. 6 
41   Release your mind, and you will look upon a world released.
42   W-pI.132.14. Today our purpose is to free the world from all the idle thoughts we ever 
43   held about it, and about all living things we see upon it. 2 They can not be there. 3 No 
44   more can we. 4 For we are in the home our Father set for us, along with them. 5 And we who 
45   are as He created us would loose the world this day from every one of our illusions, that 
46   we may be free.
47   W-pI.132.15. Begin the fifteen-minute periods in which we practice twice today with 
48   this: 
49   
50   2 I who remain as God created me would loose the world from all I thought it was. 3 For
0531
 1   I am real because the world is not, and I would know my own reality. 
 2   
 3   4 Then merely rest, alert but with no strain, and let your mind in quietness be changed
 4   so that the world is freed, along with you.
 5   W-pI.132.16. You need not realize that healing comes to many brothers far across the 
 6   world, as well as to the ones you see nearby, as you send out these thoughts to bless the 
 7   world. 2 But you will sense your own release, although you may not fully understand as yet 
 8   that you could never be released alone.
 9   W-pI.132.17. Throughout the day, increase the freedom sent through your ideas to all 
10   the world, and say whenever you are tempted to deny the power of your simple change of 
11   mind: 
12   
13   2 I loose the world from all I thought it was, and choose my own reality instead.
14   
15   
16   
17   LESSON 133.
18   
19   I will not value what is valueless.
20   W-pI.133.1. Sometimes in teaching there is benefit, particularly after you have gone 
21   through what seems theoretical and far from what the student has already learned, to bring him
22   back to practical concerns. 2 This we will do today. 3 We will not speak of lofty, 
23   world-encompassing ideas, but dwell instead on benefits to you.
24   W-pI.133.2. You do not ask too much of life, but far too little. 2 When you let your 
25   mind be drawn to bodily concerns, to things you buy, to eminence as valued by the world, 
26   you ask for sorrow, not for happiness. 3 This course does not attempt to take from you the
27   little that you have. 4 It does not try to substitute utopian ideas for satisfactions 
28   which the world contains. 5 There are no satisfactions in the world.
29   W-pI.133.3. Today we list the real criteria by which to test all things you think you 
30   want. 2 Unless they meet these sound requirements, they are not worth desiring at all, for 
31   they can but replace what offers more. 3 The laws that govern choice you cannot make, no 
32   more than you can make alternatives from which to choose. 4 The choosing you can do; indeed,
33    you must. 5 But it is wise to learn the laws you set in motion when you choose, and 
34   what alternatives you choose between.
35   W-pI.133.4. We have already stressed there are but two, however many there appear to be.
36    2 The range is set, and this we cannot change. 3 It would be most ungenerous to you to
37   let alternatives be limitless, and thus delay your final choice until you had 
38   considered all of them in time; and not been brought so clearly to the place where there is but 
39   one choice that must be made.
40   W-pI.133.5. Another kindly and related law is that there is no compromise in what your 
41   choice must bring. 2 It cannot give you just a little, for there is no in between. 3 Each 
42   choice you make brings everything to you or nothing. 4 Therefore, if you learn the tests by 
43   which you can distinguish everything from nothing, you will make the better choice.
44   W-pI.133.6. First, if you choose a thing that will not last forever, what you chose is 
45   valueless. 2 A temporary value is without all value. 3 Time can never take away a value that is 
46   real. 4 What fades and dies was never there, and makes no offering to him who chooses it. 5
47   He is deceived by nothing in a form he thinks he likes.
48   W-pI.133.7. Next, if you choose to take a thing away from someone else, you will have 
49   nothing left. 2 This is because, when you deny his right to everything, you have denied your 
50   own. 3 You therefore will not recognize the things you really have, denying they are there.
0532
 1    4 Who seeks to take away has been deceived by the illusion loss can offer gain. 5 Yet 
 2   loss must offer loss, and nothing more.
 3   W-pI.133.8. Your next consideration is the one on which the others rest. 2 Why is the 
 4   choice you make of value to you? 3 What attracts your mind to it? 4 What purpose does it 
 5   serve? 5 Here it is easiest of all to be deceived. 6 For what the ego wants it fails to 
 6   recognize. 7 It does not even tell the truth as it perceives it, for it needs to keep the halo 
 7   which it uses to protect its goals from tarnish and from rust, that you may see how "
 8   innocent" it is.
 9   W-pI.133.9. Yet is its camouflage a thin veneer, which could deceive but those who are 
10   content to be deceived. 2 Its goals are obvious to anyone who cares to look for them. 3 Here 
11   is deception doubled, for the one who is deceived will not perceive that he has merely 
12   failed to gain. 4 He will believe that he has served the ego's hidden goals.
13   W-pI.133.10. Yet though he tries to keep its halo clear within his vision, still must 
14   he perceive its tarnished edges and its rusted core. 2 His ineffectual mistakes appear as
15   sins to him, because he looks upon the tarnish as his own; the rust a sign of deep 
16   unworthiness within himself. 3 He who would still preserve the ego's goals and serve them as his 
17   own makes no mistakes, according to the dictates of his guide. 4 This guidance teaches it 
18   is error to believe that sins are but mistakes, for who would suffer for his sins if this
19   were so?
20   W-pI.133.11. And so we come to the criterion for choice that is the hardest to believe,
21   because its obviousness is overlaid with many levels of obscurity. 2 If you feel any 
22   guilt about your choice, you have allowed the ego's goals to come between the real 
23   alternatives. 3 And thus you do not realize there are but two, and the alternative you think you 
24   chose seems fearful, and too dangerous to be the nothingness it actually is.
25   W-pI.133.12. All things are valuable or valueless, worthy or not of being sought at all,
26    entirely desirable or not worth the slightest effort to obtain. 2 Choosing is easy 
27   just because of this. 3 Complexity is nothing but a screen of smoke, which hides the very 
28   simple fact that no decision can be difficult. 4 What is the gain to you in learning this? 5 
29   It is far more than merely letting you make choices easily and without pain.
30   W-pI.133.13. Heaven itself is reached with empty hands and open minds, which come with 
31   nothing to find everything and claim it as their own. 2 We will attempt to reach this state 
32   today, with self-deception laid aside, and with an honest willingness to value but the truly
33   valuable and the real. 3 Our two extended practice periods of fifteen minutes each 
34   begin with this: 
35   
36   4 I will not value what is valueless, and only what has value do I seek, for only that 
37   do I desire to find.
38   
39   W-pI.133.14. And then receive what waits for everyone who reaches, unencumbered, to the
40   gate of Heaven, which swings open as he comes. 2 Should you begin to let yourself 
41   collect some needless burdens, or believe you see some difficult decisions facing you, be 
42   quick to answer with this simple thought: 
43   
44   3 I will not value what is valueless, for what is valuable belongs to me.
45   
46   
47   
48   LESSON 134.
49   
50   Let me perceive forgiveness as it is.
0533
 1   W-pI.134.1. Let us review the meaning of "forgive," for it is apt to be distorted and 
 2   to be perceived as something that entails an unfair sacrifice of righteous wrath, a gift 
 3   unjustified and undeserved, and a complete denial of the truth. 2 In such a view, forgiveness must
 4   be seen as mere eccentric folly, and this course appear to rest salvation on a whim.
 5   W-pI.134.2. This twisted view of what forgiveness means is easily corrected, when you 
 6   can accept the fact that pardon is not asked for what is true. 2 It must be limited to 
 7   what is false. 3 It is irrelevant to everything except illusions. 4 Truth is God's creation,
 8    and to pardon that is meaningless. 5 All truth belongs to Him, reflects His laws and 
 9   radiates His Love. 6 Does this need pardon? 7 How can you forgive the sinless and eternally 
10   benign?
11   W-pI.134.3. The major difficulty that you find in genuine forgiveness on your part is 
12   that you still believe you must forgive the truth, and not illusions. 2 You conceive of 
13   pardon as a vain attempt to look past what is there; to overlook the truth, in an unfounded 
14   effort to deceive yourself by making an illusion true. 3 This twisted viewpoint but reflects 
15   the hold that the idea of sin retains as yet upon your mind, as you regard yourself.
16   W-pI.134.4. Because you think your sins are real, you look on pardon as deception. 2 
17   For it is impossible to think of sin as true and not believe forgiveness is a lie. 3 Thus 
18   is forgiveness really but a sin, like all the rest. 4 It says the truth is false, and 
19   smiles on the corrupt as if they were as blameless as the grass; as white as snow. 5 It is 
20   delusional in what it thinks it can accomplish. 6 It would see as right the plainly wrong; the 
21   loathsome as the good.
22   W-pI.134.5. Pardon is no escape in such a view. 2 It merely is a further sign that sin 
23   is unforgivable, at best to be concealed, denied or called another name, for pardon is a 
24   treachery to truth. 3 Guilt cannot be forgiven. 4 If you sin, your guilt is everlasting. 5 Those
25   who are forgiven from the view their sins are real are pitifully mocked and twice 
26   condemned; first, by themselves for what they think they did, and once again by those who pardon
27   them.
28   W-pI.134.6. It is sin's unreality that makes forgiveness natural and wholly sane, a 
29   deep relief to those who offer it; a quiet blessing where it is received. 2 It does not 
30   countenance illusions, but collects them lightly, with a little laugh, and gently lays them at the
31   feet of truth. 3 And there they disappear entirely.
32   W-pI.134.7. Forgiveness is the only thing that stands for truth in the illusions of the
33   world. 2 It sees their nothingness, and looks straight through the thousand forms in 
34   which they may appear. 3 It looks on lies, but it is not deceived. 4 It does not heed the 
35   self-accusing shrieks of sinners mad with guilt. 5 It looks on them with quiet eyes, and merely says
36   to them, "My brother, what you think is not the truth."
37   W-pI.134.8. The strength of pardon is its honesty, which is so uncorrupted that it sees
38   illusions as illusions, not as truth. 2 It is because of this that it becomes the 
39   undeceiver in the face of lies; the great restorer of the simple truth. 3 By its ability to 
40   overlook what is not there, it opens up the way to truth, which has been blocked by dreams of 
41   guilt. 4 Now are you free to follow in the way your true forgiveness opens up to you. 5 For 
42   if one brother has received this gift of you, the door is open to yourself.
43   W-pI.134.9. There is a very simple way to find the door to true forgiveness, and 
44   perceive it open wide in welcome. 2 When you feel that you are tempted to accuse someone of sin
45   in any form, do not allow your mind to dwell on what you think he did, for that is 
46   self-deception. 3 Ask instead, "Would I accuse myself of doing this?"
47   W-pI.134.10. Thus will you see alternatives for choice in terms that render choosing 
48   meaningful, and keep your mind as free of guilt and pain as God Himself intended it to be, and as
49   it is in truth. 2 It is but lies that would condemn. 3 In truth is innocence the only 
50   thing there is. 4 Forgiveness stands between illusions and the truth; between the world you 
0534
 1   see and that which lies beyond; between the hell of guilt and Heaven's gate.
 2   W-pI.134.11. Across this bridge, as powerful as love which laid its blessing on it, are
 3   all dreams of evil and of hatred and attack brought silently to truth. 2 They are not 
 4   kept to swell and bluster, and to terrify the foolish dreamer who believes in them. 3 He 
 5   has been gently wakened from his dream by understanding what he thought he saw was never 
 6   there. 4 And now he cannot feel that all escape has been denied to him.
 7   W-pI.134.12. He does not have to fight to save himself. 2 He does not have to kill the 
 8   dragons which he thought pursued him. 3 Nor need he erect the heavy walls of stone and iron 
 9   doors he thought would make him safe. 4 He can remove the ponderous and useless armor made 
10   to chain his mind to fear and misery. 5 His step is light, and as he lifts his foot to 
11   stride ahead a star is left behind, to point the way to those who follow him.
12   W-pI.134.13. Forgiveness must be practiced, for the world cannot perceive its meaning, 
13   nor provide a guide to teach you its beneficence. 2 There is no thought in all the world 
14   that leads to any understanding of the laws it follows, nor the Thought that it reflects. 3
15   It is as alien to the world as is your own reality. 4 And yet it joins your mind with 
16   the reality in you.
17   W-pI.134.14. Today we practice true forgiveness, that the time of joining be no more 
18   delayed. 2 For we would meet with our reality in freedom and in peace. 3 Our practicing 
19   becomes the footsteps lighting up the way for all our brothers, who will follow us to the 
20   reality we share with them. 4 That this may be accomplished, let us give a quarter of an hour 
21   twice today, and spend it with the Guide Who understands the meaning of forgiveness, and was
22   sent to us to teach it. 5 Let us ask of Him: 
23   
24   6 Let me perceive forgiveness as it is.
25   
26   W-pI.134.15. Then choose one brother as He will direct, and catalogue his "sins," as 
27   one by one they cross your mind. 2 Be certain not to dwell on any one of them, but realize
28   that you are using his "offenses" but to save the world from all ideas of sin. 3 
29   Briefly consider all the evil things you thought of him, and each time ask yourself, "Would I 
30   condemn myself for doing this?"
31   W-pI.134.16. Let him be freed from all the thoughts you had of sin in him. 2 And now 
32   you are prepared for freedom. 3 If you have been practicing thus far in willingness and 
33   honesty, you will begin to sense a lifting up, a lightening of weight across your chest, a 
34   deep and certain feeling of relief. 4 The time remaining should be given to experiencing 
35   the escape from all the heavy chains you sought to lay upon your brother, but were laid 
36   upon yourself.
37   W-pI.134.17. Forgiveness should be practiced through the day, for there will still be 
38   many times when you forget its meaning and attack yourself. 2 When this occurs, allow your 
39   mind to see through this illusion as you tell yourself: 
40   
41   3 Let me perceive forgiveness as it is. 4 Would I accuse myself of doing this? 5 I will
42   not lay this chain upon myself. 
43   
44   6 In everything you do remember this: 
45   
46   7 No one is crucified alone, and yet no one can enter Heaven by himself.
47   
48   
49   
50   LESSON 135.
0535
 1   
 2   If I defend myself I am attacked.
 3   W-pI.135.1. Who would defend himself unless he thought he were attacked, that the 
 4   attack were real, and that his own defense could save himself? 2 And herein lies the folly of
 5   defense; it gives illusions full reality, and then attempts to handle them as real. 3 
 6   It adds illusions to illusions, thus making correction doubly difficult. 4 And it is this
 7   you do when you attempt to plan the future, activate the past, or organize the present 
 8   as you wish.
 9   W-pI.135.2. You operate from the belief you must protect yourself from what is 
10   happening because it must contain what threatens you. 2 A sense of threat is an acknowledgment 
11   of an inherent weakness; a belief that there is danger which has power to call on you to 
12   make appropriate defense. 3 The world is based on this insane belief. 4 And all its 
13   structures, all its thoughts and doubts, its penalties and heavy armaments, its legal definitions
14   and its codes, its ethics and its leaders and its gods, all serve but to preserve its 
15   sense of threat. 5 For no one walks the world in armature but must have terror striking at 
16   his heart.
17   W-pI.135.3. Defense is frightening. 2 It stems from fear, increasing fear as each 
18   defense is made. 3 You think it offers safety. 4 Yet it speaks of fear made real and terror 
19   justified. 5 Is it not strange you do not pause to ask, as you elaborate your plans and make 
20   your armor thicker and your locks more tight, what you defend, and how, and against what?
21   W-pI.135.4. Let us consider first what you defend. 2 It must be something that is very 
22   weak and easily assaulted. 3 It must be something made easy prey, unable to protect itself 
23   and needing your defense. 4 What but the body has such frailty that constant care and 
24   watchful, deep concern are needful to protect its little life? 5 What but the body falters and 
25   must fail to serve the Son of God as worthy host?
26   W-pI.135.5. Yet it is not the body that can fear, nor be a thing of fear. 2 It has no 
27   needs but those which you assign to it. 3 It needs no complicated structures of defense, no 
28   health-inducing medicine, no care and no concern at all. 4 Defend its life, or give it gifts to make 
29   it beautiful or walls to make it safe, and you but say your home is open to the thief of 
30   time, corruptible and crumbling, so unsafe it must be guarded with your very life.
31   W-pI.135.6. Is not this picture fearful? 2 Can you be at peace with such a concept of 
32   your home? 3 Yet what endowed the body with the right to serve you thus except your own 
33   belief? 4 It is your mind which gave the body all the functions that you see in it, and set 
34   its value far beyond a little pile of dust and water. 5 Who would make defense of 
35   something that he recognized as this?
36   W-pI.135.7. The body is in need of no defense. 2 This cannot be too often emphasized. 3
37   It will be strong and healthy if the mind does not abuse it by assigning it to roles it
38   cannot fill, to purposes beyond its scope, and to exalted aims which it cannot 
39   accomplish. 4 Such attempts, ridiculous yet deeply cherished, are the sources for the many mad 
40   attacks you make upon it. 5 For it seems to fail your hopes, your needs, your values and your 
41   dreams.
42   W-pI.135.8. The "self" that needs protection is not real. 2 The body, valueless and 
43   hardly worth the least defense, need merely be perceived as quite apart from you, and it 
44   becomes a healthy, serviceable instrument through which the mind can operate until its 
45   usefulness is over. 3 Who would want to keep it when its usefulness is done?
46   W-pI.135.9. Defend the body and you have attacked your mind. 2 For you have seen in it 
47   the faults, the weaknesses, the limits and the lacks from which you think the body must be
48   saved. 3 You will not see the mind as separate from bodily conditions. 4 And you will 
49   impose upon the body all the pain that comes from the conception of the mind as limited and 
50   fragile, and apart from other minds and separate from its Source.
0536
 1   W-pI.135.10. These are the thoughts in need of healing, and the body will respond with 
 2   health when they have been corrected and replaced with truth. 2 This is the body's only real 
 3   defense. 3 Yet is this where you look for its defense? 4 You offer it protection of a kind 
 4   from which it gains no benefit at all, but merely adds to your distress of mind. 5 You do 
 5   not heal, but merely take away the hope of healing, for you fail to see where hope must 
 6   lie if it be meaningful.
 7   W-pI.135.11. A healed mind does not plan. 2 It carries out the plans that it receives 
 8   through listening to wisdom that is not its own. 3 It waits until it has been taught what 
 9   should be done, and then proceeds to do it. 4 It does not depend upon itself for anything 
10   except its adequacy to fulfill the plans assigned to it. 5 It is secure in certainty that 
11   obstacles can not impede its progress to accomplishment of any goal that serves the greater plan
12   established for the good of everyone.
13   W-pI.135.12. A healed mind is relieved of the belief that it must plan, although it 
14   cannot know the outcome which is best, the means by which it is achieved, nor how to 
15   recognize the problem that the plan is made to solve. 2 It must misuse the body in its plans 
16   until it recognizes this is so. 3 But when it has accepted this as true, then is it healed, 
17   and lets the body go.
18   W-pI.135.13. Enslavement of the body to the plans the unhealed mind sets up to save 
19   itself must make the body sick. 2 It is not free to be the means of helping in a plan which 
20   far exceeds its own protection, and which needs its service for a little while. 3 In this 
21   capacity is health assured. 4 For everything the mind employs for this will function flawlessly,
22    and with the strength that has been given it and cannot fail.
23   W-pI.135.14. It is, perhaps, not easy to perceive that self-initiated plans are but 
24   defenses, with the purpose all of them were made to realize. 2 They are the means by which a 
25   frightened mind would undertake its own protection, at the cost of truth. 3 This is not difficult
26   to realize in some forms which these self-deceptions take, where the denial of reality 
27   is very obvious. 4 Yet planning is not often recognized as a defense.
28   W-pI.135.15. The mind engaged in planning for itself is occupied in setting up control 
29   of future happenings. 2 It does not think that it will be provided for, unless it makes 
30   its own provisions. 3 Time becomes a future emphasis, to be controlled by learning and 
31   experience obtained from past events and previous beliefs. 4 It overlooks the present, for it 
32   rests on the idea the past has taught enough to let the mind direct its future course.
33   W-pI.135.16. The mind that plans is thus refusing to allow for change. 2 What it has 
34   learned before becomes the basis for its future goals. 3 Its past experience directs its 
35   choice of what will happen. 4 And it does not see that here and now is everything it needs to
36   guarantee a future quite unlike the past, without a continuity of any old ideas and 
37   sick beliefs. 5 Anticipation plays no part at all, for present confidence directs the way.
38   W-pI.135.17. Defenses are the plans you undertake to make against the truth. 2 Their 
39   aim is to select what you approve, and disregard what you consider incompatible with your 
40   beliefs of your reality. 3 Yet what remains is meaningless indeed. 4 For it is your reality 
41   that is the "threat" which your defenses would attack, obscure, and take apart and crucify.
42   W-pI.135.18. What could you not accept, if you but knew that everything that happens, 
43   all events, past, present and to come, are gently planned by One Whose only purpose is 
44   your good? 2 Perhaps you have misunderstood His plan, for He would never offer pain to you.
45   3 But your defenses did not let you see His loving blessing shine in every step you 
46   ever took. 4 While you made plans for death, He led you gently to eternal life.
47   W-pI.135.19. Your present trust in Him is the defense that promises a future 
48   undisturbed, without a trace of sorrow, and with joy that constantly increases, as this life 
49   becomes a holy instant, set in time, but heeding only immortality. 2 Let no defenses but your 
50   present trust direct the future, and this life becomes a meaningful encounter with the truth 
0537
 1   that only your defenses would conceal.
 2   W-pI.135.20. Without defenses, you become a light which Heaven gratefully acknowledges 
 3   to be its own. 2 And it will lead you on in ways appointed for your happiness according 
 4   to the ancient plan, begun when time was born. 3 Your followers will join their light 
 5   with yours, and it will be increased until the world is lighted up with joy. 4 And gladly 
 6   will our brothers lay aside their cumbersome defenses, which availed them nothing and could
 7   only terrify.
 8   W-pI.135.21. We will anticipate that time today with present confidence, for this is 
 9   part of what was planned for us. 2 We will be sure that everything we need is given us for 
10   our accomplishment of this today. 3 We make no plans for how it will be done, but realize 
11   that our defenselessness is all that is required for the truth to dawn upon our minds with 
12   certainty.
13   W-pI.135.22. For fifteen minutes twice today we rest from senseless planning, and from 
14   every thought that blocks the truth from entering our minds. 2 Today we will receive instead
15   of plan, that we may give instead of organize. 3 And we are given truly, as we say: 
16   
17   4 If I defend myself I am attacked. 5 But in defenselessness I will be strong, and I 
18   will learn what my defenses hide.
19   
20   W-pI.135.23. Nothing but that. 2 If there are plans to make, you will be told of them. 
21   3 They may not be the plans you thought were needed, nor indeed the answers to the 
22   problems which you thought confronted you. 4 But they are answers to another kind of question, 
23   which remains unanswered yet in need of answering until the Answer comes to you at last.
24   W-pI.135.24. All your defenses have been aimed at not receiving what you will receive 
25   today. 2 And in the light and joy of simple trust, you will but wonder why you ever thought 
26   that you must be defended from release. 3 Heaven asks nothing. 4 It is hell that makes 
27   extravagant demands for sacrifice. 5 You give up nothing in these times today when, undefended, 
28   you present yourself to your Creator as you really are.
29   W-pI.135.25. He has remembered you. 2 Today we will remember Him. 3 For this is 
30   Eastertime in your salvation. 4 And you rise again from what was seeming death and hopelessness. 
31   5 Now is the light of hope reborn in you, for now you come without defense, to learn the
32   part for you within the plan of God. 6 What little plans or magical beliefs can still 
33   have value, when you have received your function from the Voice for God Himself?
34   W-pI.135.26. Try not to shape this day as you believe would benefit you most. 2 For you
35   can not conceive of all the happiness that comes to you without your planning. 3 Learn 
36   today. 4 And all the world will take this giant stride, and celebrate your Eastertime with 
37   you. 5 Throughout the day, as foolish little things appear to raise defensiveness in you 
38   and tempt you to engage in weaving plans, remind yourself this is a special day for 
39   learning, and acknowledge it with this: 
40   
41   6 This is my Eastertime. 7 And I would keep it holy. 8 I will not defend myself, 
42   because the Son of God needs no defense against the truth of his reality.
43   
