0542
 1   LESSON 138.
 2   
 3   Heaven is the decision I must make.
 4   W-pI.138.1. In this world Heaven is a choice, because here we believe there are 
 5   alternatives to choose between. 2 We think that all things have an opposite, and what we want we 
 6   choose. 3 If Heaven exists there must be hell as well, for contradiction is the way we make 
 7   what we perceive, and what we think is real.
 8   W-pI.138.2. Creation knows no opposite. 2 But here is opposition part of being "real." 
 9   3 It is this strange perception of the truth that makes the choice of Heaven seem to be 
10   the same as the relinquishment of hell. 4 It is not really thus. 5 Yet what is true in 
11   God's creation cannot enter here until it is reflected in some form the world can understand.
12    6 Truth cannot come where it could only be perceived with fear. 7 For this would be 
13   the error truth can be brought to illusions. 8 Opposition makes the truth unwelcome, and 
14   it cannot come.
15   W-pI.138.3. Choice is the obvious escape from what appears as opposites. 2 Decision 
16   lets one of conflicting goals become the aim of effort and expenditure of time. 3 Without 
17   decision, time is but a waste and effort dissipated. 4 It is spent for nothing in return, and 
18   time goes by without results. 5 There is no sense of gain, for nothing is accomplished; 
19   nothing learned.
20   W-pI.138.4. You need to be reminded that you think a thousand choices are confronting 
21   you, when there is really only one to make. 2 And even this but seems to be a choice. 3 Do
22   not confuse yourself with all the doubts that myriad decisions would induce. 4 You make
23   but one. 5 And when that one is made, you will perceive it was no choice at all. 6 For 
24   truth is true, and nothing else is true. 7 There is no opposite to choose instead. 8 There 
25   is no contradiction to the truth.
26   W-pI.138.5. Choosing depends on learning. 2 And the truth cannot be learned, but only 
27   recognized. 3 In recognition its acceptance lies, and as it is accepted it is known. 4 But 
28   knowledge is beyond the goals we seek to teach within the framework of this course. 5 Ours are 
29   teaching goals, to be attained through learning how to reach them, what they are, and what they
30   offer you. 6 Decisions are the outcome of your learning, for they rest on what you have
31   accepted as the truth of what you are, and what your needs must be.
32   W-pI.138.6. In this insanely complicated world, Heaven appears to take the form of 
33   choice, rather than merely being what it is. 2 Of all the choices you have tried to make this
34   is the simplest, most definitive and prototype of all the rest, the one which settles 
35   all decisions. 3 If you could decide the rest, this one remains unsolved. 4 But when you 
36   solve this one, the others are resolved with it, for all decisions but conceal this one by 
37   taking different forms. 5 Here is the final and the only choice in which is truth accepted or
38   denied.
39   W-pI.138.7. So we begin today considering the choice that time was made to help us make.
40    2 Such is its holy purpose, now transformed from the intent you gave it; that it be a 
41   means for demonstrating hell is real, hope changes to despair, and life itself must in the 
42   end be overcome by death. 3 In death alone are opposites resolved, for ending opposition 
43   is to die. 4 And thus salvation must be seen as death, for life is seen as conflict. 5 To
44   resolve the conflict is to end your life as well.
45   W-pI.138.8. These mad beliefs can gain unconscious hold of great intensity, and grip 
46   the mind with terror and anxiety so strong that it will not relinquish its ideas about its
47   own protection. 2 It must be saved from salvation, threatened to be safe, and magically
48   armored against truth. 3 And these decisions are made unaware, to keep them safely 
49   undisturbed; apart from question and from reason and from doubt.
50   W-pI.138.9. Heaven is chosen consciously. 2 The choice cannot be made until 
0543
 1   alternatives are accurately seen and understood. 3 All that is veiled in shadows must be raised to 
 2   understanding, to be judged again, this time with Heaven's help. 4 And all mistakes in judgment that
 3   the mind had made before are open to correction, as the truth dismisses them as 
 4   causeless. 5 Now are they without effects. 6 They cannot be concealed, because their nothingness
 5   is recognized.
 6   W-pI.138.10. The conscious choice of Heaven is as sure as is the ending of the fear of 
 7   hell, when it is raised from its protective shield of unawareness, and is brought to light.
 8   2 Who can decide between the clearly seen and the unrecognized? 3 Yet who can fail to 
 9   make a choice between alternatives when only one is seen as valuable; the other as a wholly
10   worthless thing, a but imagined source of guilt and pain? 4 Who hesitates to make a 
11   choice like this? 5 And shall we hesitate to choose today?
12   W-pI.138.11. We make the choice for Heaven as we wake, and spend five minutes making 
13   sure that we have made the one decision that is sane. 2 We recognize we make a conscious 
14   choice between what has existence and what has nothing but an appearance of the truth. 3 Its 
15   pseudo-being, brought to what is real, is flimsy and transparent in the light. 4 It holds no terror
16   now, for what was made enormous, vengeful, pitiless with hate, demands obscurity for 
17   fear to be invested there. 5 Now it is recognized as but a foolish, trivial mistake.
18   W-pI.138.12. Before we close our eyes in sleep tonight, we reaffirm the choice that we 
19   have made each hour in between. 2 And now we give the last five minutes of our waking day 
20   to the decision with which we awoke. 3 As every hour passed, we have declared our choice 
21   again, in a brief quiet time devoted to maintaining sanity. 4 And finally, we close the day 
22   with this, acknowledging we chose but what we want: 
23   
24   5 Heaven is the decision I must make. 6 I make it now, and will not change my mind, 
25   because it is the only thing I want.
26   
27   
28   
29   LESSON 139.
30   
31   I will accept Atonement for myself.
32   W-pI.139.1. Here is the end of choice. 2 For here we come to a decision to accept 
33   ourselves as God created us. 3 And what is choice except uncertainty of what we are? 4 There is 
34   no doubt that is not rooted here. 5 There is no question but reflects this one. 6 There 
35   is no conflict that does not entail the single, simple question, "What am I?"
36   W-pI.139.2. Yet who could ask this question except one who has refused to recognize 
37   himself? 2 Only refusal to accept yourself could make the question seem to be sincere. 3 The 
38   only thing that can be surely known by any living thing is what it is. 4 From this one 
39   point of certainty, it looks on other things as certain as itself.
40   W-pI.139.3. Uncertainty about what you must be is self-deception on a scale so vast, 
41   its magnitude can hardly be conceived. 2 To be alive and not to know yourself is to 
42   believe that you are really dead. 3 For what is life except to be yourself, and what but you 
43   can be alive instead? 4 Who is the doubter? 5 What is it he doubts? 6 Whom does he 
44   question? 7 Who can answer him?
45   W-pI.139.4. He merely states that he is not himself, and therefore, being something 
46   else, becomes a questioner of what that something is. 2 Yet he could never be alive at all 
47   unless he knew the answer. 3 If he asks as if he does not know, it merely shows he does not 
48   want to be the thing he is. 4 He has accepted it because he lives; has judged against it 
49   and denied its worth, and has decided that he does not know the only certainty by which he
50   lives.
0544
 1   W-pI.139.5. Thus he becomes uncertain of his life, for what it is has been denied by 
 2   him. 2 It is for this denial that you need Atonement. 3 Your denial made no change in what
 3   you are. 4 But you have split your mind into what knows and does not know the truth. 5 
 4   You are yourself. 6 There is no doubt of this. 7 And yet you doubt it. 8 But you do not 
 5   ask what part of you can really doubt yourself. 9 It cannot really be a part of you that 
 6   asks this question. 10 For it asks of one who knows the answer. 11 Were it part of you, 
 7   then certainty would be impossible.
 8   W-pI.139.6. Atonement remedies the strange idea that it is possible to doubt yourself, 
 9   and be unsure of what you really are. 2 This is the depth of madness. 3 Yet it is the 
10   universal question of the world. 4 What does this mean except the world is mad? 5 Why share its 
11   madness in the sad belief that what is universal here is true?
12   W-pI.139.7. Nothing the world believes is true. 2 It is a place whose purpose is to be 
13   a home where those who claim they do not know themselves can come to question what it is
14   they are. 3 And they will come again until the time Atonement is accepted, and they 
15   learn it is impossible to doubt yourself, and not to be aware of what you are.
16   W-pI.139.8. Only acceptance can be asked of you, for what you are is certain. 2 It is 
17   set forever in the holy Mind of God, and in your own. 3 It is so far beyond all doubt and 
18   question that to ask what it must be is all the proof you need to show that you believe the 
19   contradiction that you know not what you cannot fail to know. 4 Is this a question, or a statement 
20   which denies itself in statement? 5 Let us not allow our holy minds to occupy themselves 
21   with senseless musings such as this.
22   W-pI.139.9. We have a mission here. 2 We did not come to reinforce the madness that we 
23   once believed in. 3 Let us not forget the goal that we accepted. 4 It is more than just our
24   happiness alone we came to gain. 5 What we accept as what we are proclaims what 
25   everyone must be, along with us. 6 Fail not your brothers, or you fail yourself. 7 Look 
26   lovingly on them, that they may know that they are part of you, and you of them.
27   W-pI.139.10. This does Atonement teach, and demonstrates the Oneness of God's Son is 
28   unassailed by his belief he knows not what he is. 2 Today accept Atonement, not to change reality,
29    but merely to accept the truth about yourself, and go your way rejoicing in the 
30   endless Love of God. 3 It is but this that we are asked to do. 4 It is but this that we will 
31   do today.
32   W-pI.139.11. Five minutes in the morning and at night we will devote to dedicate our 
33   minds to our assignment for today. 2 We start with this review of what our mission is: 
34   
35   3 I will accept Atonement for myself, For I remain as God created me. 
36   
37   4 We have not lost the knowledge that God gave to us when He created us like Him. 5 We 
38   can remember it for everyone, for in creation are all minds as one. 6 And in our memory is
39   the recall how dear our brothers are to us in truth, how much a part of us is every 
40   mind, how faithful they have really been to us, and how our Father's Love contains them all.
41   
42   W-pI.139.12. In thanks for all creation, in the Name of its Creator and His Oneness 
43   with all aspects of creation, we repeat our dedication to our cause today each hour, as we 
44   lay aside all thoughts that would distract us from our holy aim. 2 For several minutes let
45   your mind be cleared of all the foolish cobwebs which the world would weave around the 
46   holy Son of God. 3 And learn the fragile nature of the chains that seem to keep the 
47   knowledge of yourself apart from your awareness, as you say: 
48   
49   4 I will accept Atonement for myself, For I remain as God created me.
50   
0545
 1   
 2   
 3   LESSON 140.
 4   
 5   Only salvation can be said to cure.
 6   W-pI.140.1. "Cure" is a word that cannot be applied to any remedy the world accepts as 
 7   beneficial. 2 What the world perceives as therapeutic is but what will make the body "better." 3 
 8   When it tries to heal the mind, it sees no separation from the body, where it thinks the 
 9   mind exists. 4 Its forms of healing thus must substitute illusion for illusion. 5 One 
10   belief in sickness takes another form, and so the patient now perceives himself as well.
11   W-pI.140.2. He is not healed. 2 He merely had a dream that he was sick, and in the 
12   dream he found a magic formula to make him well. 3 Yet he has not awakened from the dream, 
13   and so his mind remains exactly as it was before. 4 He has not seen the light that would 
14   awaken him and end the dream. 5 What difference does the content of a dream make in reality? 
15   6 One either sleeps or wakens. 7 There is nothing in between.
16   W-pI.140.3. The happy dreams the Holy Spirit brings are different from the dreaming of 
17   the world, where one can merely dream he is awake. 2 The dreams forgiveness lets the mind 
18   perceive do not induce another form of sleep, so that the dreamer dreams another dream. 3 His 
19   happy dreams are heralds of the dawn of truth upon the mind. 4 They lead from sleep to 
20   gentle waking, so that dreams are gone. 5 And thus they cure for all eternity.
21   W-pI.140.4. Atonement heals with certainty, and cures all sickness. 2 For the mind 
22   which understands that sickness can be nothing but a dream is not deceived by forms the 
23   dream may take. 3 Sickness where guilt is absent cannot come, for it is but another form of 
24   guilt. 4 Atonement does not heal the sick, for that is not a cure. 5 It takes away the guilt
25   that makes the sickness possible. 6 And that is cure indeed. 7 For sickness now is gone,
26    with nothing left to which it can return.
27   W-pI.140.5. Peace be to you who have been cured in God, and not in idle dreams. 2 For 
28   cure must come from holiness, and holiness can not be found where sin is cherished. 3 God 
29   abides in holy temples. 4 He is barred where sin has entered. 5 Yet there is no place where 
30   He is not. 6 And therefore sin can have no home in which to hide from His beneficence. 7 
31   There is no place where holiness is not, and nowhere sin and sickness can abide.
32   W-pI.140.6. This is the thought that cures. 2 It does not make distinctions among 
33   unrealities. 3 Nor does it seek to heal what is not sick, unmindful where the need for healing is.
34   4 This is no magic. 5 It is merely an appeal to truth, which cannot fail to heal and 
35   heal forever. 6 It is not a thought that judges an illusion by its size, its seeming 
36   gravity, or anything that is related to the form it takes. 7 It merely focuses on what it is, 
37   and knows that no illusion can be real.
38   W-pI.140.7. Let us not try today to seek to cure what cannot suffer sickness. 2 Healing
39   must be sought but where it is, and then applied to what is sick, so that it can be 
40   cured. 3 There is no remedy the world provides that can effect a change in anything. 4 The 
41   mind that brings illusions to the truth is really changed. 5 There is no change but this. 6
42   For how can one illusion differ from another but in attributes that have no substance, 
43   no reality, no core, and nothing that is truly different?
44   W-pI.140.8. Today we seek to change our minds about the source of sickness, for we seek
45   a cure for all illusions, not another shift among them. 2 We will try today to find the
46   source of healing, which is in our minds because our Father placed it there for us. 3 
47   It is not farther from us than ourselves. 4 It is as near to us as our own thoughts; so 
48   close it is impossible to lose. 5 We need but seek it and it must be found.
49   W-pI.140.9. We will not be misled today by what appears to us as sick. 2 We go beyond 
50   appearances today and reach the source of healing, from which nothing is exempt. 3 We will succeed
0546
 1   to the extent to which we realize that there can never be a meaningful distinction made
 2   between what is untrue and equally untrue. 4 Here there are no degrees, and no beliefs 
 3   that what does not exist is truer in some forms than others. 5 All of them are false, and 
 4   can be cured because they are not true.
 5   W-pI.140.10. So do we lay aside our amulets, our charms and medicines, our chants and 
 6   bits of magic in whatever form they take. 2 We will be still and listen for the Voice of 
 7   healing, which will cure all ills as one, restoring saneness to the Son of God. 3 No voice but
 8   this can cure. 4 Today we hear a single Voice which speaks to us of truth, where all 
 9   illusions end, and peace returns to the eternal, quiet home of God.
10   W-pI.140.11. We waken hearing Him, and let Him speak to us five minutes as the day 
11   begins, and end the day by listening again five minutes more before we go to sleep. 2 Our 
12   only preparation is to let our interfering thoughts be laid aside, not separately, but all 
13   of them as one. 3 They are the same. 4 We have no need to make them different, and thus 
14   delay the time when we can hear our Father speak to us. 5 We hear Him now. 6 We come to Him 
15   today.
16   W-pI.140.12. With nothing in our hands to which we cling, with lifted hearts and 
17   listening minds we pray: 
18   
19   2 Only salvation can be said to cure. 
20   3 Speak to us, Father, that we may be healed. 
21   
22   4 And we will feel salvation cover us with soft protection, and with peace so deep that
23   no illusion can disturb our minds, nor offer proof to us that it is real. 5 This will 
24   we learn today. 6 And we will say our prayer for healing hourly, and take a minute as the
25   hour strikes, to hear the answer to our prayer be given us as we attend in silence and 
26   in joy. 7 This is the day when healing comes to us. 8 This is the day when separation 
27   ends, and we remember Who we really are.
28   
29   
30   
31   REVIEW IV
32   
33   Introduction
34   W-pI.rIV.in.1. Now we review again, this time aware we are preparing for the second 
35   part of learning how the truth can be applied. 2 Today we will begin to concentrate on 
36   readiness for what will follow next. 3 Such is our aim for this review, and for the lessons 
37   following. 4 Thus, we review the recent lessons and their central thoughts in such a way as will
38   facilitate the readiness that we would now achieve.
39   W-pI.rIV.in.2. There is a central theme that unifies each step in the review we 
40   undertake, which can be simply stated in these words: 
41   
42   2 My mind holds only what I think with God. 
43   
44   3 That is a fact, and represents the truth of What you are and What your Father is. 4 
45   It is this thought by which the Father gave creation to the Son, establishing the Son as 
46   co-creator with Himself. 5 It is this thought that fully guarantees salvation to the Son. 6 For 
47   in his mind no thoughts can dwell but those his Father shares. 7 Lack of forgiveness 
48   blocks this thought from his awareness. 8 Yet it is forever true.
49   W-pI.rIV.in.3. Let us begin our preparation with some understanding of the many forms 
50   in which the lack of true forgiveness may be carefully concealed. 2 Because they are 
0547
 1   illusions, they are not perceived to be but what they are; defenses that protect your 
 2   unforgiving thoughts from being seen and recognized. 3 Their purpose is to show you something else,
 3    and hold correction off through self-deceptions made to take its place.
 4   W-pI.rIV.in.4. And yet, your mind holds only what you think with God. 2 Your 
 5   self-deceptions cannot take the place of truth. 3 No more than can a child who throws a stick into the
 6   ocean change the coming and the going of the tides, the warming of the water by the sun,
 7    the silver of the moon on it by night. 4 So do we start each practice period in this 
 8   review with readying our minds to understand the lessons that we read, and see the meaning 
 9   that they offer us.
10   W-pI.rIV.in.5. Begin each day with time devoted to the preparation of your mind to 
11   learn what each idea you will review that day can offer you in freedom and in peace. 2 Open 
12   your mind, and clear it of all thoughts that would deceive, and let this thought alone 
13   engage it fully, and remove the rest: 
14   
15   3 My mind holds only what I think with God. 
16   
17   4 Five minutes with this thought will be enough to set the day along the lines which 
18   God appointed, and to place His Mind in charge of all the thoughts you will receive that 
19   day.
20   W-pI.rIV.in.6. They will not come from you alone, for they will all be shared with Him.
21   2 And so each one will bring the message of His Love to you, returning messages of 
22   yours to Him. 3 So will communion with the Lord of Hosts be yours, as He Himself has willed 
23   it be. 4 And as His Own completion joins with Him, so will He join with you who are 
24   complete as you unite with Him, and He with you.
25   W-pI.rIV.in.7. After your preparation, merely read each of the two ideas assigned to 
26   you to be reviewed that day. 2 Then close your eyes, and say them slowly to yourself. 3 
27   There is no hurry now, for you are using time for its intended purpose. 4 Let each word 
28   shine with the meaning God has given it, as it was given to you through His Voice. 5 Let 
29   each idea which you review that day give you the gift that He has laid in it for you to 
30   have of Him. 6 And we will use no format for our practicing but this:
31   W-pI.rIV.in.8. Each hour of the day, bring to your mind the thought with which the day 
32   began, and spend a quiet moment with it. 2 Then repeat the two ideas you practice for the 
33   day unhurriedly, with time enough to see the gifts that they contain for you, and let them
34   be received where they were meant to be.
35   W-pI.rIV.in.9. We add no other thoughts, but let these be the messages they are. 2 We 
36   need no more than this to give us happiness and rest, and endless quiet, perfect certainty,
37   and all our Father wills that we receive as the inheritance we have of Him. 3 Each day 
38   of practicing, as we review, we close as we began, repeating first the thought that made 
39   the day a special time of blessing and of happiness for us; and through our faithfulness 
40   restored the world from darkness to the light, from grief to joy, from pain to peace, from sin 
41   to holiness.
42   W-pI.rIV.in.10. God offers thanks to you who practice thus the keeping of His Word. 2 
43   And as you give your mind to the ideas for the day again before you sleep, His gratitude 
44   surrounds you in the peace wherein He wills you be forever, and are learning now to claim again 
45   as your inheritance.
