29   LESSON 151.
30   
31   All things are echoes of the Voice for God.
32   W-pI.151.1. No one can judge on partial evidence. 2 That is not judgment. 3 It is 
33   merely an opinion based on ignorance and doubt. 4 Its seeming certainty is but a cloak for 
34   the uncertainty it would conceal. 5 It needs irrational defense because it is irrational. 
35   6 And its defense seems strong, convincing, and without a doubt because of all the 
36   doubting underneath.
37   W-pI.151.2. You do not seem to doubt the world you see. 2 You do not really question 
38   what is shown you through the body's eyes. 3 Nor do you ask why you believe it, even though
39   you learned a long while since your senses do deceive. 4 That you believe them to the 
40   last detail which they report is even stranger, when you pause to recollect how frequently 
41   they have been faulty witnesses indeed! 5 Why would you trust them so implicitly? 6 Why but
42   because of underlying doubt, which you would hide with show of certainty?
43   W-pI.151.3. How can you judge? 2 Your judgment rests upon the witness that your senses 
44   offer you. 3 Yet witness never falser was than this. 4 But how else do you judge the world 
45   you see? 5 You place pathetic faith in what your eyes and ears report. 6 You think your 
46   fingers touch reality, and close upon the truth. 7 This is awareness that you understand, and 
47   think more real than what is witnessed to by the eternal Voice for God Himself.
48   W-pI.151.4. Can this be judgment? 2 You have often been urged to refrain from judging, 
49   not because it is a right to be withheld from you. 3 You cannot judge. 4 You merely can 
50   believe the ego's judgments, all of which are false. 5 It guides your senses carefully, to 
0550
 1   prove how weak you are; how helpless and afraid, how apprehensive of just punishment, how 
 2   black with sin, how wretched in your guilt.
 3   W-pI.151.5. This thing it speaks of, and would yet defend, it tells you is yourself. 2 
 4   And you believe that this is so with stubborn certainty. 3 Yet underneath remains the 
 5   hidden doubt that what it shows you as reality with such conviction it does not believe. 4 It
 6   is itself alone that it condemns. 5 It is within itself it sees the guilt. 6 It is its 
 7   own despair it sees in you.
 8   W-pI.151.6. Hear not its voice. 2 The witnesses it sends to prove to you its evil is 
 9   your own are false, and speak with certainty of what they do not know. 3 Your faith in them
10   is blind because you would not share the doubts their lord can not completely vanquish.
11   4 You believe to doubt his vassals is to doubt yourself.
12   W-pI.151.7. Yet you must learn to doubt their evidence will clear the way to recognize 
13   yourself, and let the Voice for God alone be Judge of what is worthy of your own belief. 2 He 
14   will not tell you that your brother should be judged by what your eyes behold in him, nor 
15   what his body's mouth says to your ears, nor what your fingers' touch reports of him. 3 He 
16   passes by such idle witnesses, which merely bear false witness to God's Son. 4 He recognizes 
17   only what God loves, and in the holy light of what He sees do all the ego's dreams of what 
18   you are vanish before the splendor He beholds.
19   W-pI.151.8. Let Him be Judge of what you are, for He has certainty in which there is no
20   doubt, because it rests on Certainty so great that doubt is meaningless before Its face.
21    2 Christ cannot doubt Himself. 3 The Voice for God can only honor Him, rejoicing in 
22   His perfect, everlasting sinlessness. 4 Whom He has judged can only laugh at guilt, 
23   unwilling now to play with toys of sin; unheeding of the body's witnesses before the rapture of 
24   Christ's holy face.
25   W-pI.151.9. And thus He judges you. 2 Accept His Word for what you are, for He bears 
26   witness to your beautiful creation, and the Mind Whose Thought created your reality. 3 What 
27   can the body mean to Him Who knows the glory of the Father and the Son? 4 What whispers of
28   the ego can He hear? 5 What could convince Him that your sins are real? 6 Let Him be 
29   Judge as well of everything that seems to happen to you in this world. 7 His lessons will 
30   enable you to bridge the gap between illusions and the truth.
31   W-pI.151.10. He will remove all faith that you have placed in pain, disaster, suffering
32   and loss. 2 He gives you vision which can look beyond these grim appearances, and can 
33   behold the gentle face of Christ in all of them. 3 You will no longer doubt that only good 
34   can come to you who are beloved of God, for He will judge all happenings, and teach the 
35   single lesson that they all contain.
36   W-pI.151.11. He will select the elements in them which represent the truth, and 
37   disregard those aspects which reflect but idle dreams. 2 And He will reinterpret all you see, 
38   and all occurrences, each circumstance, and every happening that seems to touch on you in 
39   any way from His one frame of reference, wholly unified and sure. 3 And you will see the 
40   love beyond the hate, the constancy in change, the pure in sin, and only Heaven's blessing 
41   on the world.
42   W-pI.151.12. Such is your resurrection, for your life is not a part of anything you see.
43    2 It stands beyond the body and the world, past every witness for unholiness, within 
44   the Holy, holy as Itself. 3 In everyone and everything His Voice would speak to you of 
45   nothing but your Self and your Creator, Who is One with Him. 4 So will you see the holy face 
46   of Christ in everything, and hear in everything no sound except the echo of God's Voice.
47   W-pI.151.13. We practice wordlessly today, except at the beginning of the time we spend
48   with God. 2 We introduce these times with but a single, slow repeating of the thought 
49   with which the day begins. 3 And then we watch our thoughts, appealing silently to Him Who 
50   sees the elements of truth in them. 4 Let Him evaluate each thought that comes to mind, 
0551
 1   remove the elements of dreams, and give them back again as clean ideas that do not contradict
 2   the Will of God.
 3   W-pI.151.14. Give Him your thoughts, and He will give them back as miracles which 
 4   joyously proclaim the wholeness and the happiness God wills His Son, as proof of His eternal 
 5   Love. 2 And as each thought is thus transformed, it takes on healing power from the Mind 
 6   which saw the truth in it, and failed to be deceived by what was falsely added. 3 All the 
 7   threads of fantasy are gone. 4 And what remains is unified into a perfect Thought that offers 
 8   its perfection everywhere.
 9   W-pI.151.15. Spend fifteen minutes thus when you awake, and gladly give another fifteen
10   more before you go to sleep. 2 Your ministry begins as all your thoughts are purified. 
11   3 So are you taught to teach the Son of God the holy lesson of his sanctity. 4 No one 
12   can fail to listen, when you hear the Voice for God give honor to God's Son. 5 And 
13   everyone will share the thoughts with you which He has retranslated in your mind.
14   W-pI.151.16. Such is your Eastertide. 2 And so you lay the gift of snow-white lilies on
15   the world, replacing witnesses to sin and death. 3 Through your transfiguration is the 
16   world redeemed, and joyfully released from guilt. 4 Now do we lift our resurrected minds in 
17   gladness and in gratitude to Him Who has restored our sanity to us.
18   W-pI.151.17. And we will hourly remember Him Who is salvation and deliverance. 2 As we 
19   give thanks, the world unites with us and happily accepts our holy thoughts, which Heaven 
20   has corrected and made pure. 3 Now has our ministry begun at last, to carry round the 
21   world the joyous news that truth has no illusions, and the peace of God, through us, belongs
22   to everyone.
