24   
25   
26   LESSON 152.
27   
28   The power of decision is my own.
29   W-pI.152.1. No one can suffer loss unless it be his own decision. 2 No one suffers pain
30   except his choice elects this state for him. 3 No one can grieve nor fear nor think him
31   sick unless these are the outcomes that he wants. 4 And no one dies without his own 
32   consent. 5 Nothing occurs but represents your wish, and nothing is omitted that you choose. 6 
33   Here is your world, complete in all details. 7 Here is its whole reality for you. 8 And it 
34   is only here salvation is.
35   W-pI.152.2. You may believe that this position is extreme, and too inclusive to be true.
36    2 Yet can truth have exceptions? 3 If you have the gift of everything, can loss be 
37   real? 4 Can pain be part of peace, or grief of joy? 5 Can fear and sickness enter in a mind
38   where love and perfect holiness abide? 6 Truth must be all-inclusive, if it be the 
39   truth at all. 7 Accept no opposites and no exceptions, for to do so is to contradict the 
40   truth entirely.
41   W-pI.152.3. Salvation is the recognition that the truth is true, and nothing else is 
42   true. 2 This you have heard before, but may not yet accept both parts of it. 3 Without the 
43   first, the second has no meaning. 4 But without the second, is the first no longer true. 5 
44   Truth cannot have an opposite. 6 This can not be too often said and thought about. 7 For if 
45   what is not true is true as well as what is true, then part of truth is false. 8 And truth 
46   has lost its meaning. 9 Nothing but the truth is true, and what is false is false.
47   W-pI.152.4. This is the simplest of distinctions, yet the most obscure. 2 But not 
48   because it is a difficult distinction to perceive. 3 It is concealed behind a vast array of 
49   choices that do not appear to be entirely your own. 4 And thus the truth appears to have some 
50   aspects that belie consistency, but do not seem to be but contradictions introduced by you.
0552
 1   W-pI.152.5. As God created you, you must remain unchangeable, with transitory states by
 2   definition false. 2 And that includes all shifts in feeling, alterations in conditions 
 3   of the body and the mind; in all awareness and in all response. 3 This is the 
 4   all-inclusiveness which sets the truth apart from falsehood, and the false kept separate from the truth,
 5   as what it is.
 6   W-pI.152.6. Is it not strange that you believe to think you made the world you see is 
 7   arrogance? 2 God made it not. 3 Of this you can be sure. 4 What can He know of the ephemeral, 
 8   the sinful and the guilty, the afraid, the suffering and lonely, and the mind that lives 
 9   within a body that must die? 5 You but accuse Him of insanity, to think He made a world where
10   such things seem to have reality. 6 He is not mad. 7 Yet only madness makes a world 
11   like this.
12   W-pI.152.7. To think that God made chaos, contradicts His Will, invented opposites to 
13   truth, and suffers death to triumph over life; all this is arrogance. 2 Humility would see 
14   at once these things are not of Him. 3 And can you see what God created not? 4 To think 
15   you can is merely to believe you can perceive what God willed not to be. 5 And what could 
16   be more arrogant than this?
17   W-pI.152.8. Let us today be truly humble, and accept what we have made as what it is. 2
18   The power of decision is our own. 3 Decide but to accept your rightful place as 
19   co-creator of the universe, and all you think you made will disappear. 4 What rises to awareness 
20   then will be all that there ever was, eternally as it is now. 5 And it will take the place 
21   of self-deceptions made but to usurp the altar to the Father and the Son.
22   W-pI.152.9. Today we practice true humility, abandoning the false pretense by which the
23   ego seeks to prove it arrogant. 2 Only the ego can be arrogant. 3 But truth is humble 
24   in acknowledging its mightiness, its changelessness and its eternal wholeness, 
25   all-encompassing, God's perfect gift to His beloved Son. 4 We lay aside the arrogance which says that 
26   we are sinners, guilty and afraid, ashamed of what we are; and lift our hearts in true 
27   humility instead to Him Who has created us immaculate, like to Himself in power and in love.
28   W-pI.152.10. The power of decision is our own. 2 And we accept of Him that which we are,
29    and humbly recognize the Son of God. 3 To recognize God's Son implies as well that all
30   self-concepts have been laid aside, and recognized as false. 4 Their arrogance has been
31   perceived. 5 And in humility the radiance of God's Son, his gentleness, his perfect 
32   sinlessness, his Father's Love, his right to Heaven and release from hell, are joyously accepted 
33   as our own.
34   W-pI.152.11. Now do we join in glad acknowledgment that lies are false, and only truth 
35   is true. 2 We think of truth alone as we arise, and spend five minutes practicing its 
36   ways, encouraging our frightened minds with this: 
37   
38   3 The power of decision is my own. 4 This day I will accept myself as what my Father's 
39   Will created me to be. 
40   
41   5 Then will we wait in silence, giving up all self-deceptions, as we humbly ask our 
42   Self that He reveal Himself to us. 6 And He Who never left will come again to our awareness,
43    grateful to restore His home to God, as it was meant to be.
44   W-pI.152.12. In patience wait for Him throughout the day, and hourly invite Him with 
45   the words with which the day began, concluding it with this same invitation to your Self. 
46   2 God's Voice will answer, for He speaks for you and for your Father. 3 He will 
47   substitute the peace of God for all your frantic thoughts, the truth of God for self-deceptions, 
48   and God's Son for your illusions of yourself.
