0553
 1   
 2   LESSON 153.
 3   In my defenselessness my safety lies.
 4   W-pI.153.1. You who feel threatened by this changing world, its twists of fortune and 
 5   its bitter jests, its brief relationships and all the "gifts" it merely lends to take away
 6   again; attend this lesson well. 2 The world provides no safety. 3 It is rooted in 
 7   attack, and all its "gifts" of seeming safety are illusory deceptions. 4 It attacks, and then
 8   attacks again. 5 No peace of mind is possible where danger threatens thus.
 9   W-pI.153.2. The world gives rise but to defensiveness. 2 For threat brings anger, anger
10   makes attack seem reasonable, honestly provoked, and righteous in the name of 
11   self-defense. 3 Yet is defensiveness a double threat. 4 For it attests to weakness, and sets up a 
12   system of defense that cannot work. 5 Now are the weak still further undermined, for there is
13   treachery without and still a greater treachery within. 6 The mind is now confused, and
14   knows not where to turn to find escape from its imaginings.
15   W-pI.153.3. It is as if a circle held it fast, wherein another circle bound it and 
16   another one in that, until escape no longer can be hoped for nor obtained. 2 Attack, defense; 
17   defense, attack, become the circles of the hours and the days that bind the mind in heavy 
18   bands of steel with iron overlaid, returning but to start again. 3 There seems to be no 
19   break nor ending in the ever-tightening grip of the imprisonment upon the mind.
20   W-pI.153.4. Defenses are the costliest of all the prices which the ego would exact. 2 
21   In them lies madness in a form so grim that hope of sanity seems but to be an idle dream,
22   beyond the possible. 3 The sense of threat the world encourages is so much deeper, and 
23   so far beyond the frenzy and intensity of which you can conceive, that you have no idea 
24   of all the devastation it has wrought.
25   W-pI.153.5. You are its slave. 2 You know not what you do, in fear of it. 3 You do not 
26   understand how much you have been made to sacrifice, who feel its iron grip upon your heart. 4 
27   You do not realize what you have done to sabotage the holy peace of God by your 
28   defensiveness. 5 For you behold the Son of God as but a victim to attack by fantasies, by dreams, 
29   and by illusions he has made; yet helpless in their presence, needful only of defense by 
30   still more fantasies, and dreams by which illusions of his safety comfort him.
31   W-pI.153.6. Defenselessness is strength. 2 It testifies to recognition of the Christ in
32   you. 3 Perhaps you will recall the text maintains that choice is always made between 
33   Christ's strength and your own weakness, seen apart from Him. 4 Defenselessness can never be 
34   attacked, because it recognizes strength so great attack is folly, or a silly game a tired 
35   child might play, when he becomes too sleepy to remember what he wants.
36   W-pI.153.7. Defensiveness is weakness. 2 It proclaims you have denied the Christ and 
37   come to fear His Father's anger. 3 What can save you now from your delusion of an angry god,
38    whose fearful image you believe you see at work in all the evils of the world? 4 What 
39   but illusions could defend you now, when it is but illusions that you fight?
40   W-pI.153.8. We will not play such childish games today. 2 For our true purpose is to 
41   save the world, and we would not exchange for foolishness the endless joy our function 
42   offers us. 3 We would not let our happiness slip by because a fragment of a senseless dream 
43   happened to cross our minds, and we mistook the figures in it for the Son of God; its tiny 
44   instant for eternity.
45   W-pI.153.9. We look past dreams today, and recognize that we need no defense because we
46   are created unassailable, without all thought or wish or dream in which attack has any 
47   meaning. 2 Now we cannot fear, for we have left all fearful thoughts behind. 3 And in 
48   defenselessness we stand secure, serenely certain of our safety now, sure of salvation; sure we will 
49   fulfill our chosen purpose, as our ministry extends its holy blessing through the world.
50   W-pI.153.10. Be still a moment, and in silence think how holy is your purpose, how 
0554
 1   secure you rest, untouchable within its light. 2 God's ministers have chosen that the truth 
 2   be with them. 3 Who is holier than they? 4 Who could be surer that his happiness is fully
 3   guaranteed? 5 And who could be more mightily protected? 6 What defense could possibly 
 4   be needed by the ones who are among the chosen ones of God, by His election and their own
 5   as well?
 6   W-pI.153.11. It is the function of God's ministers to help their brothers choose as 
 7   they have done. 2 God has elected all, but few have come to realize His Will is but their 
 8   own. 3 And while you fail to teach what you have learned, salvation waits and darkness 
 9   holds the world in grim imprisonment. 4 Nor will you learn that light has come to you, and 
10   your escape has been accomplished. 5 For you will not see the light, until you offer it to 
11   all your brothers. 6 As they take it from your hands, so will you recognize it as your own.
12   
13   W-pI.153.12. Salvation can be thought of as a game that happy children play. 2 It was 
14   designed by One Who loves His children, and Who would replace their fearful toys with joyous 
15   games, which teach them that the game of fear is gone. 3 His game instructs in happiness 
16   because there is no loser. 4 Everyone who plays must win, and in his winning is the gain to 
17   everyone ensured. 5 The game of fear is gladly laid aside, when children come to see the 
18   benefits salvation brings.
19   W-pI.153.13. You who have played that you are lost to hope, abandoned by your Father, 
20   left alone in terror in a fearful world made mad by sin and guilt; be happy now. 2 That 
21   game is over. 3 Now a quiet time has come, in which we put away the toys of guilt, and lock
22   our quaint and childish thoughts of sin forever from the pure and holy minds of 
23   Heaven's children and the Son of God.
24   W-pI.153.14. We pause but for a moment more, to play our final, happy game upon this 
25   earth. 2 And then we go to take our rightful place where truth abides and games are 
26   meaningless. 3 So is the story ended. 4 Let this day bring the last chapter closer to the world, 
27   that everyone may learn the tale he reads of terrifying destiny, defeat of all his hopes, 
28   his pitiful defense against a vengeance he can not escape, is but his own deluded fantasy.
29   5 God's ministers have come to waken him from the dark dreams this story has evoked in 
30   his confused, bewildered memory of this distorted tale. 6 God's Son can smile at last, on 
31   learning that it is not true.
32   W-pI.153.15. Today we practice in a form we will maintain for quite a while. 2 We will 
33   begin each day by giving our attention to the daily thought as long as possible. 3 Five 
34   minutes now becomes the least we give to preparation for a day in which salvation is the only 
35   goal we have. 4 Ten would be better; fifteen better still. 5 And as distraction ceases to 
36   arise to turn us from our purpose, we will find that half an hour is too short a time to 
37   spend with God. 6 Nor will we willingly give less at night, in gratitude and joy.
38   W-pI.153.16. Each hour adds to our increasing peace, as we remember to be faithful to 
39   the Will we share with God. 2 At times, perhaps, a minute, even less, will be the most 
40   that we can offer as the hour strikes. 3 Sometimes we will forget. 4 At other times the 
41   business of the world will close on us, and we will be unable to withdraw a little while, and 
42   turn our thoughts to God.
43   W-pI.153.17. Yet when we can, we will observe our trust as ministers of God, in hourly 
44   remembrance of our mission and His Love. 2 And we will quietly sit by and wait on Him and listen 
45   to His Voice, and learn what He would have us do the hour that is yet to come; while 
46   thanking Him for all the gifts He gave us in the one gone by.
47   W-pI.153.18. In time, with practice, you will never cease to think of Him, and hear His
48   loving Voice guiding your footsteps into quiet ways, where you will walk in true 
49   defenselessness. 2 For you will know that Heaven goes with you. 3 Nor would you keep your mind away 
50   from Him a moment, even though your time is spent in offering salvation to the world. 4 
0555
 1   Think you He will not make this possible, for you who chose to carry out His plan for the 
 2   salvation of the world and yours?
 3   W-pI.153.19. Today our theme is our defenselessness. 2 We clothe ourselves in it, as we
 4   prepare to meet the day. 3 We rise up strong in Christ, and let our weakness disappear,
 5   as we remember that His strength abides in us. 4 We will remind ourselves that He 
 6   remains beside us through the day, and never leaves our weakness unsupported by His strength. 
 7   5 We call upon His strength each time we feel the threat of our defenses undermine our 
 8   certainty of purpose. 6 We will pause a moment, as He tells us, "I am here."
 9   W-pI.153.20. Your practicing will now begin to take the earnestness of love, to help 
10   you keep your mind from wandering from its intent. 2 Be not afraid nor timid. 3 There can 
11   be no doubt that you will reach your final goal. 4 The ministers of God can never fail, 
12   because the love and strength and peace that shine from them to all their brothers come from 
13   Him. 5 These are His gifts to you. 6 Defenselessness is all you need to give Him in return.
14    7 You lay aside but what was never real, to look on Christ and see His sinlessness.
