50   LESSON 160.
0563
 1   
 2   I am at home. Fear is the stranger here.
 3   W-pI.160.1. Fear is a stranger to the ways of love. 2 Identify with fear, and you will 
 4   be a stranger to yourself. 3 And thus you are unknown to you. 4 What is your Self remains
 5   an alien to the part of you which thinks that it is real, but different from yourself. 
 6   5 Who could be sane in such a circumstance? 6 Who but a madman could believe he is what 
 7   he is not, and judge against himself?
 8   W-pI.160.2. There is a stranger in our midst, who comes from an idea so foreign to the 
 9   truth he speaks a different language, looks upon a world truth does not know, and 
10   understands what truth regards as senseless. 2 Stranger yet, he does not recognize to whom he 
11   comes, and yet maintains his home belongs to him, while he is alien now who is at home. 3 
12   And yet, how easy it would be to say, "This is my home. 4 Here I belong, and will not 
13   leave because a madman says I must."
14   W-pI.160.3. What reason is there for not saying this? 2 What could the reason be except
15   that you had asked this stranger in to take your place, and let you be a stranger to 
16   yourself? 3 No one would let himself be dispossessed so needlessly, unless he thought there 
17   were another home more suited to his tastes.
18   W-pI.160.4. Who is the stranger? 2 Is it fear or you who are unsuited to the home which
19   God provided for His Son? 3 Is fear His Own, created in His likeness? 4 Is it fear that
20   love completes, and is completed by? 5 There is no home can shelter love and fear. 6 
21   They cannot coexist. 7 If you are real, then fear must be illusion. 8 And if fear is real, 
22   then you do not exist at all.
23   W-pI.160.5. How simply, then, the question is resolved. 2 Who fears has but denied 
24   himself and said, "I am the stranger here. 3 And so I leave my home to one more like me than 
25   myself, and give him all I thought belonged to me." 4 Now is he exiled of necessity, not 
26   knowing who he is, uncertain of all things but this; that he is not himself, and that his home
27   has been denied to him.
28   W-pI.160.6. What does he search for now? 2 What can he find? 3 A stranger to himself 
29   can find no home wherever he may look, for he has made return impossible. 4 His way is 
30   lost, except a miracle will search him out and show him that he is no stranger now. 5 The 
31   miracle will come. 6 For in his home his Self remains. 7 It asked no stranger in, and took no 
32   alien thought to be Itself. 8 And It will call Its Own unto Itself in recognition of what is
33   Its Own.
34   W-pI.160.7. Who is the stranger? 2 Is he not the one your Self calls not? 3 You are 
35   unable now to recognize this stranger in your midst, for you have given him your rightful 
36   place. 4 Yet is your Self as certain of Its Own as God is of His Son. 5 He cannot be 
37   confused about creation. 6 He is sure of what belongs to Him. 7 No stranger can be interposed 
38   between His knowledge and His Son's reality. 8 He does not know of strangers. 9 He is certain 
39   of His Son.
40   W-pI.160.8. God's certainty suffices. 2 Who He knows to be His Son belongs where He has
41   set His Son forever. 3 He has answered you who ask, "Who is the stranger?" 4 Hear His 
42   Voice assure you, quietly and sure, that you are not a stranger to your Father, nor is your 
43   Creator stranger made to you. 5 Whom God has joined remain forever one, at home in Him, no 
44   stranger to Himself.
45   W-pI.160.9. Today we offer thanks that Christ has come to search the world for what 
46   belongs to Him. 2 His vision sees no strangers, but beholds His Own and joyously unites with 
47   them. 3 They see Him as a stranger, for they do not recognize themselves. 4 Yet as they 
48   give Him welcome, they remember. 5 And He leads them gently home again, where they belong.
49   W-pI.160.10. Not one does Christ forget. 2 Not one He fails to give you to remember, 
50   that your home may be complete and perfect as it was established. 3 He has not forgotten 
0564
 1   you. 4 But you will not remember Him until you look on all as He does. 5 Who denies his 
 2   brother is denying Him, and thus refusing to accept the gift of sight by which his Self is 
 3   clearly recognized, his home remembered and salvation come.
 4   
 5   
 6   
 7   LESSON 161.
 8   
 9   Give me your blessing, holy Son of God.
10   W-pI.161.1. Today we practice differently, and take a stand against our anger, that our
11   fears may disappear and offer room to love. 2 Here is salvation in the simple words in 
12   which we practice with today's idea. 3 Here is the answer to temptation which can never fail
13   to welcome in the Christ where fear and anger had prevailed before. 4 Here is Atonement
14   made complete, the world passed safely by and Heaven now restored. 5 Here is the answer
15   of the Voice for God.
16   W-pI.161.2. Complete abstraction is the natural condition of the mind. 2 But part of it
17   is now unnatural. 3 It does not look on everything as one. 4 It sees instead but 
18   fragments of the whole, for only thus could it invent the partial world you see. 5 The purpose 
19   of all seeing is to show you what you wish to see. 6 All hearing but brings to your mind 
20   the sounds it wants to hear.
21   W-pI.161.3. Thus were specifics made. 2 And now it is specifics we must use in 
22   practicing. 3 We give them to the Holy Spirit, that He may employ them for a purpose which is 
23   different from the one we gave to them. 4 Yet He can use but what we made, to teach us from a 
24   different point of view, so we can see a different use in everything.
25   W-pI.161.4. One brother is all brothers. 2 Every mind contains all minds, for every 
26   mind is one. 3 Such is the truth. 4 Yet do these thoughts make clear the meaning of 
27   creation? 5 Do these words bring perfect clarity with them to you? 6 What can they seem to be 
28   but empty sounds; pretty, perhaps, correct in sentiment, yet fundamentally not understood 
29   nor understandable. 7 The mind that taught itself to think specifically can no longer 
30   grasp abstraction in the sense that it is all-encompassing. 8 We need to see a little, that 
31   we learn a lot.
32   W-pI.161.5. It seems to be the body that we feel limits our freedom, makes us suffer, 
33   and at last puts out our life. 2 Yet bodies are but symbols for a concrete form of fear. 3
34   Fear without symbols calls for no response, for symbols can stand for the meaningless. 
35   4 Love needs no symbols, being true. 5 But fear attaches to specifics, being false.
36   W-pI.161.6. Bodies attack, but minds do not. 2 This thought is surely reminiscent of 
37   our text, where it is often emphasized. 3 This is the reason bodies easily become fear's 
38   symbols. 4 You have many times been urged to look beyond the body, for its sight presents the 
39   symbol of love's "enemy" Christ's vision does not see. 5 The body is the target for attack, 
40   for no one thinks he hates a mind. 6 Yet what but mind directs the body to attack? 7 What 
41   else could be the seat of fear except what thinks of fear?
42   W-pI.161.7. Hate is specific. 2 There must be a thing to be attacked. 3 An enemy must 
43   be perceived in such a form he can be touched and seen and heard, and ultimately killed. 
44   4 When hatred rests upon a thing, it calls for death as surely as God's Voice proclaims 
45   there is no death. 5 Fear is insatiable, consuming everything its eyes behold, seeing itself
46   in everything, compelled to turn upon itself and to destroy.
47   W-pI.161.8. Who sees a brother as a body sees him as fear's symbol. 2 And he will 
48   attack, because what he beholds is his own fear external to himself, poised to attack, and 
49   howling to unite with him again. 3 Mistake not the intensity of rage projected fear must spawn.
50    4 It shrieks in wrath, and claws the air in frantic hope it can reach to its maker and
0565
 1   devour him.
 2   W-pI.161.9. This do the body's eyes behold in one whom Heaven cherishes, the angels 
 3   love and God created perfect. 2 This is his reality. 3 And in Christ's vision is his 
 4   loveliness reflected in a form so holy and so beautiful that you could scarce refrain from 
 5   kneeling at his feet. 4 Yet you will take his hand instead, for you are like him in the sight 
 6   that sees him thus. 5 Attack on him is enemy to you, for you will not perceive that in his 
 7   hands is your salvation. 6 Ask him but for this, and he will give it to you. 7 Ask him not 
 8   to symbolize your fear. 8 Would you request that love destroy itself? 9 Or would you have
 9   it be revealed to you and set you free?
10   W-pI.161.10. Today we practice in a form we have attempted earlier. 2 Your readiness is
11   closer now, and you will come today nearer Christ's vision. 3 If you are intent on 
12   reaching it, you will succeed today. 4 And once you have succeeded, you will not be willing to 
13   accept the witnesses your body's eyes call forth. 5 What you will see will sing to you of 
14   ancient melodies you will remember. 6 You are not forgot in Heaven. 7 Would you not remember 
15   it?
16   W-pI.161.11. Select one brother, symbol of the rest, and ask salvation of him. 2 See 
17   him first as clearly as you can, in that same form to which you are accustomed. 3 See his 
18   face, his hands and feet, his clothing. 4 Watch him smile, and see familiar gestures which 
19   he makes so frequently. 5 Then think of this: What you are seeing now conceals from you 
20   the sight of one who can forgive you all your sins; whose sacred hands can take away the 
21   nails which pierce your own, and lift the crown of thorns which you have placed upon your 
22   bleeding head. 6 Ask this of him, that he may set you free: 
23   
24   7 Give me your blessing, holy Son of God. 8 I would behold you with the eyes of Christ,
25   and see my perfect sinlessness in you.
26   
27   W-pI.161.12. And He will answer Whom you called upon. 2 For He will hear the Voice for 
28   God in you, and answer in your own. 3 Behold him now, whom you have seen as merely flesh 
29   and bone, and recognize that Christ has come to you. 4 Today's idea is your safe escape 
30   from anger and from fear. 5 Be sure you use it instantly, should you be tempted to attack a
31   brother and perceive in him the symbol of your fear. 6 And you will see him suddenly 
32   transformed from enemy to savior; from the devil into Christ.
