35   
36   LESSON 162.
37   
38   I am as God created me.
39   W-pI.162.1. This single thought, held firmly in the mind, would save the world. 2 From 
40   time to time we will repeat it, as we reach another stage in learning. 3 It will mean far 
41   more to you as you advance. 4 These words are sacred, for they are the words God gave in 
42   answer to the world you made. 5 By them it disappears, and all things seen within its misty 
43   clouds and vaporous illusions vanish as these words are spoken. 6 For they come from God.
44   W-pI.162.2. Here is the Word by which the Son became his Father's happiness, His Love 
45   and His completion. 2 Here creation is proclaimed, and honored as it is. 3 There is no 
46   dream these words will not dispel; no thought of sin and no illusion which the dream 
47   contains that will not fade away before their might. 4 They are the trumpet of awakening that 
48   sounds around the world. 5 The dead awake in answer to its call. 6 And those who live and 
49   hear this sound will never look on death.
50   W-pI.162.3. Holy indeed is he who makes these words his own; arising with them in his 
0566
 1   mind, recalling them throughout the day, at night bringing them with him as he goes to 
 2   sleep. 2 His dreams are happy and his rest secure, his safety certain and his body healed, 
 3   because he sleeps and wakens with the truth before him always. 3 He will save the world, 
 4   because he gives the world what he receives each time he practices the words of truth.
 5   W-pI.162.4. Today we practice simply. 2 For the words we use are mighty, and they need 
 6   no thoughts beyond themselves to change the mind of him who uses them. 3 So wholly is it 
 7   changed that it is now the treasury in which God places all His gifts and all His Love, to be 
 8   distributed to all the world, increased in giving; kept complete because its sharing is unlimited.
 9   4 And thus you learn to think with God. 5 Christ's vision has restored your sight by 
10   salvaging your mind.
11   W-pI.162.5. We honor you today. 2 Yours is the right to perfect holiness you now accept.
12    3 With this acceptance is salvation brought to everyone, for who could cherish sin 
13   when holiness like this has blessed the world? 4 Who could despair when perfect joy is 
14   yours, available to all as remedy for grief and misery, all sense of loss, and for complete 
15   escape from sin and guilt?
16   W-pI.162.6. And who would not be brother to you now; you, his redeemer and his savior. 
17   2 Who could fail to welcome you into his heart with loving invitation, eager to unite 
18   with one like him in holiness? 3 You are as God created you. 4 These words dispel the night,
19    and darkness is no more. 5 The light is come today to bless the world. 6 For you have 
20   recognized the Son of God, and in that recognition is the world's.
21   
22   
23   
24   LESSON 163.
25   
26   There is no death. The Son of God is free.
27   W-pI.163.1. Death is a thought that takes on many forms, often unrecognized. 2 It may 
28   appear as sadness, fear, anxiety or doubt; as anger, faithlessness and lack of trust; concern
29   for bodies, envy, and all forms in which the wish to be as you are not may come to 
30   tempt you. 3 All such thoughts are but reflections of the worshipping of death as savior and
31   as giver of release.
32   W-pI.163.2. Embodiment of fear, the host of sin, god of the guilty and the lord of all 
33   illusions and deceptions, does the thought of death seem mighty. 2 For it seems to hold all 
34   living things within its withered hand; all hopes and wishes in its blighting grasp; all 
35   goals perceived but in its sightless eyes. 3 The frail, the helpless and the sick bow down 
36   before its image, thinking it alone is real, inevitable, worthy of their trust. 4 For it 
37   alone will surely come.
38   W-pI.163.3. All things but death are seen to be unsure, too quickly lost however hard 
39   to gain, uncertain in their outcome, apt to fail the hopes they once engendered, and to 
40   leave the taste of dust and ashes in their wake, in place of aspirations and of dreams. 2 
41   But death is counted on. 3 For it will come with certain footsteps when the time has come 
42   for its arrival. 4 It will never fail to take all life as hostage to itself.
43   W-pI.163.4. Would you bow down to idols such as this? 2 Here is the strength and might 
44   of God Himself perceived within an idol made of dust. 3 Here is the opposite of God 
45   proclaimed as lord of all creation, stronger than God's Will for life, the endlessness of love 
46   and Heaven's perfect, changeless constancy. 4 Here is the Will of Father and of Son 
47   defeated finally, and laid to rest beneath the headstone death has placed upon the body of the 
48   holy Son of God.
49   W-pI.163.5. Unholy in defeat, he has become what death would have him be. 2 His epitaph,
50    which death itself has written, gives no name to him, for he has passed to dust. 3 It 
0567
 1   says but this: "Here lies a witness God is dead." 4 And this it writes again and still 
 2   again, while all the while its worshippers agree, and kneeling down with foreheads to the 
 3   ground, they whisper fearfully that it is so.
 4   W-pI.163.6. It is impossible to worship death in any form, and still select a few you 
 5   would not cherish and would yet avoid, while still believing in the rest. 2 For death is 
 6   total. 3 Either all things die, or else they live and cannot die. 4 No compromise is 
 7   possible. 5 For here again we see an obvious position, which we must accept if we be sane; what
 8   contradicts one thought entirely can not be true, unless its opposite is proven false.
 9   W-pI.163.7. The idea of the death of God is so preposterous that even the insane have 
10   difficulty in believing it. 2 For it implies that God was once alive and somehow perished; killed,
11    apparently, by those who did not want Him to survive. 3 Their stronger will could 
12   triumph over His, and so eternal life gave way to death. 4 And with the Father died the Son as
13   well.
14   W-pI.163.8. Death's worshippers may be afraid. 2 And yet, can thoughts like these be 
15   fearful? 3 If they saw that it is only this which they believe, they would be instantly 
16   released. 4 And you will show them this today. 5 There is no death, and we renounce it now in 
17   every form, for their salvation and our own as well. 6 God made not death. 7 Whatever form 
18   it takes must therefore be illusion. 8 This the stand we take today. 9 And it is given us
19   to look past death, and see the life beyond.
20   
21   W-pI.163.9.  <Our Father, bless our eyes today. 2 We are Your messengers, and we would 
22   look upon the glorious reflection of Your Love which shines in everything. 3 We live and 
23   move in You alone. 4 We are not separate from Your eternal life. 5 There is no death, for 
24   death is not Your Will. 6 And we abide where You have placed us, in the life we share with 
25   You and with all living things, to be like You and part of You forever. 7 We accept Your 
26   Thoughts as ours, and our will is one with Yours eternally. 8 Amen.>
