31   
32   
33   LESSON 166.
34   
35   I am entrusted with the gifts of God.
36   W-pI.166.1. All things are given you. 2 God's trust in you is limitless. 3 He knows His
37   Son. 4 He gives without exception, holding nothing back that can contribute to your 
38   happiness. 5 And yet, unless your will is one with His, His gifts are not received. 6 But what 
39   would make you think there is another will than His?
40   W-pI.166.2. Here is the paradox that underlies the making of the world. 2 This world is
41   not the Will of God, and so it is not real. 3 Yet those who think it real must still 
42   believe there is another will, and one that leads to opposite effects from those He wills. 4 
43   Impossible indeed; but every mind that looks upon the world and judges it as certain, solid, 
44   trustworthy and true believes in two creators; or in one, himself alone. 5 But never in one God.
45   W-pI.166.3. The gifts of God are not acceptable to anyone who holds such strange 
46   beliefs. 2 He must believe that to accept God's gifts, however evident they may become, 
47   however urgently he may be called to claim them as his own, is to be pressed to treachery 
48   against himself. 3 He must deny their presence, contradict the truth, and suffer to preserve 
49   the world he made.
50   W-pI.166.4. Here is the only home he thinks he knows. 2 Here is the only safety he 
0570
 1   believes that he can find. 3 Without the world he made is he an outcast; homeless and afraid. 4
 2   He does not realize that it is here he is afraid indeed, and homeless, too; an outcast 
 3   wandering so far from home, so long away, he does not realize he has forgotten where he came 
 4   from, where he goes, and even who he really is.
 5   W-pI.166.5. Yet in his lonely, senseless wanderings, God's gifts go with him, all 
 6   unknown to him. 2 He cannot lose them. 3 But he will not look at what is given him. 4 He 
 7   wanders on, aware of the futility he sees about him everywhere, perceiving how his little lot 
 8   but dwindles, as he goes ahead to nowhere. 5 Still he wanders on in misery and poverty, 
 9   alone though God is with him, and a treasure his so great that everything the world contains
10   is valueless before its magnitude.
11   W-pI.166.6. He seems a sorry figure; weary, worn, in threadbare clothing, and with feet
12   that bleed a little from the rocky road he walks. 2 No one but has identified with him,
13   for everyone who comes here has pursued the path he follows, and has felt defeat and 
14   hopelessness as he is feeling them. 3 Yet is he really tragic, when you see that he is following 
15   the way he chose, and need but realize Who walks with him and open up his treasures to be 
16   free?
17   W-pI.166.7. This is your chosen self, the one you made as a replacement for reality. 2 
18   This is the self you savagely defend against all reason, every evidence, and all the 
19   witnesses with proof to show this is not you. 3 You heed them not. 4 You go on your appointed 
20   way, with eyes cast down lest you might catch a glimpse of truth, and be released from 
21   self-deception and set free.
22   W-pI.166.8. You cower fearfully lest you should feel Christ's touch upon your shoulder,
23   and perceive His gentle hand directing you to look upon your gifts. 2 How could you 
24   then proclaim your poverty in exile? 3 He would make you laugh at this perception of 
25   yourself. 4 Where is self-pity then? 5 And what becomes of all the tragedy you sought to make 
26   for him whom God intended only joy?
27   W-pI.166.9. Your ancient fear has come upon you now, and justice has caught up with you
28   at last. 2 Christ's hand has touched your shoulder, and you feel that you are not alone.
29    3 You even think the miserable self you thought was you may not be your Identity. 4 
30   Perhaps God's Word is truer than your own. 5 Perhaps His gifts to you are real. 6 Perhaps He 
31   has not wholly been outwitted by your plan to keep His Son in deep oblivion, and go the 
32   way you chose without your Self.
33   W-pI.166.10. God's Will does not oppose. 2 It merely is. 3 It is not God you have 
34   imprisoned in your plan to lose your Self. 4 He does not know about a plan so alien to His Will. 
35   5 There was a need He did not understand, to which He gave an Answer. 6 That is all. 7 
36   And you who have this Answer given you have need no more of anything but this.
37   W-pI.166.11. Now do we live, for now we cannot die. 2 The wish for death is answered, 
38   and the sight that looked upon it now has been replaced by vision which perceives that you
39   are not what you pretend to be. 3 One walks with you Who gently answers all your fears 
40   with this one merciful reply, "It is not so." 4 He points to all the gifts you have each 
41   time the thought of poverty oppresses you, and speaks of His Companionship when you 
42   perceive yourself as lonely and afraid.
43   W-pI.166.12. Yet He reminds you still of one thing more you had forgotten. 2 For His 
44   touch on you has made you like Himself. 3 The gifts you have are not for you alone. 4 What 
45   He has come to offer you, you now must learn to give. 5 This is the lesson that His 
46   giving holds, for He has saved you from the solitude you sought to make in which to hide from
47   God. 6 He has reminded you of all the gifts that God has given you. 7 He speaks as well
48   of what becomes your will when you accept these gifts, and recognize they are your own.
49   W-pI.166.13. The gifts are yours, entrusted to your care, to give to all who chose the 
50   lonely road you have escaped. 2 They do not understand they but pursue their wishes. 3 It is 
0571
 1   you who teach them now. 4 For you have learned of Christ there is another way for them to 
 2   walk. 5 Teach them by showing them the happiness that comes to those who feel the touch of 
 3   Christ, and recognize God's gifts. 6 Let sorrow not tempt you to be unfaithful to your trust.
 4   W-pI.166.14. Your sighs will now betray the hopes of those who look to you for their 
 5   release. 2 Your tears are theirs. 3 If you are sick, you but withhold their healing. 4 What 
 6   you fear but teaches them their fears are justified. 5 Your hand becomes the giver of 
 7   Christ's touch; your change of mind becomes the proof that who accepts God's gifts can never 
 8   suffer anything. 6 You are entrusted with the world's release from pain.
 9   W-pI.166.15. Betray it not. 2 Become the living proof of what Christ's touch can offer 
10   everyone. 3 God has entrusted all His gifts to you. 4 Be witness in your happiness to how 
11   transformed the mind becomes which chooses to accept His gifts, and feel the touch of Christ. 5 
12   Such is your mission now. 6 For God entrusts the giving of His gifts to all who have 
13   received them. 7 He has shared His joy with you. 8 And now you go to share it with the world.
14   
15   
16   
17   LESSON 167.
18   
19   There is one life, and that I share with God.
20   W-pI.167.1. There are not different kinds of life, for life is like the truth. 2 It 
21   does not have degrees. 3 It is the one condition in which all that God created share. 4 
22   Like all His Thoughts, it has no opposite. 5 There is no death because what God created 
23   shares His life. 6 There is no death because an opposite to God does not exist. 7 There is no
24   death because the Father and the Son are One.
25   W-pI.167.2. In this world, there appears to be a state that is life's opposite. 2 You 
26   call it death. 3 Yet we have learned that the idea of death takes many forms. 4 It is the 
27   one idea which underlies all feelings that are not supremely happy. 5 It is the alarm to 
28   which you give response of any kind that is not perfect joy. 6 All sorrow, loss, anxiety and
29   suffering and pain, even a little sigh of weariness, a slight discomfort or the merest 
30   frown, acknowledge death. 7 And thus deny you live.
31   W-pI.167.3. You think that death is of the body. 2 Yet it is but an idea, irrelevant to
32   what is seen as physical. 3 A thought is in the mind. 4 It can be then applied as mind 
33   directs it. 5 But its origin is where it must be changed, if change occurs. 6 Ideas leave not 
34   their source. 7 The emphasis this course has placed on that idea is due to its centrality in
35   our attempts to change your mind about yourself. 8 It is the reason you can heal. 9 It 
36   is the cause of healing. 10 It is why you cannot die. 11 Its truth established you as one
37   with God.
38   W-pI.167.4. Death is the thought that you are separate from your Creator. 2 It is the 
39   belief conditions change, emotions alternate because of causes you cannot control, you did 
40   not make, and you can never change. 3 It is the fixed belief ideas can leave their source,
41   and take on qualities the source does not contain, becoming different from their own 
42   origin, apart from it in kind as well as distance, time and form.
43   W-pI.167.5. Death cannot come from life. 2 Ideas remain united to their source. 3 They 
44   can extend all that their source contains. 4 In that, they can go far beyond themselves. 5
45   But they can not give birth to what was never given them. 6 As they are made, so will 
46   their making be. 7 As they were born, so will they then give birth. 8 And where they come 
47   from, there will they return.
48   W-pI.167.6. The mind can think it sleeps, but that is all. 2 It cannot change what is 
49   its waking state. 3 It cannot make a body, nor abide within a body. 4 What is alien to the
50   mind does not exist, because it has no source. 5 For mind creates all things that are, 
0572
 1   and cannot give them attributes it lacks, nor change its own eternal, mindful state. 6 It 
 2   cannot make the physical. 7 What seems to die is but the sign of mind asleep.
 3   W-pI.167.7. The opposite of life can only be another form of life. 2 As such, it can be
 4   reconciled with what created it, because it is not opposite in truth. 3 Its form may 
 5   change; it may appear to be what it is not. 4 Yet mind is mind, awake or sleeping. 5 It is 
 6   not its opposite in anything created, nor in what it seems to make when it believes it 
 7   sleeps.
 8   W-pI.167.8. God creates only mind awake. 2 He does not sleep, and His creations cannot 
 9   share what He gives not, nor make conditions which He does not share with them. 3 The 
10   thought of death is not the opposite to thoughts of life. 4 Forever unopposed by opposites of 
11   any kind, the Thoughts of God remain forever changeless, with the power to extend forever 
12   changelessly, but yet within themselves, for they are everywhere.
13   W-pI.167.9. What seems to be the opposite of life is merely sleeping. 2 When the mind 
14   elects to be what it is not, and to assume an alien power which it does not have, a foreign 
15   state it cannot enter, or a false condition not within its Source, it merely seems to go to 
16   sleep a while. 3 It dreams of time; an interval in which what seems to happen never has 
17   occurred, the changes wrought are substanceless, and all events are nowhere. 4 When the mind 
18   awakes, it but continues as it always was.
19   W-pI.167.10. Let us today be children of the truth, and not deny our holy heritage. 2 
20   Our life is not as we imagine it. 3 Who changes life because he shuts his eyes, or makes 
21   himself what he is not because he sleeps, and sees in dreams an opposite to what he is? 4 We 
22   will not ask for death in any form today. 5 Nor will we let imagined opposites to life 
23   abide even an instant where the Thought of life eternal has been set by God Himself.
24   W-pI.167.11. His holy home we strive to keep today as He established it, and wills it 
25   be forever and forever. 2 He is Lord of what we think today. 3 And in His Thoughts, which
26   have no opposite, we understand there is one life, and that we share with Him, with all
27   creation, with their thoughts as well, whom He created in a unity of life that cannot 
28   separate in death and leave the Source of life from where it came.
29   W-pI.167.12. We share one life because we have one Source, a Source from which 
30   perfection comes to us, remaining always in the holy minds which He created perfect. 2 As we were,
31    so are we now and will forever be. 3 A sleeping mind must waken, as it sees its own 
32   perfection mirroring the Lord of life so perfectly it fades into what is reflected there. 4 And 
33   now it is no more a mere reflection. 5 It becomes the thing reflected, and the light which
34   makes reflection possible. 6 No vision now is needed. 7 For the wakened mind is one 
35   that knows its Source, its Self, its Holiness.
36   
37   
38   
39   LESSON 168.
40   
41   Your grace is given me. I claim it now.
42   W-pI.168.1. God speaks to us. 2 Shall we not speak to Him? 3 He is not distant. 4 He 
43   makes no attempt to hide from us. 5 We try to hide from Him, and suffer from deception. 6 He
44   remains entirely accessible. 7 He loves His Son. 8 There is no certainty but this, yet 
45   this suffices. 9 He will love His Son forever. 10 When his mind remains asleep, He loves 
46   him still. 11 And when his mind awakes, He loves him with a never-changing Love.
47   W-pI.168.2. If you but knew the meaning of His Love, hope and despair would be 
48   impossible. 2 For hope would be forever satisfied; despair of any kind unthinkable. 3 His grace 
49   His answer is to all despair, for in it lies remembrance of His Love. 4 Would He not 
50   gladly give the means by which His Will is recognized? 5 His grace is yours by your 
0573
 1   acknowledgment. 6 And memory of Him awakens in the mind that asks the means of Him whereby its sleep 
 2   is done.
 3   W-pI.168.3. Today we ask of God the gift He has most carefully preserved within our 
 4   hearts, waiting to be acknowledged. 2 This the gift by which God leans to us and lifts us up,
 5   taking salvation's final step Himself. 3 All steps but this we learn, instructed by His
 6   Voice. 4 But finally He comes Himself, and takes us in His Arms and sweeps away the 
 7   cobwebs of our sleep. 5 His gift of grace is more than just an answer. 6 It restores all 
 8   memories the sleeping mind forgot; all certainty of what Love's meaning is.
 9   W-pI.168.4. God loves His Son. 2 Request Him now to give the means by which this world 
10   will disappear, and vision first will come, with knowledge but an instant later. 3 For in 
11   grace you see a light that covers all the world in love, and watch fear disappear from every
12   face as hearts rise up and claim the light as theirs. 4 What now remains that Heaven be
13   delayed an instant longer? 5 What is still undone when your forgiveness rests on 
14   everything?
15   W-pI.168.5. It is a new and holy day today, for we receive what has been given us. 2 
16   Our faith lies in the Giver, not our own acceptance. 3 We acknowledge our mistakes, but He
17   to Whom all error is unknown is yet the One Who answers our mistakes by giving us the 
18   means to lay them down, and rise to Him in gratitude and love.
19   W-pI.168.6. And He descends to meet us, as we come to Him. 2 For what He has prepared 
20   for us He gives and we receive. 3 Such is His Will, because He loves His Son. 4 To Him we 
21   pray today, returning but the word He gave to us through His Own Voice, His Word, His Love:
22   
23   
24   5 Your grace is given me. 6 I claim it now. 7 Father, I come to You. 8 And You will 
25   come to me who ask. 9 I am the Son You love.
26   
27   
28   
29   LESSON 169.
30   
31   By grace I live. By grace I am released.
32   W-pI.169.1. Grace is an aspect of the Love of God which is most like the state 
33   prevailing in the unity of truth. 2 It is the world's most lofty aspiration, for it leads beyond 
34   the world entirely. 3 It is past learning, yet the goal of learning, for grace cannot come
35   until the mind prepares itself for true acceptance. 4 Grace becomes inevitable 
36   instantly in those who have prepared a table where it can be gently laid and willingly received;
37   an altar clean and holy for the gift.
38   W-pI.169.2. Grace is acceptance of the Love of God within a world of seeming hate and 
39   fear. 2 By grace alone the hate and fear are gone, for grace presents a state so opposite 
40   to everything the world contains, that those whose minds are lighted by the gift of grace
41   can not believe the world of fear is real.
42   W-pI.169.3. Grace is not learned. 2 The final step must go beyond all learning. 3 Grace
43   is not the goal this course aspires to attain. 4 Yet we prepare for grace in that an 
44   open mind can hear the Call to waken. 5 It is not shut tight against God's Voice. 6 It has 
45   become aware that there are things it does not know, and thus is ready to accept a state 
46   completely different from experience with which it is familiarly at home.
47   W-pI.169.4. We have perhaps appeared to contradict our statement that the revelation of
48   the Father and the Son as One has been already set. 2 But we have also said the mind 
49   determines when that time will be, and has determined it. 3 And yet we urge you to bear witness 
50   to the Word of God to hasten the experience of truth, and speed its advent into every 
0574
 1   mind that recognizes truth's effects on you.
 2   W-pI.169.5. Oneness is simply the idea God is. 2 And in His Being, He encompasses all 
 3   things. 3 No mind holds anything but Him. 4 We say "God is," and then we cease to speak, for 
 4   in that knowledge words are meaningless. 5 There are no lips to speak them, and no part 
 5   of mind sufficiently distinct to feel that it is now aware of something not itself. 6 It 
 6   has united with its Source. 7 And like its Source Itself, it merely is.
 7   W-pI.169.6. We cannot speak nor write nor even think of this at all. 2 It comes to 
 8   every mind when total recognition that its will is God's has been completely given and 
 9   received completely. 3 It returns the mind into the endless present, where the past and future 
10   cannot be conceived. 4 It lies beyond salvation; past all thought of time, forgiveness and 
11   the holy face of Christ. 5 The Son of God has merely disappeared into his Father, as his 
12   Father has in him. 6 The world has never been at all. 7 Eternity remains a constant state.
13   W-pI.169.7. This is beyond experience we try to hasten. 2 Yet forgiveness, taught and 
14   learned, brings with it the experiences which bear witness that the time the mind itself 
15   determined to abandon all but this is now at hand. 3 We do not hasten it, in that what you will 
16   offer was concealed from Him Who teaches what forgiveness means.
17   W-pI.169.8. All learning was already in His Mind, accomplished and complete. 2 He 
18   recognized all that time holds, and gave it to all minds that each one might determine, from a 
19   point where time was ended, when it is released to revelation and eternity. 3 We have 
20   repeated several times before that you but make a journey that is done.
21   W-pI.169.9. For oneness must be here. 2 Whatever time the mind has set for revelation 
22   is entirely irrelevant to what must be a constant state, forever as it always was; 
23   forever to remain as it is now. 3 We merely take the part assigned long since, and fully 
24   recognized as perfectly fulfilled by Him Who wrote salvation's script in His Creator's Name, and 
25   in the Name of His Creator's Son.
26   W-pI.169.10. There is no need to further clarify what no one in the world can 
27   understand. 2 When revelation of your oneness comes, it will be known and fully understood. 3 Now
28   we have work to do, for those in time can speak of things beyond, and listen to words 
29   which explain what is to come is past already. 4 Yet what meaning can the words convey to 
30   those who count the hours still, and rise and work and go to sleep by them?
31   W-pI.169.11. Suffice it, then, that you have work to do to play your part. 2 The ending
32   must remain obscure to you until your part is done. 3 It does not matter. 4 For your 
33   part is still what all the rest depends on. 5 As you take the role assigned to you, 
34   salvation comes a little nearer each uncertain heart that does not beat as yet in tune with God.
35   W-pI.169.12. Forgiveness is the central theme that runs throughout salvation, holding 
36   all its parts in meaningful relationships, the course it runs directed and its outcome 
37   sure. 2 And now we ask for grace, the final gift salvation can bestow. 3 Experience that 
38   grace provides will end in time, for grace foreshadows Heaven, yet does not replace the 
39   thought of time but for a little while.
40   W-pI.169.13. The interval suffices. 2 It is here that miracles are laid; to be returned
41   by you from holy instants you receive, through grace in your experience, to all who see
42   the light that lingers in your face. 3 What is the face of Christ but his who went a 
43   moment into timelessness, and brought a clear reflection of the unity he felt an instant back
44   to bless the world? 4 How could you finally attain to it forever, while a part of you 
45   remains outside, unknowing, unawakened, and in need of you as witness to the truth?
46   W-pI.169.14. Be grateful to return, as you were glad to go an instant, and accept the 
47   gifts that grace provided you. 2 You carry them back to yourself. 3 And revelation stands 
48   not far behind. 4 Its coming is ensured. 5 We ask for grace, and for experience that comes
49   from grace. 6 We welcome the release it offers everyone. 7 We do not ask for the 
50   unaskable. 8 We do not look beyond what grace can give. 9 For this we can give in the grace that
0575
 1   has been given us.
 2   W-pI.169.15. Our learning goal today does not exceed this prayer. 2 Yet in the world, 
 3   what could be more than what we ask this day of Him Who gives the grace we ask, as it was 
 4   given Him? 
 5   
 6   3 By grace I live. 4 By grace I am released. 
 7   5 By grace I give. 6 By grace I will release.
 8   
 9   
10   
11   LESSON 170.
12   
13   There is no cruelty in God and none in me.
14   W-pI.170.1. No one attacks without intent to hurt. 2 This can have no exception. 3 When
15   you think that you attack in self-defense, you mean that to be cruel is protection; you
16   are safe because of cruelty. 4 You mean that you believe to hurt another brings you 
17   freedom. 5 And you mean that to attack is to exchange the state in which you are for something
18   better, safer, more secure from dangerous invasion and from fear.
19   W-pI.170.2. How thoroughly insane is the idea that to defend from fear is to attack! 2 
20   For here is fear begot and fed with blood, to make it grow and swell and rage. 3 And thus 
21   is fear protected, not escaped. 4 Today we learn a lesson which can save you more delay 
22   and needless misery than you can possibly imagine. 5 It is this: 
23   
24   6 You make what you defend against, and by your own defense against it is it real and 
25   inescapable. 7 Lay down your arms, and only then do you perceive it false.
26   
27   W-pI.170.3. It seems to be the enemy without that you attack. 2 Yet your defense sets 
28   up an enemy within; an alien thought at war with you, depriving you of peace, splitting 
29   your mind into two camps which seem wholly irreconcilable. 3 For love now has an "enemy," 
30   an opposite; and fear, the alien, now needs your defense against the threat of what you 
31   really are.
32   W-pI.170.4. If you consider carefully the means by which your fancied self-defense 
33   proceeds on its imagined way, you will perceive the premises on which the idea stands. 2 First,
34   it is obvious ideas must leave their source, for it is you who make attack, and must 
35   have first conceived of it. 3 Yet you attack outside yourself, and separate your mind from 
36   him who is to be attacked, with perfect faith the split you made is real.
37   W-pI.170.5. Next, are the attributes of love bestowed upon its "enemy." 2 For fear 
38   becomes your safety and protector of your peace, to which you turn for solace and escape from 
39   doubts about your strength, and hope of rest in dreamless quiet. 3 And as love is shorn of 
40   what belongs to it and it alone, love is endowed with attributes of fear. 4 For love would 
41   ask you lay down all defense as merely foolish. 5 And your arms indeed would crumble into 
42   dust. 6 For such they are.
43   W-pI.170.6. With love as enemy, must cruelty become a god. 2 And gods demand that those
44   who worship them obey their dictates, and refuse to question them. 3 Harsh punishment 
45   is meted out relentlessly to those who ask if the demands are sensible or even sane. 4 It
46   is their enemies who are unreasonable and insane, while they are always merciful and 
47   just.
48   W-pI.170.7. Today we look upon this cruel god dispassionately. 2 And we note that 
49   though his lips are smeared with blood, and fire seems to flame from him, he is but made of 
50   stone. 3 He can do nothing. 4 We need not defy his power. 5 He has none. 6 And those who see
0576
 1   in him their safety have no guardian, no strength to call upon in danger, and no mighty
 2   warrior to fight for them.
 3   W-pI.170.8. This moment can be terrible. 2 But it can also be the time of your release 
 4   from abject slavery. 3 You make a choice, standing before this idol, seeing him exactly as 
 5   he is. 4 Will you restore to love what you have sought to wrest from it and lay before 
 6   this mindless piece of stone? 5 Or will you make another idol to replace it? 6 For the god 
 7   of cruelty takes many forms. 7 Another can be found.
 8   W-pI.170.9. Yet do not think that fear is the escape from fear. 2 Let us remember what 
 9   the text has stressed about the obstacles to peace. 3 The final one, the hardest to 
10   believe is nothing, and a seeming obstacle with the appearance of a solid block, impenetrable,
11   fearful and beyond surmounting, is the fear of God Himself. 4 Here is the basic premise
12   which enthrones the thought of fear as god. 5 For fear is loved by those who worship it,
13    and love appears to be invested now with cruelty.
14   W-pI.170.10. Where does the totally insane belief in gods of vengeance come from? 2 
15   Love has not confused its attributes with those of fear. 3 Yet must the worshippers of fear
16   perceive their own confusion in fear's "enemy"; its cruelty as now a part of love. 4 
17   And what becomes more fearful than the Heart of Love Itself? 5 The blood appears to be 
18   upon His Lips; the fire comes from Him. 6 And He is terrible above all else, cruel beyond 
19   conception, striking down all who acknowledge Him to be their God.
20   W-pI.170.11. The choice you make today is certain. 2 For you look for the last time 
21   upon this bit of carven stone you made, and call it god no longer. 3 You have reached this 
22   place before, but you have chosen that this cruel god remain with you in still another form.
23   4 And so the fear of God returned with you. 5 This time you leave it there. 6 And you 
24   return to a new world, unburdened by its weight; beheld not in its sightless eyes, but in the
25   vision that your choice restored to you.
26   W-pI.170.12. Now do your eyes belong to Christ, and He looks through them. 2 Now your 
27   voice belongs to God and echoes His. 3 And now your heart remains at peace forever. 4 You 
28   have chosen Him in place of idols, and your attributes, given by your Creator, are restored
29   to you at last. 5 The Call for God is heard and answered. 6 Now has fear made way for 
30   love, as God Himself replaces cruelty.
31   
32   W-pI.170.13.  <Father, we are like You. 2 No cruelty abides in us, for there is none in
33   You. 3 Your peace is ours. 4 And we bless the world with what we have received from You
34   alone. 5 We choose again, and make our choice for all our brothers, knowing they are 
35   one with us. 6 We bring them Your salvation as we have received it now. 7 And we give 
36   thanks for them who render us complete. 8 In them we see Your glory, and in them we find our 
37   peace. 9 Holy are we because Your Holiness has set us free. 10 And we give thanks. 11 Amen.
38   
39   
