35   Introduction to Lessons 181-200.
36   
37   
38   W-pI.in.181-200.1. Our next few lessons make a special point of firming up your 
39   willingness to make your weak commitment strong; your scattered goals blend into one intent. 2 You
40   are not asked for total dedication all the time as yet. 3 But you are asked to practice
41   now in order to attain the sense of peace such unified commitment will bestow, if only 
42   intermittently. 4 It is experiencing this that makes it sure that you will give your total 
43   willingness to following the way the course sets forth.
44   W-pI.in.181-200.2. Our lessons now are geared specifically to widening horizons, and 
45   direct approaches to the special blocks that keep your vision narrow, and too limited to let 
46   you see the value of our goal. 2 We are attempting now to lift these blocks, however 
47   briefly. 3 Words alone can not convey the sense of liberation which their lifting brings. 4 
48   But the experience of freedom and of peace that comes as you give up your tight control of
49   what you see speaks for itself. 5 Your motivation will be so intensified that words 
50   become of little consequence. 6 You will be sure of what you want, and what is valueless.
0581
 1   W-pI.in.181-200.3. And so we start our journey beyond words by concentrating first on 
 2   what impedes your progress still. 2 Experience of what exists beyond defensiveness remains 
 3   beyond achievement while it is denied. 3 It may be there, but you cannot accept its presence.
 4   4 So we now attempt to go past all defenses for a little while each day. 5 No more than
 5   this is asked, because no more than this is needed. 6 It will be enough to guarantee 
 6   the rest will come.
 7   
 8   
 9   
10   LESSON 181.
11   
12   I trust my brothers, who are one with me.
13   W-pI.181.1. Trusting your brothers is essential to establishing and holding up your 
14   faith in your ability to transcend doubt and lack of sure conviction in yourself. 2 When you
15   attack a brother, you proclaim that he is limited by what you have perceived in him. 3 
16   You do not look beyond his errors. 4 Rather, they are magnified, becoming blocks to your 
17   awareness of the Self that lies beyond your own mistakes, and past his seeming sins as well as 
18   yours.
19   W-pI.181.2. Perception has a focus. 2 It is this that gives consistency to what you see.
20    3 Change but this focus, and what you behold will change accordingly. 4 Your vision 
21   now will shift, to give support to the intent which has replaced the one you held before. 
22   5 Remove your focus on your brother's sins, and you experience the peace that comes from
23   faith in sinlessness. 6 This faith receives its only sure support from what you see in 
24   others past their sins. 7 For their mistakes, if focused on, are witnesses to sins in you. 8 
25   And you will not transcend their sight and see the sinlessness that lies beyond.
26   W-pI.181.3. Therefore, in practicing today, we first let all such little focuses give 
27   way to our great need to let our sinlessness become apparent. 2 We instruct our minds that
28   it is this we seek, and only this, for just a little while. 3 We do not care about our 
29   future goals. 4 And what we saw an instant previous has no concern for us within this 
30   interval of time wherein we practice changing our intent. 5 We seek for innocence and nothing 
31   else. 6 We seek for it with no concern but now.
32   W-pI.181.4. A major hazard to success has been involvement with your past and future 
33   goals. 2 You have been quite preoccupied with how extremely different the goals this course 
34   is advocating are from those you held before. 3 And you have also been dismayed by the 
35   depressing and restricting thought that, even if you should succeed, you will inevitably lose 
36   your way again.
37   W-pI.181.5. How could this matter? 2 For the past is gone; the future but imagined. 3 
38   These concerns are but defenses against present change of focus in perception. 4 Nothing 
39   more. 5 We lay these pointless limitations by a little while. 6 We do not look to past 
40   beliefs, and what we will believe will not intrude upon us now. 7 We enter in the time of 
41   practicing with one intent; to look upon the sinlessness within.
42   W-pI.181.6. We recognize that we have lost this goal if anger blocks our way in any 
43   form. 2 And if a brother's sins occur to us, our narrowed focus will restrict our sight, 
44   and turn our eyes upon our own mistakes, which we will magnify and call our "sins." 3 So, 
45   for a little while, without regard to past or future, should such blocks arise we will 
46   transcend them with instructions to our minds to change their focus, as we say: 
47   
48   4 It is not this that I would look upon. 
49   5 I trust my brothers, who are one with me.
50   
0582
 1   W-pI.181.7. And we will also use this thought to keep us safe throughout the day. 2 We 
 2   do not seek for long-range goals. 3 As each obstruction seems to block the vision of our 
 3   sinlessness, we seek but for surcease an instant from the misery the focus upon sin will bring, 
 4   and uncorrected will remain.
 5   W-pI.181.8. Nor do we ask for fantasies. 2 For what we seek to look upon is really 
 6   there. 3 And as our focus goes beyond mistakes, we will behold a wholly sinless world. 4 
 7   When seeing this is all we want to see, when this is all we seek for in the name of true 
 8   perception, are the eyes of Christ inevitably ours. 5 And the Love He feels for us becomes our 
 9   own as well. 6 This will become the only thing we see reflected in the world and in 
10   ourselves.
11   W-pI.181.9. The world which once proclaimed our sins becomes the proof that we are 
12   sinless. 2 And our love for everyone we look upon attests to our remembrance of the holy Self 
13   which knows no sin, and never could conceive of anything without Its sinlessness. 3 We seek 
14   for this remembrance as we turn our minds to practicing today. 4 We look neither ahead nor
15   backwards. 5 We look straight into the present. 6 And we give our trust to the 
16   experience we ask for now. 7 Our sinlessness is but the Will of God. 8 This instant is our 
17   willing one with His.
