14   LESSON 184.
15   
16   The Name of God is my inheritance.
17   W-pI.184.1. You live by symbols. 2 You have made up names for everything you see. 3 
18   Each one becomes a separate entity, identified by its own name. 4 By this you carve it out 
19   of unity. 5 By this you designate its special attributes, and set it off from other 
20   things by emphasizing space surrounding it. 6 This space you lay between all things to which 
21   you give a different name; all happenings in terms of place and time; all bodies which are
22   greeted by a name.
23   W-pI.184.2. This space you see as setting off all things from one another is the means 
24   by which the world's perception is achieved. 2 You see something where nothing is, and 
25   see as well nothing where there is unity; a space between all things, between all things 
26   and you. 3 Thus do you think that you have given life in separation. 4 By this split you 
27   think you are established as a unity which functions with an independent will.
28   W-pI.184.3. What are these names by which the world becomes a series of discrete events,
29    of things ununified, of bodies kept apart and holding bits of mind as separate 
30   awarenesses? 2 You gave these names to them, establishing perception as you wished to have 
31   perception be. 3 The nameless things were given names, and thus reality was given them as well. 4
32   For what is named is given meaning and will then be seen as meaningful; a cause of true
33   effect, with consequence inherent in itself.
34   W-pI.184.4. This is the way reality is made by partial vision, purposefully set against
35   the given truth. 2 Its enemy is wholeness. 3 It conceives of little things and looks 
36   upon them. 4 And a lack of space, a sense of unity or vision that sees differently, become 
37   the threats which it must overcome, conflict with and deny.
38   W-pI.184.5. Yet does this other vision still remain a natural direction for the mind to
39   channel its perception. 2 It is hard to teach the mind a thousand alien names, and 
40   thousands more. 3 Yet you believe this is what learning means; its one essential goal by which 
41   communication is achieved, and concepts can be meaningfully shared.
42   W-pI.184.6. This is the sum of the inheritance the world bestows. 2 And everyone who 
43   learns to think that it is so accepts the signs and symbols that assert the world is real. 3 
44   It is for this they stand. 4 They leave no doubt that what is named is there. 5 It can be
45   seen, as is anticipated. 6 What denies that it is true is but illusion, for it is the 
46   ultimate reality. 7 To question it is madness; to accept its presence is the proof of sanity.
47   W-pI.184.7. Such is the teaching of the world. 2 It is a phase of learning everyone who
48   comes must go through. 3 But the sooner he perceives on what it rests, how questionable
49   are its premises, how doubtful its results, the sooner does he question its effects. 4 
50   Learning that stops with what the world would teach stops short of meaning. 5 In its proper 
0586
 1   place, it serves but as a starting point from which another kind of learning can begin, a 
 2   new perception can be gained, and all the arbitrary names the world bestows can be 
 3   withdrawn as they are raised to doubt.
 4   W-pI.184.8. Think not you made the world. 2 Illusions, yes! 3 But what is true in earth
 5   and Heaven is beyond your naming. 4 When you call upon a brother, it is to his body 
 6   that you make appeal. 5 His true Identity is hidden from you by what you believe he really 
 7   is. 6 His body makes response to what you call him, for his mind consents to take the 
 8   name you give him as his own. 7 And thus his unity is twice denied, for you perceive him 
 9   separate from you, and he accepts this separate name as his.
10   W-pI.184.9. It would indeed be strange if you were asked to go beyond all symbols of 
11   the world, forgetting them forever; yet were asked to take a teaching function. 2 You have
12   need to use the symbols of the world a while. 3 But be you not deceived by them as well.
13    4 They do not stand for anything at all, and in your practicing it is this thought 
14   that will release you from them. 5 They become but means by which you can communicate in 
15   ways the world can understand, but which you recognize is not the unity where true 
16   communication can be found.
17   W-pI.184.10. Thus what you need are intervals each day in which the learning of the 
18   world becomes a transitory phase; a prison house from which you go into the sunlight and 
19   forget the darkness. 2 Here you understand the Word, the Name which God has given you; the 
20   one Identity which all things share; the one acknowledgment of what is true. 3 And then 
21   step back to darkness, not because you think it real, but only to proclaim its unreality in
22   terms which still have meaning in the world that darkness rules.
23   W-pI.184.11. Use all the little names and symbols which delineate the world of darkness.
24    2 Yet accept them not as your reality. 3 The Holy Spirit uses all of them, but He does
25   not forget creation has one Name, one meaning, and a single Source which unifies all 
26   things within Itself. 4 Use all the names the world bestows on them but for convenience, yet 
27   do not forget they share the Name of God along with you.
28   W-pI.184.12. God has no name. 2 And yet His Name becomes the final lesson that all 
29   things are one, and at this lesson does all learning end. 3 All names are unified; all space 
30   is filled with truth's reflection. 4 Every gap is closed, and separation healed. 5 The 
31   Name of God is the inheritance He gave to those who chose the teaching of the world to take
32   the place of Heaven. 6 In our practicing, our purpose is to let our minds accept what 
33   God has given as the answer to the pitiful inheritance you made as fitting tribute to the 
34   Son He loves.
35   W-pI.184.13. No one can fail who seeks the meaning of the Name of God. 2 Experience 
36   must come to supplement the Word. 3 But first you must accept the Name for all reality, and
37   realize the many names you gave its aspects have distorted what you see, but have not 
38   interfered with truth at all. 4 One Name we bring into our practicing. 5 One Name we use to unify
39   our sight.
40   W-pI.184.14. And though we use a different name for each awareness of an aspect of 
41   God's Son, we understand that they have but one Name, which He has given them. 2 It is this 
42   Name we use in practicing. 3 And through Its use, all foolish separations disappear which 
43   kept us blind. 4 And we are given strength to see beyond them. 5 Now our sight is blessed 
44   with blessings we can give as we receive.
45   
46   W-pI.184.15.  Father, our Name is Yours. 2 In It we are united with all living things, 
47   and You Who are their one Creator. 3 What we made and call by many different names is but 
48   a shadow we have tried to cast across Your Own reality. 4 And we are glad and thankful 
49   we were wrong. 5 All our mistakes we give to You, that we may be absolved from all 
50   effects our errors seemed to have. 6 And we accept the truth You give, in place of every one 
0587
 1   of them. 7 Your Name is our salvation and escape from what we made. 8 Your Name unites us
 2   in the oneness which is our inheritance and peace. 9 Amen.
 3   
 4   
 5   
 6   LESSON 185.
 7   
 8   I want the peace of God.
 9   W-pI.185.1. To say these words is nothing. 2 But to mean these words is everything. 3 
10   If you could but mean them for just an instant, there would be no further sorrow possible
11   for you in any form; in any place or time. 4 Heaven would be completely given back to 
12   full awareness, memory of God entirely restored, the resurrection of all creation fully 
13   recognized.
14   W-pI.185.2. No one can mean these words and not be healed. 2 He cannot play with dreams,
15    nor think he is himself a dream. 3 He cannot make a hell and think it real. 4 He wants
16   the peace of God, and it is given him. 5 For that is all he wants, and that is all he 
17   will receive. 6 Many have said these words. 7 But few indeed have meant them. 8 You have 
18   but to look upon the world you see around you to be sure how very few they are. 9 The 
19   world would be completely changed, should any two agree these words express the only thing 
20   they want.
21   W-pI.185.3. Two minds with one intent become so strong that what they will becomes the 
22   Will of God. 2 For minds can only join in truth. 3 In dreams, no two can share the same 
23   intent. 4 To each, the hero of the dream is different; the outcome wanted not the same for 
24   both. 5 Loser and gainer merely shift about in changing patterns, as the ratio of gain to 
25   loss and loss to gain takes on a different aspect or another form.
26   W-pI.185.4. Yet compromise alone a dream can bring. 2 Sometimes it takes the form of 
27   union, but only the form. 3 The meaning must escape the dream, for compromising is the goal 
28   of dreaming. 4 Minds cannot unite in dreams. 5 They merely bargain. 6 And what bargain 
29   can give them the peace of God? 7 Illusions come to take His place. 8 And what He means is
30   lost to sleeping minds intent on compromise, each to his gain and to another's loss.
31   W-pI.185.5. To mean you want the peace of God is to renounce all dreams. 2 For no one 
32   means these words who wants illusions, and who therefore seeks the means which bring 
33   illusions. 3 He has looked on them, and found them wanting. 4 Now he seeks to go beyond them, 
34   recognizing that another dream would offer nothing more than all the others. 5 Dreams are one to 
35   him. 6 And he has learned their only difference is one of form, for one will bring the 
36   same despair and misery as do the rest.
37   W-pI.185.6. The mind which means that all it wants is peace must join with other minds,
38   for that is how peace is obtained. 2 And when the wish for peace is genuine, the means 
39   for finding it is given, in a form each mind that seeks for it in honesty can understand. 
40   3 Whatever form the lesson takes is planned for him in such a way that he can not 
41   mistake it, if his asking is sincere. 4 But if he asks without sincerity, there is no form in 
42   which the lesson will meet with acceptance and be truly learned.
43   W-pI.185.7. Let us today devote our practicing to recognizing that we really mean the 
44   words we say. 2 We want the peace of God. 3 This is no idle wish. 4 These words do not 
45   request another dream be given us. 5 They do not ask for compromise, nor try to make another 
46   bargain in the hope that there may yet be one that can succeed where all the rest have failed.
47   6 To mean these words acknowledges illusions are in vain, requesting the eternal in the
48   place of shifting dreams which seem to change in what they offer, but are one in 
49   nothingness.
50   W-pI.185.8. Today devote your practice periods to careful searching of your mind, to 
0588
 1   find the dreams you cherish still. 2 What do you ask for in your heart? 3 Forget the words 
 2   you use in making your requests. 4 Consider but what you believe will comfort you, and 
 3   bring you happiness. 5 But be you not dismayed by lingering illusions, for their form is not
 4   what matters now. 6 Let not some dreams be more acceptable, reserving shame and secrecy
 5   for others. 7 They are one. 8 And being one, one question should be asked of all of 
 6   them, "Is this what I would have, in place of Heaven and the peace of God?"
 7   W-pI.185.9. This is the choice you make. 2 Be not deceived that it is otherwise. 3 No 
 8   compromise is possible in this. 4 You choose God's peace, or you have asked for dreams. 5 And 
 9   dreams will come as you requested them. 6 Yet will God's peace come just as certainly, and to
10   remain with you forever. 7 It will not be gone with every twist and turning of the road,
11    to reappear, unrecognized, in forms which shift and change with every step you take.
12   W-pI.185.10. You want the peace of God. 2 And so do all who seem to seek for dreams. 3 
13   For them as well as for yourself, you ask but this when you make this request with deep 
14   sincerity. 4 For thus you reach to what they really want, and join your own intent with what 
15   they seek above all things, perhaps unknown to them, but sure to you. 5 You have been weak 
16   at times, uncertain in your purpose, and unsure of what you wanted, where to look for it,
17   and where to turn for help in the attempt. 6 Help has been given you. 7 And would you 
18   not avail yourself of it by sharing it?
19   W-pI.185.11. No one who truly seeks the peace of God can fail to find it. 2 For he 
20   merely asks that he deceive himself no longer by denying to himself what is God's Will. 3 Who
21   can remain unsatisfied who asks for what he has already? 4 Who could be unanswered who 
22   requests an answer which is his to give? 5 The peace of God is yours.
23   W-pI.185.12. For you was peace created, given you by its Creator, and established as 
24   His Own eternal gift. 2 How can you fail, when you but ask for what He wills for you? 3 
25   And how could your request be limited to you alone? 4 No gift of God can be unshared. 5 It
26   is this attribute that sets the gifts of God apart from every dream that ever seemed to
27   take the place of truth.
28   W-pI.185.13. No one can lose and everyone must gain whenever any gift of God has been 
29   requested and received by anyone. 2 God gives but to unite. 3 To take away is meaningless to Him.
30    4 And when it is as meaningless to you, you can be sure you share one Will with Him, 
31   and He with you. 5 And you will also know you share one Will with all your brothers, whose
32   intent is yours.
33   W-pI.185.14. It is this one intent we seek today, uniting our desires with the need of 
34   every heart, the call of every mind, the hope that lies beyond despair, the love attack 
35   would hide, the brotherhood that hate has sought to sever, but which still remains as God 
36   created it. 2 With Help like this beside us, can we fail today as we request the peace of God 
37   be given us?
