23   LESSON 190.
24   
25   I choose the joy of God instead of pain.
26   W-pI.190.1. Pain is a wrong perspective. 2 When it is experienced in any form, it is a 
27   proof of self-deception. 3 It is not a fact at all. 4 There is no form it takes that will 
28   not disappear if seen aright. 5 For pain proclaims God cruel. 6 How could it be real in 
29   any form? 7 It witnesses to God the Father's hatred of His Son, the sinfulness He sees in 
30   him, and His insane desire for revenge and death.
31   W-pI.190.2. Can such projections be attested to? 2 Can they be anything but wholly 
32   false? 3 Pain is but witness to the Son's mistakes in what he thinks he is. 4 It is a dream 
33   of fierce retaliation for a crime that could not be committed; for attack on what is 
34   wholly unassailable. 5 It is a nightmare of abandonment by an Eternal Love, which could not 
35   leave the Son whom It created out of love.
36   W-pI.190.3. Pain is a sign illusions reign in place of truth. 2 It demonstrates God is 
37   denied, confused with fear, perceived as mad, and seen as traitor to Himself. 3 If God is 
38   real, there is no pain. 4 If pain is real, there is no God. 5 For vengeance is not part of 
39   love. 6 And fear, denying love and using pain to prove that God is dead, has shown that 
40   death is victor over life. 7 The body is the Son of God, corruptible in death, as mortal as 
41   the Father he has slain.
42   W-pI.190.4. Peace to such foolishness! 2 The time has come to laugh at such insane 
43   ideas. 3 There is no need to think of them as savage crimes, or secret sins with weighty 
44   consequence. 4 Who but a madman could conceive of them as cause of anything? 5 Their witness, pain,
45    is mad as they, and no more to be feared than the insane illusions which it shields, 
46   and tries to demonstrate must still be true.
47   W-pI.190.5. It is your thoughts alone that cause you pain. 2 Nothing external to your 
48   mind can hurt or injure you in any way. 3 There is no cause beyond yourself that can reach 
49   down and bring oppression. 4 No one but yourself affects you. 5 There is nothing in the 
50   world that has the power to make you ill or sad, or weak or frail. 6 But it is you who have 
0595
 1   the power to dominate all things you see by merely recognizing what you are. 7 As you 
 2   perceive the harmlessness in them, they will accept your holy will as theirs. 8 And what was 
 3   seen as fearful now becomes a source of innocence and holiness.
 4   W-pI.190.6. My holy brother, think of this awhile: The world you see does nothing. 2 It
 5   has no effects at all. 3 It merely represents your thoughts. 4 And it will change 
 6   entirely as you elect to change your mind, and choose the joy of God as what you really want. 5
 7   Your Self is radiant in this holy joy, unchanged, unchanging and unchangeable, forever 
 8   and forever. 6 And would you deny a little corner of your mind its own inheritance, and 
 9   keep it as a hospital for pain; a sickly place where living things must come at last to die?
10   
11   W-pI.190.7. The world may seem to cause you pain. 2 And yet the world, as causeless, 
12   has no power to cause. 3 As an effect, it cannot make effects. 4 As an illusion, it is 
13   what you wish. 5 Your idle wishes represent its pains. 6 Your strange desires bring it evil
14   dreams. 7 Your thoughts of death envelop it in fear, while in your kind forgiveness 
15   does it live.
16   W-pI.190.8. Pain is the thought of evil taking form, and working havoc in your holy 
17   mind. 2 Pain is the ransom you have gladly paid not to be free. 3 In pain is God denied the
18   Son He loves. 4 In pain does fear appear to triumph over love, and time replace 
19   eternity and Heaven. 5 And the world becomes a cruel and a bitter place, where sorrow rules and
20   little joys give way before the onslaught of the savage pain that waits to end all joy 
21   in misery.
22   W-pI.190.9. Lay down your arms, and come without defense into the quiet place where 
23   Heaven's peace holds all things still at last. 2 Lay down all thoughts of danger and of fear. 3
24   Let no attack enter with you. 4 Lay down the cruel sword of judgment that you hold 
25   against your throat, and put aside the withering assaults with which you seek to hide your 
26   holiness.
27   W-pI.190.10. Here will you understand there is no pain. 2 Here does the joy of God 
28   belong to you. 3 This is the day when it is given you to realize the lesson that contains all
29   of salvation's power. 4 It is this: Pain is illusion; joy, reality. 5 Pain is but sleep;
30    joy is awakening. 6 Pain is deception; joy alone is truth.
31   W-pI.190.11. And so again we make the only choice that ever can be made; we choose 
32   between illusions and the truth, or pain and joy, or hell and Heaven. 2 Let our gratitude unto
33   our Teacher fill our hearts, as we are free to choose our joy instead of pain, our 
34   holiness in place of sin, the peace of God instead of conflict, and the light of Heaven for the
35   darkness of the world.
36   
37   
38   
39   LESSON 191.
40   
41   I am the holy Son of God Himself.
42   W-pI.191.1. Here is your declaration of release from bondage of the world. 2 And here 
43   as well is all the world released. 3 You do not see what you have done by giving to the 
44   world the role of jailer to the Son of God. 4 What could it be but vicious and afraid, 
45   fearful of shadows, punitive and wild, lacking all reason, blind, insane with hate?
46   W-pI.191.2. What have you done that this should be your world? 2 What have you done 
47   that this is what you see? 3 Deny your own Identity, and this is what remains. 4 You look 
48   on chaos and proclaim it is yourself. 5 There is no sight that fails to witness this to 
49   you. 6 There is no sound that does not speak of frailty within you and without; no breath 
50   you draw that does not seem to bring you nearer death; no hope you hold but will dissolve 
0596
 1   in tears.
 2   W-pI.191.3. Deny your own Identity, and you will not escape the madness which induced 
 3   this weird, unnatural and ghostly thought that mocks creation and that laughs at God. 2 
 4   Deny your own Identity, and you assail the universe alone, without a friend, a tiny 
 5   particle of dust against the legions of your enemies. 3 Deny your own Identity, and look on 
 6   evil, sin and death, and watch despair snatch from your fingers every scrap of hope, 
 7   leaving you nothing but the wish to die.
 8   W-pI.191.4. Yet what is it except a game you play in which Identity can be denied? 2 
 9   You are as God created you. 3 All else but this one thing is folly to believe. 4 In this 
10   one thought is everyone set free. 5 In this one truth are all illusions gone. 6 In this 
11   one fact is sinlessness proclaimed to be forever part of everything, the central core of 
12   its existence and its guarantee of immortality.
13   W-pI.191.5. But let today's idea find a place among your thoughts and you have risen 
14   far above the world, and all the worldly thoughts that hold it prisoner. 2 And from this 
15   place of safety and escape you will return and set it free. 3 For he who can accept his true
16   Identity is truly saved. 4 And his salvation is the gift he gives to everyone, in 
17   gratitude to Him Who pointed out the way to happiness that changed his whole perspective of the 
18   world.
19   W-pI.191.6. One holy thought like this and you are free: You are the holy Son of God 
20   Himself. 2 And with this holy thought you learn as well that you have freed the world. 3 You 
21   have no need to use it cruelly, and then perceive this savage need in it. 4 You set it free
22   of your imprisonment. 5 You will not see a devastating image of yourself walking the 
23   world in terror, with the world twisting in agony because your fears have laid the mark of 
24   death upon its heart.
25   W-pI.191.7. Be glad today how very easily is hell undone. 2 You need but tell yourself:
26   
27   
28   3 I am the holy Son of God Himself. 4 I cannot suffer, cannot be in pain; I cannot 
29   suffer loss, nor fail to do all that salvation asks. 
30   
31   5 And in that thought is everything you look on wholly changed.
32   W-pI.191.8. A miracle has lighted up all dark and ancient caverns, where the rites of 
33   death echoed since time began. 2 For time has lost its hold upon the world. 3 The Son of God
34   has come in glory to redeem the lost, to save the helpless, and to give the world the 
35   gift of his forgiveness. 4 Who could see the world as dark and sinful, when God's Son has 
36   come again at last to set it free?
37   W-pI.191.9. You who perceive yourself as weak and frail, with futile hopes and 
38   devastated dreams, born but to die, to weep and suffer pain, hear this: All power is given unto 
39   you in earth and Heaven. 2 There is nothing that you cannot do. 3 You play the game of 
40   death, of being helpless, pitifully tied to dissolution in a world which shows no mercy to 
41   you. 4 Yet when you accord it mercy, will its mercy shine on you.
42   W-pI.191.10. Then let the Son of God awaken from his sleep, and opening his holy eyes, 
43   return again to bless the world he made. 2 In error it began, but it will end in the 
44   reflection of his holiness. 3 And he will sleep no more and dream of death. 4 Then join with me 
45   today. 5 Your glory is the light that saves the world. 6 Do not withhold salvation longer. 7
46   Look about the world, and see the suffering there. 8 Is not your heart willing to bring
47   your weary brothers rest?
48   W-pI.191.11. They must await your own release. 2 They stay in chains till you are free.
49   3 They cannot see the mercy of the world until you find it in yourself. 4 They suffer 
50   pain until you have denied its hold on you. 5 They die till you accept your own eternal 
0597
 1   life. 6 You are the holy Son of God Himself. 7 Remember this, and all the world is free. 8 
 2   Remember this, and earth and Heaven are one.
 3   
 4   
 5   
 6   LESSON 192.
 7   
 8   I have a function God would have me fill.
 9   W-pI.192.1. It is your Father's holy Will that you complete Himself, and that your Self
10   shall be His sacred Son, forever pure as He, of love created and in love preserved, 
11   extending love, creating in its name, forever one with God and with your Self. 2 Yet what can 
12   such a function mean within a world of envy, hatred and attack?
13   W-pI.192.2. Therefore, you have a function in the world in its own terms. 2 For who can
14   understand a language far beyond his simple grasp? 3 Forgiveness represents your 
15   function here. 4 It is not God's creation, for it is the means by which untruth can be undone. 
16   5 And who would pardon Heaven? 6 Yet on earth, you need the means to let illusions go. 7
17   Creation merely waits for your return to be acknowledged, not to be complete.
18   W-pI.192.3. Creation cannot even be conceived of in the world. 2 It has no meaning here.
19    3 Forgiveness is the closest it can come to earth. 4 For being Heaven-born, it has no 
20   form at all. 5 Yet God created One Who has the power to translate in form the wholly 
21   formless. 6 What He makes are dreams, but of a kind so close to waking that the light of day 
22   already shines in them, and eyes already opening behold the joyful sights their offerings 
23   contain.
24   W-pI.192.4. Forgiveness gently looks upon all things unknown in Heaven, sees them 
25   disappear, and leaves the world a clean and unmarked slate on which the Word of God can now 
26   replace the senseless symbols written there before. 2 Forgiveness is the means by which the 
27   fear of death is overcome, because it holds no fierce attraction now and guilt is gone. 3 
28   Forgiveness lets the body be perceived as what it is; a simple teaching aid, to be laid by when 
29   learning is complete, but hardly changing him who learns at all.
30   W-pI.192.5. The mind without the body cannot make mistakes. 2 It cannot think that it 
31   will die, nor be the prey of merciless attack. 3 Anger becomes impossible, and where is 
32   terror then? 4 What fears could still assail those who have lost the source of all attack, 
33   the core of anguish and the seat of fear? 5 Only forgiveness can relieve the mind of 
34   thinking that the body is its home. 6 Only forgiveness can restore the peace that God intended 
35   for His holy Son. 7 Only forgiveness can persuade the Son to look again upon his holiness.
36   W-pI.192.6. With anger gone, you will indeed perceive that, for Christ's vision and the
37   gift of sight, no sacrifice was asked, and only pain was lifted from a sick and 
38   tortured mind. 2 Is this unwelcome? 3 Is it to be feared? 4 Or is it to be hoped for, met with 
39   thanks and joyously accepted? 5 We are one, and therefore give up nothing. 6 But we have 
40   indeed been given everything by God.
41   W-pI.192.7. Yet do we need forgiveness to perceive that this is so. 2 Without its 
42   kindly light we grope in darkness, using reason but to justify our rage and our attack. 3 Our
43   understanding is so limited that what we think we understand is but confusion born of 
44   error. 4 We are lost in mists of shifting dreams and fearful thoughts, our eyes shut tight 
45   against the light; our minds engaged in worshipping what is not there.
46   W-pI.192.8. Who can be born again in Christ but him who has forgiven everyone he sees 
47   or thinks of or imagines? 2 Who could be set free while he imprisons anyone? 3 A jailer 
48   is not free, for he is bound together with his prisoner. 4 He must be sure that he does 
49   not escape, and so he spends his time in keeping watch on him. 5 The bars that limit him 
50   become the world in which his jailer lives, along with him. 6 And it is on his freedom that 
0598
 1   the way to liberty depends for both of them.
 2   W-pI.192.9. Therefore, hold no one prisoner. 2 Release instead of bind, for thus are 
 3   you made free. 3 The way is simple. 4 Every time you feel a stab of anger, realize you 
 4   hold a sword above your head. 5 And it will fall or be averted as you choose to be 
 5   condemned or free. 6 Thus does each one who seems to tempt you to be angry represent your savior
 6   from the prison house of death. 7 And so you owe him thanks instead of pain.
 7   W-pI.192.10. Be merciful today. 2 The Son of God deserves your mercy. 3 It is he who 
 8   asks that you accept the way to freedom now. 4 Deny him not. 5 His Father's Love for him 
 9   belongs to you. 6 Your function here on earth is only to forgive him, that you may accept him 
10   back as your Identity. 7 He is as God created him. 8 And you are what he is. 9 Forgive him 
11   now his sins, and you will see that you are one with him.
12   
13   
14   
15   LESSON 193.
16   
17   All things are lessons God would have me learn.
18   W-pI.193.1. God does not know of learning. 2 Yet His Will extends to what He does not 
19   understand, in that He wills the happiness His Son inherited of Him be undisturbed; eternal and 
20   forever gaining scope, eternally expanding in the joy of full creation, and eternally open and
21   wholly limitless in Him. 3 That is His Will. 4 And thus His Will provides the means to 
22   guarantee that it is done.
23   W-pI.193.2. God sees no contradictions. 2 Yet His Son believes he sees them. 3 Thus he 
24   has a need for One Who can correct his erring sight, and give him vision that will lead 
25   him back to where perception ceases. 4 God does not perceive at all. 5 Yet it is He Who 
26   gives the means by which perception is made true and beautiful enough to let the light of 
27   Heaven shine upon it. 6 It is He Who answers what His Son would contradict, and keeps his 
28   sinlessness forever safe.
29   W-pI.193.3. These are the lessons God would have you learn. 2 His Will reflects them 
30   all, and they reflect His loving kindness to the Son He loves. 3 Each lesson has a central
31   thought, the same in all of them. 4 The form alone is changed, with different 
32   circumstances and events; with different characters and different themes, apparent but not real. 5 
33   They are the same in fundamental content. 6 It is this: 
34   
35   7 Forgive, and you will see this differently.
36   
37   W-pI.193.4. Certain it is that all distress does not appear to be but unforgiveness. 2 
38   Yet that is the content underneath the form. 3 It is this sameness which makes learning 
39   sure, because the lesson is so simple that it cannot be rejected in the end. 4 No one can 
40   hide forever from a truth so very obvious that it appears in countless forms, and yet is 
41   recognized as easily in all of them, if one but wants to see the simple lesson there.
42   
43   W-pI.193.5. <Forgive, and you will see this differently.>
44   
45   2 These are the words the Holy Spirit speaks in all your tribulations, all your pain, 
46   all suffering regardless of its form. 3 These are the words with which temptation ends, 
47   and guilt, abandoned, is revered no more. 4 These are the words which end the dream of sin,
48    and rid the mind of fear. 5 These are the words by which salvation comes to all the 
49   world.
50   W-pI.193.6. Shall we not learn to say these words when we are tempted to believe that 
0599
 1   pain is real, and death becomes our choice instead of life? 2 Shall we not learn to say 
 2   these words when we have understood their power to release all minds from bondage? 3 These 
 3   are words which give you power over all events that seem to have been given power over you.
 4    4 You see them rightly when you hold these words in full awareness, and do not forget 
 5   these words apply to everything you see or any brother looks upon amiss.
 6   W-pI.193.7. How can you tell when you are seeing wrong, or someone else is failing to 
 7   perceive the lesson he should learn? 2 Does pain seem real in the perception? 3 If it does, be 
 8   sure the lesson is not learned. 4 And there remains an unforgiveness hiding in the mind 
 9   that sees the pain through eyes the mind directs.
10   W-pI.193.8. God would not have you suffer thus. 2 He would help you forgive yourself. 3
11   His Son does not remember who he is. 4 And God would have him not forget His Love, and 
12   all the gifts His Love brings with it. 5 Would you now renounce your own salvation? 6 
13   Would you fail to learn the simple lessons Heaven's Teacher sets before you, that all pain 
14   may disappear and God may be remembered by His Son?
15   W-pI.193.9. All things are lessons God would have you learn. 2 He would not leave an 
16   unforgiving thought without correction, nor one thorn or nail to hurt His holy Son in any way. 3 
17   He would ensure his holy rest remain untroubled and serene, without a care, in an eternal
18   home which cares for him. 4 And He would have all tears be wiped away, with none 
19   remaining yet unshed, and none but waiting their appointed time to fall. 5 For God has willed 
20   that laughter should replace each one, and that His Son be free again.
21   W-pI.193.10. We will attempt today to overcome a thousand seeming obstacles to peace in
22   just one day. 2 Let mercy come to you more quickly. 3 Do not try to hold it off another
23   day, another minute or another instant. 4 Time was made for this. 5 Use it today for 
24   what its purpose is. 6 Morning and night, devote what time you can to serve its proper aim,
25   and do not let the time be less than meets your deepest need.
26   W-pI.193.11. Give all you can, and give a little more. 2 For now we would arise in 
27   haste and go unto our Father's house. 3 We have been gone too long, and we would linger here
28   no more. 4 And as we practice, let us think about all things we saved to settle by 
29   ourselves, and kept apart from healing. 5 Let us give them all to Him Who knows the way to look 
30   upon them so that they will disappear. 6 Truth is His message; truth His teaching is. 7 His
31   are the lessons God would have us learn.
32   W-pI.193.12. Each hour, spend a little time today, and in the days to come, in 
33   practicing the lesson in forgiveness in the form established for the day. 2 And try to give it 
34   application to the happenings the hour brought, so that the next one is free of the one before. 3 
35   The chains of time are easily unloosened in this way. 4 Let no one hour cast its shadow on
36   the one that follows, and when that one goes, let everything that happened in its 
37   course go with it. 5 Thus will you remain unbound, in peace eternal in the world of time.
38   W-pI.193.13. This is the lesson God would have you learn: There is a way to look on 
39   everything that lets it be to you another step to Him, and to salvation of the world. 2 To all 
40   that speaks of terror, answer thus: 
41   
42   3 I will forgive, and this will disappear. 
43   
44   4 To every apprehension, every care and every form of suffering, repeat these selfsame 
45   words. 5 And then you hold the key that opens Heaven's gate, and brings the Love of God the 
46   Father down to earth at last, to raise it up to Heaven. 6 God will take this final step 
47   Himself. 7 Do not deny the little steps He asks you take to Him.
