45   
46   Let me not see myself as limited.
47   W-pII.250.1. Let me behold the Son of God today, and witness to his glory. 2 Let me not
48   try to obscure the holy light in him, and see his strength diminished and reduced to 
49   frailty; nor perceive the lacks in him with which I would attack his sovereignty.
50   
0628
 1   W-pII.250.2.  <He is Your Son, my Father. 2 And today I would behold his gentleness 
 2   instead of my illusions. 3 He is what I am, and as I see him so I see myself. 4 Today I would 
 3   see truly, that this day I may at last identify with him.>
 4   
 5   
 6   4. What Is Sin?
 7   W-pII.4.1. Sin is insanity. 2 It is the means by which the mind is driven mad, and 
 8   seeks to let illusions take the place of truth. 3 And being mad, it sees illusions where the
 9   truth should be, and where it really is. 4 Sin gave the body eyes, for what is there 
10   the sinless would behold? 5 What need have they of sights or sounds or touch? 6 What would
11   they hear or reach to grasp? 7 What would they sense at all? 8 To sense is not to know.
12   9 And truth can be but filled with knowledge, and with nothing else.
13   W-pII.4.2. The body is the instrument the mind made in its efforts to deceive itself. 2
14   Its purpose is to strive. 3 Yet can the goal of striving change. 4 And now the body 
15   serves a different aim for striving. 5 What it seeks for now is chosen by the aim the mind 
16   has taken as replacement for the goal of self-deception. 6 Truth can be its aim as well as
17   lies. 7 The senses then will seek instead for witnesses to what is true.
18   W-pII.4.3. Sin is the home of all illusions, which but stand for things imagined, 
19   issuing from thoughts that are untrue. 2 They are the "proof" that what has no reality is real.
20    3 Sin "proves" God's Son is evil; timelessness must have an end; eternal life must die.
21    4 And God Himself has lost the Son He loves, with but corruption to complete Himself, 
22   His Will forever overcome by death, love slain by hate, and peace to be no more.
23   W-pII.4.4. A madman's dreams are frightening, and sin appears indeed to terrify. 2 And 
24   yet what sin perceives is but a childish game. 3 The Son of God may play he has become a 
25   body, prey to evil and to guilt, with but a little life that ends in death. 4 But all the 
26   while his Father shines on him, and loves him with an everlasting Love which his pretenses 
27   cannot change at all.
28   W-pII.4.5. How long, O Son of God, will you maintain the game of sin? 2 Shall we not 
29   put away these sharp-edged children's toys? 3 How soon will you be ready to come home? 4 
30   Perhaps today? 5 There is no sin. 6 Creation is unchanged. 7 Would you still hold return to 
31   Heaven back? 8 How long, O holy Son of God, how long?
32   
33   
34   
35   LESSON 251.
36   
37   I am in need of nothing but the truth.
38   W-pII.251.1. I sought for many things, and found despair. 2 Now do I seek but one, for 
39   in that one is all I need, and only what I need. 3 All that I sought before I needed not,
40   and did not even want. 4 My only need I did not recognize. 5 But now I see that I need 
41   only truth. 6 In that all needs are satisfied, all cravings end, all hopes are finally 
42   fulfilled and dreams are gone. 7 Now have I everything that I could need. 8 Now have I 
43   everything that I could want. 9 And now at last I find myself at peace.
44   
45   W-pII.251.2.  <And for that peace, our Father, we give thanks. 2 What we denied 
46   ourselves You have restored, and only that is what we really want.>
