 5   
 6   8. What Is the Real World?
 7   W-pII.8.1. The real world is a symbol, like the rest of what perception offers. 2 Yet 
 8   it stands for what is opposite to what you made. 3 Your world is seen through eyes of 
 9   fear, and brings the witnesses of terror to your mind. 4 The real world cannot be perceived
10   except through eyes forgiveness blesses, so they see a world where terror is impossible,
11    and witnesses to fear can not be found.
12   W-pII.8.2. The real world holds a counterpart for each unhappy thought reflected in 
13   your world; a sure correction for the sights of fear and sounds of battle which your world 
14   contains. 2 The real world shows a world seen differently, through quiet eyes and with a mind 
15   at peace. 3 Nothing but rest is there. 4 There are no cries of pain and sorrow heard, for
16   nothing there remains outside forgiveness. 5 And the sights are gentle. 6 Only happy 
17   sights and sounds can reach the mind that has forgiven itself.
18   W-pII.8.3. What need has such a mind for thoughts of death, attack and murder? 2 What 
19   can it perceive surrounding it but safety, love and joy? 3 What is there it would choose 
20   to be condemned, and what is there that it would judge against? 4 The world it sees 
21   arises from a mind at peace within itself. 5 No danger lurks in anything it sees, for it is 
22   kind, and only kindness does it look upon.
23   W-pII.8.4. The real world is the symbol that the dream of sin and guilt is over, and 
24   God's Son no longer sleeps. 2 His waking eyes perceive the sure reflection of his Father's 
25   Love; the certain promise that he is redeemed. 3 The real world signifies the end of time, 
26   for its perception makes time purposeless.
27   W-pII.8.5. The Holy Spirit has no need of time when it has served His purpose. 2 Now He
28   waits but that one instant more for God to take His final step, and time has 
29   disappeared, taking perception with it as it goes, and leaving but the truth to be itself. 3 That 
30   instant is our goal, for it contains the memory of God. 4 And as we look upon a world forgiven,
31    it is He Who calls to us and comes to take us home, reminding us of our Identity which
32   our forgiveness has restored to us.
33   
34   
35   
36   LESSON 291.
37   
38   This is a day of stillness and of peace.
39   W-pII.291.1. Christ's vision looks through me today. 2 His sight shows me all things 
40   forgiven and at peace, and offers this same vision to the world. 3 And I accept this vision in 
41   its name, both for myself and for the world as well. 4 What loveliness we look upon today!
42   5 What holiness we see surrounding us! 6 And it is given us to recognize it is a 
43   holiness in which we share; it is the Holiness of God Himself.
44   
45   W-pII.291.2.  <This day my mind is quiet, to receive the Thoughts You offer me. 2 And I
46   accept what comes from You, instead of from myself. 3 I do not know the way to You. 4 
47   But You are wholly certain. 5 Father, guide Your Son along the quiet path that leads to 
48   You. 6 Let my forgiveness be complete, and let the memory of You return to me.>
